21Ec 1:1 The words of the Preacher, the son of David, king in Jerusalem.
21Ec 1:2 Vanity of vanities, says the Preacher, vanity of vanities! All is vanity.
21Ec 1:3 What does man gain by all the toil at which he toils under the sun?
21Ec 1:4 A generation goes, and a generation comes, but the earth remains forever.
21Ec 1:5 The sun rises, and the sun goes down, and hastens to the place where it rises.
21Ec 1:6 The wind blows to the south and goes around to the north; around and around goes the wind, and on its circuits the wind returns.
21Ec 1:7 All streams run to the sea, but the sea is not full; to the place where the streams flow, there they flow again.
21Ec 1:8 All things are full of weariness; a man cannot utter it; the eye is not satisfied with seeing, nor the ear filled with hearing.
21Ec 1:9 What has been is what will be, and what has been done is what will be done, and there is nothing new under the sun.
21Ec 1:10 Is there a thing of which it is said, "See, this is new"? It has been already in the ages before us.
21Ec 1:11 There is no remembrance of former things, nor will there be any remembrance of later things yet to be among those who come after.
21Ec 1:12 I the Preacher have been king over Israel in Jerusalem.
21Ec 1:13 And I applied my heart to seek and to search out by wisdom all that is done under heaven. It is an unhappy business that God has given to the children of man to be busy with.
21Ec 1:14 I have seen everything that is done under the sun, and behold, all is vanity and a striving after wind.
21Ec 1:15 What is crooked cannot be made straight, and what is lacking cannot be counted.
21Ec 1:16 I said in my heart, "I have acquired great wisdom, surpassing all who were over Jerusalem before me, and my heart has had great experience of wisdom and knowledge."
21Ec 1:17 And I applied my heart to know wisdom and to know madness and folly. I perceived that this also is but a striving after wind.
21Ec 1:18 For in much wisdom is much vexation, and he who increases knowledge increases sorrow.
21Ec 2:1 I said in my heart, "Come now, I will test you with pleasure; enjoy yourself." But behold, this also was vanity.
21Ec 2:2 I said of laughter, "It is mad," and of pleasure, "What use is it?"
21Ec 2:3 I searched with my heart how to cheer my body with wine--my heart still guiding me with wisdom--and how to lay hold on folly, till I might see what was good for the children of man to do under heaven during the few days of their life.
21Ec 2:4 I made great works. I built houses and planted vineyards for myself.
21Ec 2:5 I made myself gardens and parks, and planted in them all kinds of fruit trees.
21Ec 2:6 I made myself pools from which to water the forest of growing trees.
21Ec 2:7 I bought male and female slaves, and had slaves who were born in my house. I had also great possessions of herds and flocks, more than any who had been before me in Jerusalem.
21Ec 2:8 I also gathered for myself silver and gold and the treasure of kings and provinces. I got singers, both men and women, and many concubines, the delight of the children of man.
21Ec 2:9 So I became great and surpassed all who were before me in Jerusalem. Also my wisdom remained with me.
21Ec 2:10 And whatever my eyes desired I did not keep from them. I kept my heart from no pleasure, for my heart found pleasure in all my toil, and this was my reward for all my toil.
21Ec 2:11 Then I considered all that my hands had done and the toil I had expended in doing it, and behold, all was vanity and a striving after wind, and there was nothing to be gained under the sun.
21Ec 2:12 So I turned to consider wisdom and madness and folly. For what can the man do who comes after the king? Only what has already been done.
21Ec 2:13 Then I saw that there is more gain in wisdom than in folly, as there is more gain in light than in darkness.
21Ec 2:14 The wise person has his eyes in his head, but the fool walks in darkness. And yet I perceived that the same event happens to all of them.
21Ec 2:15 Then I said in my heart, "What happens to the fool will happen to me also. Why then have I been so very wise?" And I said in my heart that this also is vanity.
21Ec 2:16 For of the wise as of the fool there is no enduring remembrance, seeing that in the days to come all will have been long forgotten. How the wise dies just like the fool!
21Ec 2:17 So I hated life, because what is done under the sun was grievous to me, for all is vanity and a striving after wind.
21Ec 2:18 I hated all my toil in which I toil under the sun, seeing that I must leave it to the man who will come after me,
21Ec 2:19 and who knows whether he will be wise or a fool? Yet he will be master of all for which I toiled and used my wisdom under the sun. This also is vanity.
21Ec 2:20 So I turned about and gave my heart up to despair over all the toil of my labors under the sun,
21Ec 2:21 because sometimes a person who has toiled with wisdom and knowledge and skill must leave everything to be enjoyed by someone who did not toil for it. This also is vanity and a great evil.
21Ec 2:22 What has a man from all the toil and striving of heart with which he toils beneath the sun?
21Ec 2:23 For all his days are full of sorrow, and his work is a vexation. Even in the night his heart does not rest. This also is vanity.
21Ec 2:24 There is nothing better for a person than that he should eat and drink and find enjoyment in his toil. This also, I saw, is from the hand of God,
21Ec 2:25 for apart from him who can eat or who can have enjoyment?
21Ec 2:26 For to the one who pleases him God has given wisdom and knowledge and joy, but to the sinner he has given the business of gathering and collecting, only to give to one who pleases God. This also is vanity and a striving after wind.
21Ec 3:1 For everything there is a season, and a time for every matter under heaven:
21Ec 3:2 a time to be born, and a time to die; a time to plant, and a time to pluck up what is planted;
21Ec 3:3 a time to kill, and a time to heal; a time to break down, and a time to build up;
21Ec 3:4 a time to weep, and a time to laugh; a time to mourn, and a time to dance;
21Ec 3:5 a time to cast away stones, and a time to gather stones together; a time to embrace, and a time to refrain from embracing;
21Ec 3:6 a time to seek, and a time to lose; a time to keep, and a time to cast away;
21Ec 3:7 a time to tear, and a time to sew; a time to keep silence, and a time to speak;
21Ec 3:8 a time to love, and a time to hate; a time for war, and a time for peace.
21Ec 3:9 What gain has the worker from his toil?
21Ec 3:10 I have seen the business that God has given to the children of man to be busy with.
21Ec 3:11 He has made everything beautiful in its time. Also, he has put eternity into man's heart, yet so that he cannot find out what God has done from the beginning to the end.
21Ec 3:12 I perceived that there is nothing better for them than to be joyful and to do good as long as they live;
21Ec 3:13 also that everyone should eat and drink and take pleasure in all his toil--this is God's gift to man.
21Ec 3:14 I perceived that whatever God does endures forever; nothing can be added to it, nor anything taken from it. God has done it, so that people fear before him.
21Ec 3:15 That which is, already has been; that which is to be, already has been; and God seeks what has been driven away.
21Ec 3:16 Moreover, I saw under the sun that in the place of justice, even there was wickedness, and in the place of righteousness, even there was wickedness.
21Ec 3:17 I said in my heart, God will judge the righteous and the wicked, for there is a time for every matter and for every work.
21Ec 3:18 I said in my heart with regard to the children of man that God is testing them that they may see that they themselves are but beasts.
21Ec 3:19 For what happens to the children of man and what happens to the beasts is the same; as one dies, so dies the other. They all have the same breath, and man has no advantage over the beasts, for all is vanity.
21Ec 3:20 All go to one place. All are from the dust, and to dust all return.
21Ec 3:21 Who knows whether the spirit of man goes upward and the spirit of the beast goes down into the earth?
21Ec 3:22 So I saw that there is nothing better than that a man should rejoice in his work, for that is his lot. Who can bring him to see what will be after him?
21Ec 4:1 Again I saw all the oppressions that are done under the sun. And behold, the tears of the oppressed, and they had no one to comfort them! On the side of their oppressors there was power, and there was no one to comfort them.
21Ec 4:2 And I thought the dead who are already dead more fortunate than the living who are still alive.
21Ec 4:3 But better than both is he who has not yet been and has not seen the evil deeds that are done under the sun.
21Ec 4:4 Then I saw that all toil and all skill in work come from a man's envy of his neighbor. This also is vanity and a striving after wind.
21Ec 4:5 The fool folds his hands and eats his own flesh.
21Ec 4:6 Better is a handful of quietness than two hands full of toil and a striving after wind.
21Ec 4:7 Again, I saw vanity under the sun:
21Ec 4:8 one person who has no other, either son or brother, yet there is no end to all his toil, and his eyes are never satisfied with riches, so that he never asks, "For whom am I toiling and depriving myself of pleasure?" This also is vanity and an unhappy business.
21Ec 4:9 Two are better than one, because they have a good reward for their toil.
21Ec 4:10 For if they fall, one will lift up his fellow. But woe to him who is alone when he falls and has not another to lift him up!
21Ec 4:11 Again, if two lie together, they keep warm, but how can one keep warm alone?
21Ec 4:12 And though a man might prevail against one who is alone, two will withstand him--a threefold cord is not quickly broken.
21Ec 4:13 Better was a poor and wise youth than an old and foolish king who no longer knew how to take advice.
21Ec 4:14 For he went from prison to the throne, though in his own kingdom he had been born poor.
21Ec 4:15 I saw all the living who move about under the sun, along with that youth who was to stand in the king's place.
21Ec 4:16 There was no end of all the people, all of whom he led. Yet those who come later will not rejoice in him. Surely this also is vanity and a striving after wind.
21Ec 5:1  Guard your steps when you go to the house of God. To draw near to listen is better than to offer the sacrifice of fools, for they do not know that they are doing evil.
21Ec 5:2  Be not rash with your mouth, nor let your heart be hasty to utter a word before God, for God is in heaven and you are on earth. Therefore let your words be few.
21Ec 5:3 For a dream comes with much business, and a fool's voice with many words.
21Ec 5:4 When you vow a vow to God, do not delay paying it, for he has no pleasure in fools. Pay what you vow.
21Ec 5:5 It is better that you should not vow than that you should vow and not pay.
21Ec 5:6 Let not your mouth lead you into sin, and do not say before the messenger that it was a mistake. Why should God be angry at your voice and destroy the work of your hands?
21Ec 5:7 For when dreams increase and words grow many, there is vanity; but God is the one you must fear.
21Ec 5:8 If you see in a province the oppression of the poor and the violation of justice and righteousness, do not be amazed at the matter, for the high official is watched by a higher, and there are yet higher ones over them.
21Ec 5:9 But this is gain for a land in every way: a king committed to cultivated fields.
21Ec 5:10 He who loves money will not be satisfied with money, nor he who loves wealth with his income; this also is vanity.
21Ec 5:11 When goods increase, they increase who eat them, and what advantage has their owner but to see them with his eyes?
21Ec 5:12 Sweet is the sleep of a laborer, whether he eats little or much, but the full stomach of the rich will not let him sleep.
21Ec 5:13 There is a grievous evil that I have seen under the sun: riches were kept by their owner to his hurt,
21Ec 5:14 and those riches were lost in a bad venture. And he is father of a son, but he has nothing in his hand.
21Ec 5:15 As he came from his mother's womb he shall go again, naked as he came, and shall take nothing for his toil that he may carry away in his hand.
21Ec 5:16 This also is a grievous evil: just as he came, so shall he go, and what gain is there to him who toils for the wind?
21Ec 5:17 Moreover, all his days he eats in darkness in much vexation and sickness and anger.
21Ec 5:18 Behold, what I have seen to be good and fitting is to eat and drink and find enjoyment in all the toil with which one toils under the sun the few days of his life that God has given him, for this is his lot.
21Ec 5:19 Everyone also to whom God has given wealth and possessions and power to enjoy them, and to accept his lot and rejoice in his toil--this is the gift of God.
21Ec 5:20 For he will not much remember the days of his life because God keeps him occupied with joy in his heart.
21Ec 6:1 There is an evil that I have seen under the sun, and it lies heavy on mankind:
21Ec 6:2 a man to whom God gives wealth, possessions, and honor, so that he lacks nothing of all that he desires, yet God does not give him power to enjoy them, but a stranger enjoys them. This is vanity; it is a grievous evil.
21Ec 6:3 If a man fathers a hundred children and lives many years, so that the days of his years are many, but his soul is not satisfied with life's good things, and he also has no burial, I say that a stillborn child is better off than he.
21Ec 6:4 For it comes in vanity and goes in darkness, and in darkness its name is covered.
21Ec 6:5 Moreover, it has not seen the sun or known anything, yet it finds rest rather than he.
21Ec 6:6 Even though he should live a thousand years twice over, yet enjoy no good--do not all go to the one place?
21Ec 6:7 All the toil of man is for his mouth, yet his appetite is not satisfied.
21Ec 6:8 For what advantage has the wise man over the fool? And what does the poor man have who knows how to conduct himself before the living?
21Ec 6:9 Better is the sight of the eyes than the wandering of the appetite: this also is vanity and a striving after wind.
21Ec 6:10 Whatever has come to be has already been named, and it is known what man is, and that he is not able to dispute with one stronger than he.
21Ec 6:11 The more words, the more vanity, and what is the advantage to man?
21Ec 6:12 For who knows what is good for man while he lives the few days of his vain life, which he passes like a shadow? For who can tell man what will be after him under the sun?
21Ec 7:1 A good name is better than precious ointment, and the day of death than the day of birth.
21Ec 7:2 It is better to go to the house of mourning than to go to the house of feasting, for this is the end of all mankind, and the living will lay it to heart.
21Ec 7:3 Sorrow is better than laughter, for by sadness of face the heart is made glad.
21Ec 7:4 The heart of the wise is in the house of mourning, but the heart of fools is in the house of mirth.
21Ec 7:5 It is better for a man to hear the rebuke of the wise than to hear the song of fools.
21Ec 7:6 For as the crackling of thorns under a pot, so is the laughter of the fools; this also is vanity.
21Ec 7:7 Surely oppression drives the wise into madness, and a bribe corrupts the heart.
21Ec 7:8 Better is the end of a thing than its beginning, and the patient in spirit is better than the proud in spirit.
21Ec 7:9 Be not quick in your spirit to become angry, for anger lodges in the bosom of fools.
21Ec 7:10 Say not, "Why were the former days better than these?" For it is not from wisdom that you ask this.
21Ec 7:11 Wisdom is good with an inheritance, an advantage to those who see the sun.
21Ec 7:12 For the protection of wisdom is like the protection of money, and the advantage of knowledge is that wisdom preserves the life of him who has it.
21Ec 7:13 Consider the work of God: who can make straight what he has made crooked?
21Ec 7:14 In the day of prosperity be joyful, and in the day of adversity consider: God has made the one as well as the other, so that man may not find out anything that will be after him.
21Ec 7:15 In my vain life I have seen everything. There is a righteous man who perishes in his righteousness, and there is a wicked man who prolongs his life in his evildoing.
21Ec 7:16 Be not overly righteous, and do not make yourself too wise. Why should you destroy yourself?
21Ec 7:17 Be not overly wicked, neither be a fool. Why should you die before your time?
21Ec 7:18 It is good that you should take hold of this, and from that withhold not your hand, for the one who fears God shall come out from both of them.
21Ec 7:19 Wisdom gives strength to the wise man more than ten rulers who are in a city.
21Ec 7:20 Surely there is not a righteous man on earth who does good and never sins.
21Ec 7:21 Do not take to heart all the things that people say, lest you hear your servant cursing you.
21Ec 7:22 Your heart knows that many times you yourself have cursed others.
21Ec 7:23 All this I have tested by wisdom. I said, "I will be wise," but it was far from me.
21Ec 7:24 That which has been is far off, and deep, very deep; who can find it out?
21Ec 7:25 I turned my heart to know and to search out and to seek wisdom and the scheme of things, and to know the wickedness of folly and the foolishness that is madness.
21Ec 7:26 And I find something more bitter than death: the woman whose heart is snares and nets, and whose hands are fetters. He who pleases God escapes her, but the sinner is taken by her.
21Ec 7:27 Behold, this is what I found, says the Preacher, while adding one thing to another to find the scheme of things--
21Ec 7:28 which my soul has sought repeatedly, but I have not found. One man among a thousand I found, but a woman among all these I have not found.
21Ec 7:29 See, this alone I found, that God made man upright, but they have sought out many schemes.
21Ec 8:1 Who is like the wise? And who knows the interpretation of a thing? A man's wisdom makes his face shine, and the hardness of his face is changed.
21Ec 8:2 I say: Keep the king's command, because of God's oath to him.
21Ec 8:3 Be not hasty to go from his presence. Do not take your stand in an evil cause, for he does whatever he pleases.
21Ec 8:4 For the word of the king is supreme, and who may say to him, "What are you doing?"
21Ec 8:5 Whoever keeps a command will know no evil thing, and the wise heart will know the proper time and the just way.
21Ec 8:6 For there is a time and a way for everything, although man's trouble lies heavy on him.
21Ec 8:7 For he does not know what is to be, for who can tell him how it will be?
21Ec 8:8 No man has power to retain the spirit, or power over the day of death. There is no discharge from war, nor will wickedness deliver those who are given to it.
21Ec 8:9 All this I observed while applying my heart to all that is done under the sun, when man had power over man to his hurt.
21Ec 8:10 Then I saw the wicked buried. They used to go in and out of the holy place and were praised in the city where they had done such things. This also is vanity.
21Ec 8:11 Because the sentence against an evil deed is not executed speedily, the heart of the children of man is fully set to do evil.
21Ec 8:12 Though a sinner does evil a hundred times and prolongs his life, yet I know that it will be well with those who fear God, because they fear before him.
21Ec 8:13 But it will not be well with the wicked, neither will he prolong his days like a shadow, because he does not fear before God.
21Ec 8:14 There is a vanity that takes place on earth, that there are righteous people to whom it happens according to the deeds of the wicked, and there are wicked people to whom it happens according to the deeds of the righteous. I said that this also is vanity.
21Ec 8:15 And I commend joy, for man has no good thing under the sun but to eat and drink and be joyful, for this will go with him in his toil through the days of his life that God has given him under the sun.
21Ec 8:16 When I applied my heart to know wisdom, and to see the business that is done on earth, how neither day nor night do one's eyes see sleep,
21Ec 8:17 then I saw all the work of God, that man cannot find out the work that is done under the sun. However much man may toil in seeking, he will not find it out. Even though a wise man claims to know, he cannot find it out.
21Ec 9:1 But all this I laid to heart, examining it all, how the righteous and the wise and their deeds are in the hand of God. Whether it is love or hate, man does not know; both are before him.
21Ec 9:2 It is the same for all, since the same event happens to the righteous and the wicked, to the good and the evil, to the clean and the unclean, to him who sacrifices and him who does not sacrifice. As the good one is, so is the sinner, and he who swears is as he who shuns an oath.
21Ec 9:3 This is an evil in all that is done under the sun, that the same event happens to all. Also, the hearts of the children of man are full of evil, and madness is in their hearts while they live, and after that they go to the dead.
21Ec 9:4 But he who is joined with all the living has hope, for a living dog is better than a dead lion.
21Ec 9:5 For the living know that they will die, but the dead know nothing, and they have no more reward, for the memory of them is forgotten.
21Ec 9:6 Their love and their hate and their envy have already perished, and forever they have no more share in all that is done under the sun.
21Ec 9:7 Go, eat your bread with joy, and drink your wine with a merry heart, for God has already approved what you do.
21Ec 9:8 Let your garments be always white. Let not oil be lacking on your head.
21Ec 9:9 Enjoy life with the wife whom you love, all the days of your vain life that he has given you under the sun, because that is your portion in life and in your toil at which you toil under the sun.
21Ec 9:10 Whatever your hand finds to do, do it with your might, for there is no work or thought or knowledge or wisdom in Sheol, to which you are going.
21Ec 9:11 Again I saw that under the sun the race is not to the swift, nor the battle to the strong, nor bread to the wise, nor riches to the intelligent, nor favor to those with knowledge, but time and chance happen to them all.
21Ec 9:12 For man does not know his time. Like fish that are taken in an evil net, and like birds that are caught in a snare, so the children of man are snared at an evil time, when it suddenly falls upon them.
21Ec 9:13 I have also seen this example of wisdom under the sun, and it seemed great to me.
21Ec 9:14 There was a little city with few men in it, and a great king came against it and besieged it, building great siegeworks against it.
21Ec 9:15 But there was found in it a poor, wise man, and he by his wisdom delivered the city. Yet no one remembered that poor man.
21Ec 9:16 But I say that wisdom is better than might, though the poor man's wisdom is despised and his words are not heard.
21Ec 9:17 The words of the wise heard in quiet are better than the shouting of a ruler among fools.
21Ec 9:18 Wisdom is better than weapons of war, but one sinner destroys much good.
21Ec 10:1 Dead flies make the perfumer's ointment give off a stench; so a little folly outweighs wisdom and honor.
21Ec 10:2 A wise man's heart inclines him to the right, but a fool's heart to the left.
21Ec 10:3 Even when the fool walks on the road, he lacks sense, and he says to everyone that he is a fool.
21Ec 10:4 If the anger of the ruler rises against you, do not leave your place, for calmness will lay great offenses to rest.
21Ec 10:5 There is an evil that I have seen under the sun, as it were an error proceeding from the ruler:
21Ec 10:6 folly is set in many high places, and the rich sit in a low place.
21Ec 10:7 I have seen slaves on horses, and princes walking on the ground like slaves.
21Ec 10:8 He who digs a pit will fall into it, and a serpent will bite him who breaks through a wall.
21Ec 10:9 He who quarries stones is hurt by them, and he who splits logs is endangered by them.
21Ec 10:10 If the iron is blunt, and one does not sharpen the edge, he must use more strength, but wisdom helps one to succeed.
21Ec 10:11 If the serpent bites before it is charmed, there is no advantage to the charmer.
21Ec 10:12 The words of a wise man's mouth win him favor, but the lips of a fool consume him.
21Ec 10:13 The beginning of the words of his mouth is foolishness, and the end of his talk is evil madness.
21Ec 10:14 A fool multiplies words, though no man knows what is to be, and who can tell him what will be after him?
21Ec 10:15 The toil of a fool wearies him, for he does not know the way to the city.
21Ec 10:16 Woe to you, O land, when your king is a child, and your princes feast in the morning!
21Ec 10:17 Happy are you, O land, when your king is the son of the nobility, and your princes feast at the proper time, for strength, and not for drunkenness!
21Ec 10:18 Through sloth the roof sinks in, and through indolence the house leaks.
21Ec 10:19 Bread is made for laughter, and wine gladdens life, and money answers everything.
21Ec 10:20 Even in your thoughts, do not curse the king, nor in your bedroom curse the rich, for a bird of the air will carry your voice, or some winged creature tell the matter.
21Ec 11:1 Cast your bread upon the waters, for you will find it after many days.
21Ec 11:2 Give a portion to seven, or even to eight, for you know not what disaster may happen on earth.
21Ec 11:3 If the clouds are full of rain, they empty themselves on the earth, and if a tree falls to the south or to the north, in the place where the tree falls, there it will lie.
21Ec 11:4 He who observes the wind will not sow, and he who regards the clouds will not reap.
21Ec 11:5 As you do not know the way the spirit comes to the bones in the womb of a woman with child, so you do not know the work of God who makes everything.
21Ec 11:6 In the morning sow your seed, and at evening withhold not your hand, for you do not know which will prosper, this or that, or whether both alike will be good.
21Ec 11:7 Light is sweet, and it is pleasant for the eyes to see the sun.
21Ec 11:8 So if a person lives many years, let him rejoice in them all; but let him remember that the days of darkness will be many. All that comes is vanity.
21Ec 11:9 Rejoice, O young man, in your youth, and let your heart cheer you in the days of your youth. Walk in the ways of your heart and the sight of your eyes. But know that for all these things God will bring you into judgment.
21Ec 11:10 Remove vexation from your heart, and put away pain from your body, for youth and the dawn of life are vanity.
21Ec 12:1 Remember also your Creator in the days of your youth, before the evil days come and the years draw near of which you will say, "I have no pleasure in them";
21Ec 12:2 before the sun and the light and the moon and the stars are darkened and the clouds return after the rain,
21Ec 12:3 in the day when the keepers of the house tremble, and the strong men are bent, and the grinders cease because they are few, and those who look through the windows are dimmed,
21Ec 12:4 and the doors on the street are shut--when the sound of the grinding is low, and one rises up at the sound of a bird, and all the daughters of song are brought low--
21Ec 12:5 they are afraid also of what is high, and terrors are in the way; the almond tree blossoms, the grasshopper drags itself along, and desire fails, because man is going to his eternal home, and the mourners go about the streets--
21Ec 12:6 before the silver cord is snapped, or the golden bowl is broken, or the pitcher is shattered at the fountain, or the wheel broken at the cistern,
21Ec 12:7 and the dust returns to the earth as it was, and the spirit returns to God who gave it.
21Ec 12:8 Vanity of vanities, says the Preacher; all is vanity.
21Ec 12:9 Besides being wise, the Preacher also taught the people knowledge, weighing and studying and arranging many proverbs with great care.
21Ec 12:10 The Preacher sought to find words of delight, and uprightly he wrote words of truth.
21Ec 12:11 The words of the wise are like goads, and like nails firmly fixed are the collected sayings; they are given by one Shepherd.
21Ec 12:12 My son, beware of anything beyond these. Of making many books there is no end, and much study is a weariness of the flesh.
21Ec 12:13 The end of the matter; all has been heard. Fear God and keep his commandments, for this is the whole duty of man.
21Ec 12:14 For God will bring every deed into judgment, with every secret thing, whether good or evil.
22
22Sg 1:1 The Song of Songs, which is Solomon's.
22Sg 1:2 Let him kiss me with the kisses of his mouth! For your love is better than wine;
22Sg 1:3 your anointing oils are fragrant; your name is oil poured out; therefore virgins love you.
22Sg 1:4 Draw me after you; let us run. The king has brought me into his chambers. We will exult and rejoice in you; we will extol your love more than wine; rightly do they love you.
22Sg 1:5 I am very dark, but lovely, O daughters of Jerusalem, like the tents of Kedar, like the curtains of Solomon.
22Sg 1:6 Do not gaze at me because I am dark, because the sun has looked upon me. My mother's sons were angry with me; they made me keeper of the vineyards, but my own vineyard I have not kept!
22Sg 1:7 Tell me, you whom my soul loves, where you pasture your flock, where you make it lie down at noon; for why should I be like one who veils herself beside the flocks of your companions?
22Sg 1:8 If you do not know, O most beautiful among women, follow in the tracks of the flock, and pasture your young goats beside the shepherds' tents.
22Sg 1:9 I compare you, my love, to a mare among Pharaoh's chariots.
22Sg 1:10 Your cheeks are lovely with ornaments, your neck with strings of jewels.
22Sg 1:11 We will make for you ornaments of gold, studded with silver.
22Sg 1:12 While the king was on his couch, my nard gave forth its fragrance.
22Sg 1:13 My beloved is to me a sachet of myrrh that lies between my breasts.
22Sg 1:14 My beloved is to me a cluster of henna blossoms in the vineyards of Engedi.
22Sg 1:15 Behold, you are beautiful, my love; behold, you are beautiful; your eyes are doves.
22Sg 1:16 Behold, you are beautiful, my beloved, truly delightful. Our couch is green;
22Sg 1:17 the beams of our house are cedar; our rafters are pine.
22Sg 2:1 I am a rose of Sharon, a lily of the valleys.
22Sg 2:2 As a lily among brambles, so is my love among the young women.
22Sg 2:3 As an apple tree among the trees of the forest, so is my beloved among the young men. With great delight I sat in his shadow, and his fruit was sweet to my taste.
22Sg 2:4 He brought me to the banqueting house, and his banner over me was love.
22Sg 2:5 Sustain me with raisins; refresh me with apples, for I am sick with love.
22Sg 2:6 His left hand is under my head, and his right hand embraces me!
22Sg 2:7 I adjure you, O daughters of Jerusalem, by the gazelles or the does of the field, that you not stir up or awaken love until it pleases.
22Sg 2:8 The voice of my beloved! Behold, he comes, leaping over the mountains, bounding over the hills.
22Sg 2:9 My beloved is like a gazelle or a young stag. Behold, there he stands behind our wall, gazing through the windows, looking through the lattice.
22Sg 2:10 My beloved speaks and says to me: "Arise, my love, my beautiful one, and come away,
22Sg 2:11 for behold, the winter is past; the rain is over and gone.
22Sg 2:12 The flowers appear on the earth, the time of singing has come, and the voice of the turtledove is heard in our land.
22Sg 2:13 The fig tree ripens its figs, and the vines are in blossom; they give forth fragrance. Arise, my love, my beautiful one, and come away.
22Sg 2:14 O my dove, in the clefts of the rock, in the crannies of the cliff, let me see your face, let me hear your voice, for your voice is sweet, and your face is lovely.
22Sg 2:15 Catch the foxes for us, the little foxes that spoil the vineyards, for our vineyards are in blossom."
22Sg 2:16 My beloved is mine, and I am his; he grazes among the lilies.
22Sg 2:17 Until the day breathes and the shadows flee, turn, my beloved, be like a gazelle or a young stag on cleft mountains.
22Sg 3:1 On my bed by night I sought him whom my soul loves; I sought him, but found him not.
22Sg 3:2 I will rise now and go about the city, in the streets and in the squares; I will seek him whom my soul loves. I sought him, but found him not.
22Sg 3:3 The watchmen found me as they went about in the city. "Have you seen him whom my soul loves?"
22Sg 3:4 Scarcely had I passed them when I found him whom my soul loves. I held him, and would not let him go until I had brought him into my mother's house, and into the chamber of her who conceived me.
22Sg 3:5 I adjure you, O daughters of Jerusalem, by the gazelles or the does of the field, that you not stir up or awaken love until it pleases.
22Sg 3:6 What is that coming up from the wilderness like columns of smoke, perfumed with myrrh and frankincense, with all the fragrant powders of a merchant?
22Sg 3:7 Behold, it is the litter of Solomon! Around it are sixty mighty men, some of the mighty men of Israel,
22Sg 3:8 all of them wearing swords and expert in war, each with his sword at his thigh, against terror by night.
22Sg 3:9 King Solomon made himself a carriage from the wood of Lebanon.
22Sg 3:10 He made its posts of silver, its back of gold, its seat of purple; its interior was inlaid with love by the daughters of Jerusalem.
22Sg 3:11 Go out, O daughters of Zion, and look upon King Solomon, with the crown with which his mother crowned him on the day of his wedding, on the day of the gladness of his heart.
22Sg 4:1 Behold, you are beautiful, my love, behold, you are beautiful! Your eyes are doves behind your veil. Your hair is like a flock of goats leaping down the slopes of Gilead.
22Sg 4:2 Your teeth are like a flock of shorn ewes that have come up from the washing, all of which bear twins, and not one among them has lost its young.
22Sg 4:3 Your lips are like a scarlet thread, and your mouth is lovely. Your cheeks are like halves of a pomegranate behind your veil.
22Sg 4:4 Your neck is like the tower of David, built in rows of stone; on it hang a thousand shields, all of them shields of warriors.
22Sg 4:5 Your two breasts are like two fawns, twins of a gazelle, that graze among the lilies.
22Sg 4:6 Until the day breathes and the shadows flee, I will go away to the mountain of myrrh and the hill of frankincense.
22Sg 4:7 You are altogether beautiful, my love; there is no flaw in you.
22Sg 4:8 Come with me from Lebanon, my bride; come with me from Lebanon. Depart from the peak of Amana, from the peak of Senir and Hermon, from the dens of lions, from the mountains of leopards.
22Sg 4:9 You have captivated my heart, my sister, my bride; you have captivated my heart with one glance of your eyes, with one jewel of your necklace.
22Sg 4:10 How beautiful is your love, my sister, my bride! How much better is your love than wine, and the fragrance of your oils than any spice!
22Sg 4:11 Your lips drip nectar, my bride; honey and milk are under your tongue; the fragrance of your garments is like the fragrance of Lebanon.
22Sg 4:12 A garden locked is my sister, my bride, a spring locked, a fountain sealed.
22Sg 4:13 Your shoots are an orchard of pomegranates with all choicest fruits, henna with nard,
22Sg 4:14 nard and saffron, calamus and cinnamon, with all trees of frankincense, myrrh and aloes, with all choice spices--
22Sg 4:15 a garden fountain, a well of living water, and flowing streams from Lebanon.
22Sg 4:16 Awake, O north wind, and come, O south wind! Blow upon my garden, let its spices flow. Let my beloved come to his garden, and eat its choicest fruits.
22Sg 5:1 I came to my garden, my sister, my bride, I gathered my myrrh with my spice, I ate my honeycomb with my honey, I drank my wine with my milk. Eat, friends, drink, and be drunk with love!
22Sg 5:2 I slept, but my heart was awake. A sound! My beloved is knocking. "Open to me, my sister, my love, my dove, my perfect one, for my head is wet with dew, my locks with the drops of the night."
22Sg 5:3 I had put off my garment; how could I put it on? I had bathed my feet; how could I soil them?
22Sg 5:4 My beloved put his hand to the latch, and my heart was thrilled within me.
22Sg 5:5 I arose to open to my beloved, and my hands dripped with myrrh, my fingers with liquid myrrh, on the handles of the bolt.
22Sg 5:6 I opened to my beloved, but my beloved had turned and gone. My soul failed me when he spoke. I sought him, but found him not; I called him, but he gave no answer.
22Sg 5:7 The watchmen found me as they went about in the city; they beat me, they bruised me, they took away my veil, those watchmen of the walls.
22Sg 5:8 I adjure you, O daughters of Jerusalem, if you find my beloved, that you tell him I am sick with love.
22Sg 5:9 What is your beloved more than another beloved, O most beautiful among women? What is your beloved more than another beloved, that you thus adjure us?
22Sg 5:10 My beloved is radiant and ruddy, distinguished among ten thousand.
22Sg 5:11 His head is the finest gold; his locks are wavy, black as a raven.
22Sg 5:12 His eyes are like doves beside streams of water, bathed in milk, sitting beside a full pool.
22Sg 5:13 His cheeks are like beds of spices, mounds of sweet-smelling herbs. His lips are lilies, dripping liquid myrrh.
22Sg 5:14 His arms are rods of gold, set with jewels. His body is polished ivory, bedecked with sapphires.
22Sg 5:15 His legs are alabaster columns, set on bases of gold. His appearance is like Lebanon, choice as the cedars.
22Sg 5:16 His mouth is most sweet, and he is altogether desirable. This is my beloved and this is my friend, O daughters of Jerusalem.
22Sg 6:1 Where has your beloved gone, O most beautiful among women? Where has your beloved turned, that we may seek him with you?
22Sg 6:2 My beloved has gone down to his garden to the beds of spices, to graze in the gardens and to gather lilies.
22Sg 6:3 I am my beloved's and my beloved is mine; he grazes among the lilies.
22Sg 6:4 You are beautiful as Tirzah, my love, lovely as Jerusalem, awesome as an army with banners.
22Sg 6:5 Turn away your eyes from me, for they overwhelm me-- Your hair is like a flock of goats leaping down the slopes of Gilead.
22Sg 6:6 Your teeth are like a flock of ewes that have come up from the washing; all of them bear twins; not one among them has lost its young.
22Sg 6:7 Your cheeks are like halves of a pomegranate behind your veil.
22Sg 6:8 There are sixty queens and eighty concubines, and virgins without number.
22Sg 6:9 My dove, my perfect one, is the only one, the only one of her mother, pure to her who bore her. The young women saw her and called her blessed; the queens and concubines also, and they praised her.
22Sg 6:10 "Who is this who looks down like the dawn, beautiful as the moon, bright as the sun, awesome as an army with banners?"
22Sg 6:11 I went down to the nut orchard to look at the blossoms of the valley, to see whether the vines had budded, whether the pomegranates were in bloom.
22Sg 6:12 Before I was aware, my desire set me among the chariots of my kinsman, a prince.
22Sg 6:13  Return, return, O Shulammite, return, return, that we may look upon you. Why should you look upon the Shulammite, as upon a dance before two armies?
22Sg 7:1 How beautiful are your feet in sandals, O noble daughter! Your rounded thighs are like jewels, the work of a master hand.
22Sg 7:2 Your navel is a rounded bowl that never lacks mixed wine. Your belly is a heap of wheat, encircled with lilies.
22Sg 7:3 Your two breasts are like two fawns, twins of a gazelle.
22Sg 7:4 Your neck is like an ivory tower. Your eyes are pools in Heshbon, by the gate of Bath-rabbim. Your nose is like a tower of Lebanon, which looks toward Damascus.
22Sg 7:5 Your head crowns you like Carmel, and your flowing locks are like purple; a king is held captive in the tresses.
22Sg 7:6 How beautiful and pleasant you are, O loved one, with all your delights!
22Sg 7:7 Your stature is like a palm tree, and your breasts are like its clusters.
22Sg 7:8 I say I will climb the palm tree and lay hold of its fruit. Oh may your breasts be like clusters of the vine, and the scent of your breath like apples,
22Sg 7:9 and your mouth like the best wine. It goes down smoothly for my beloved, gliding over lips and teeth.
22Sg 7:10 I am my beloved's, and his desire is for me.
22Sg 7:11 Come, my beloved, let us go out into the fields and lodge in the villages;
22Sg 7:12 let us go out early to the vineyards and see whether the vines have budded, whether the grape blossoms have opened and the pomegranates are in bloom. There I will give you my love.
22Sg 7:13 The mandrakes give forth fragrance, and beside our doors are all choice fruits, new as well as old, which I have laid up for you, O my beloved.
22Sg 8:1 Oh that you were like a brother to me who nursed at my mother's breasts! If I found you outside, I would kiss you, and none would despise me.
22Sg 8:2 I would lead you and bring you into the house of my mother-- she who used to teach me. I would give you spiced wine to drink, the juice of my pomegranate.
22Sg 8:3 His left hand is under my head, and his right hand embraces me!
22Sg 8:4 I adjure you, O daughters of Jerusalem, that you not stir up or awaken love until it pleases.
22Sg 8:5 Who is that coming up from the wilderness, leaning on her beloved? Under the apple tree I awakened you. There your mother was in labor with you; there she who bore you was in labor.
22Sg 8:6 Set me as a seal upon your heart, as a seal upon your arm, for love is strong as death, jealousy is fierce as the grave. Its flashes are flashes of fire, the very flame of the LORD.
22Sg 8:7 Many waters cannot quench love, neither can floods drown it. If a man offered for love all the wealth of his house, he would be utterly despised.
22Sg 8:8 We have a little sister, and she has no breasts. What shall we do for our sister on the day when she is spoken for?
22Sg 8:9 If she is a wall, we will build on her a battlement of silver, but if she is a door, we will enclose her with boards of cedar.
22Sg 8:10 I was a wall, and my breasts were like towers; then I was in his eyes as one who finds peace.
22Sg 8:11 Solomon had a vineyard at Baal-hamon; he let out the vineyard to keepers; each one was to bring for its fruit a thousand pieces of silver.
22Sg 8:12 My vineyard, my very own, is before me; you, O Solomon, may have the thousand, and the keepers of the fruit two hundred.
22Sg 8:13 O you who dwell in the gardens, with companions listening for your voice; let me hear it.
22Sg 8:14 Make haste, my beloved, and be like a gazelle or a young stag on the mountains of spices.
23
23Is 1:1 The vision of Isaiah the son of Amoz, which he saw concerning Judah and Jerusalem in the days of Uzziah, Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah, kings of Judah.
23Is 1:2 Hear, O heavens, and give ear, O earth; for the LORD has spoken: "Children have I reared and brought up, but they have rebelled against me.
23Is 1:3 The ox knows its owner, and the donkey its master's crib, but Israel does not know, my people do not understand."
23Is 1:4 Ah, sinful nation, a people laden with iniquity, offspring of evildoers, children who deal corruptly! They have forsaken the LORD, they have despised the Holy One of Israel, they are utterly estranged.
23Is 1:5 Why will you still be struck down? Why will you continue to rebel? The whole head is sick, and the whole heart faint.
23Is 1:6 From the sole of the foot even to the head, there is no soundness in it, but bruises and sores and raw wounds; they are not pressed out or bound up or softened with oil.
23Is 1:7 Your country lies desolate; your cities are burned with fire; in your very presence foreigners devour your land; it is desolate, as overthrown by foreigners.
23Is 1:8 And the daughter of Zion is left like a booth in a vineyard, like a lodge in a cucumber field, like a besieged city.
23Is 1:9 If the LORD of hosts had not left us a few survivors, we should have been like Sodom, and become like Gomorrah.
23Is 1:10 Hear the word of the LORD, you rulers of Sodom! Give ear to the teaching of our God, you people of Gomorrah!
23Is 1:11 "What to me is the multitude of your sacrifices? says the LORD; I have had enough of burnt offerings of rams and the fat of well-fed beasts; I do not delight in the blood of bulls, or of lambs, or of goats.
23Is 1:12 "When you come to appear before me, who has required of you this trampling of my courts?
23Is 1:13 Bring no more vain offerings; incense is an abomination to me. New moon and Sabbath and the calling of convocations-- I cannot endure iniquity and solemn assembly.
23Is 1:14 Your new moons and your appointed feasts my soul hates; they have become a burden to me; I am weary of bearing them.
23Is 1:15 When you spread out your hands, I will hide my eyes from you; even though you make many prayers, I will not listen; your hands are full of blood.
23Is 1:16 Wash yourselves; make yourselves clean; remove the evil of your deeds from before my eyes; cease to do evil,
23Is 1:17 learn to do good; seek justice, correct oppression; bring justice to the fatherless, plead the widow's cause.
23Is 1:18 "Come now, let us reason together, says the LORD: though your sins are like scarlet, they shall be as white as snow; though they are red like crimson, they shall become like wool.
23Is 1:19 If you are willing and obedient, you shall eat the good of the land;
23Is 1:20 but if you refuse and rebel, you shall be eaten by the sword; for the mouth of the LORD has spoken."
23Is 1:21 How the faithful city has become a whore, she who was full of justice! Righteousness lodged in her, but now murderers.
23Is 1:22 Your silver has become dross, your best wine mixed with water.
23Is 1:23 Your princes are rebels and companions of thieves. Everyone loves a bribe and runs after gifts. They do not bring justice to the fatherless, and the widow's cause does not come to them.
23Is 1:24 Therefore the Lord declares, the LORD of hosts, the Mighty One of Israel: "Ah, I will get relief from my enemies and avenge myself on my foes.
23Is 1:25 I will turn my hand against you and will smelt away your dross as with lye and remove all your alloy.
23Is 1:26 And I will restore your judges as at the first, and your counselors as at the beginning. Afterward you shall be called the city of righteousness, the faithful city."
23Is 1:27 Zion shall be redeemed by justice, and those in her who repent, by righteousness.
23Is 1:28 But rebels and sinners shall be broken together, and those who forsake the LORD shall be consumed.
23Is 1:29 For they shall be ashamed of the oaks that you desired; and you shall blush for the gardens that you have chosen.
23Is 1:30 For you shall be like an oak whose leaf withers, and like a garden without water.
23Is 1:31 And the strong shall become tinder, and his work a spark, and both of them shall burn together, with none to quench them.
23Is 2:1 The word that Isaiah the son of Amoz saw concerning Judah and Jerusalem.
23Is 2:2 It shall come to pass in the latter days that the mountain of the house of the LORD shall be established as the highest of the mountains, and shall be lifted up above the hills; and all the nations shall flow to it,
23Is 2:3 and many peoples shall come, and say: "Come, let us go up to the mountain of the LORD, to the house of the God of Jacob, that he may teach us his ways and that we may walk in his paths." For out of Zion shall go the law, and the word of the LORD from Jerusalem.
23Is 2:4 He shall judge between the nations, and shall decide disputes for many peoples; and they shall beat their swords into plowshares, and their spears into pruning hooks; nation shall not lift up sword against nation, neither shall they learn war anymore.
23Is 2:5 O house of Jacob, come, let us walk in the light of the LORD.
23Is 2:6 For you have rejected your people, the house of Jacob, because they are full of things from the east and of fortune-tellers like the Philistines, and they strike hands with the children of foreigners.
23Is 2:7 Their land is filled with silver and gold, and there is no end to their treasures; their land is filled with horses, and there is no end to their chariots.
23Is 2:8 Their land is filled with idols; they bow down to the work of their hands, to what their own fingers have made.
23Is 2:9 So man is humbled, and each one is brought low-- do not forgive them!
23Is 2:10 Enter into the rock and hide in the dust from before the terror of the LORD, and from the splendor of his majesty.
23Is 2:11 The haughty looks of man shall be brought low, and the lofty pride of men shall be humbled, and the LORD alone will be exalted in that day.
23Is 2:12 For the LORD of hosts has a day against all that is proud and lofty, against all that is lifted up--and it shall be brought low;
23Is 2:13 against all the cedars of Lebanon, lofty and lifted up; and against all the oaks of Bashan;
23Is 2:14 against all the lofty mountains, and against all the uplifted hills;
23Is 2:15 against every high tower, and against every fortified wall;
23Is 2:16 against all the ships of Tarshish, and against all the beautiful craft.
23Is 2:17 And the haughtiness of man shall be humbled, and the lofty pride of men shall be brought low, and the LORD alone will be exalted in that day.
23Is 2:18 And the idols shall utterly pass away.
23Is 2:19 And people shall enter the caves of the rocks and the holes of the ground, from before the terror of the LORD, and from the splendor of his majesty, when he rises to terrify the earth.
23Is 2:20 In that day mankind will cast away their idols of silver and their idols of gold, which they made for themselves to worship, to the moles and to the bats,
23Is 2:21 to enter the caverns of the rocks and the clefts of the cliffs, from before the terror of the LORD, and from the splendor of his majesty, when he rises to terrify the earth.
23Is 2:22 Stop regarding man in whose nostrils is breath, for of what account is he?
23Is 3:1 For behold, the Lord GOD of hosts is taking away from Jerusalem and from Judah support and supply, all support of bread, and all support of water;
23Is 3:2 the mighty man and the soldier, the judge and the prophet, the diviner and the elder,
23Is 3:3 the captain of fifty and the man of rank, the counselor and the skillful magician and the expert in charms.
23Is 3:4 And I will make boys their princes, and infants shall rule over them.
23Is 3:5 And the people will oppress one another, every one his fellow and every one his neighbor; the youth will be insolent to the elder, and the despised to the honorable.
23Is 3:6 For a man will take hold of his brother in the house of his father, saying: "You have a cloak; you shall be our leader, and this heap of ruins shall be under your rule";
23Is 3:7 in that day he will speak out, saying: "I will not be a healer; in my house there is neither bread nor cloak; you shall not make me leader of the people."
23Is 3:8 For Jerusalem has stumbled, and Judah has fallen, because their speech and their deeds are against the LORD, defying his glorious presence.
23Is 3:9 For the look on their faces bears witness against them; they proclaim their sin like Sodom; they do not hide it. Woe to them! For they have brought evil on themselves.
23Is 3:10 Tell the righteous that it shall be well with them, for they shall eat the fruit of their deeds.
23Is 3:11 Woe to the wicked! It shall be ill with him, for what his hands have dealt out shall be done to him.
23Is 3:12 My people--infants are their oppressors, and women rule over them. O my people, your guides mislead you and they have swallowed up the course of your paths.
23Is 3:13 The LORD has taken his place to contend; he stands to judge peoples.
23Is 3:14 The LORD will enter into judgment with the elders and princes of his people: "It is you who have devoured the vineyard, the spoil of the poor is in your houses.
23Is 3:15 What do you mean by crushing my people, by grinding the face of the poor?" declares the Lord GOD of hosts.
23Is 3:16 The LORD said: Because the daughters of Zion are haughty and walk with outstretched necks, glancing wantonly with their eyes, mincing along as they go, tinkling with their feet,
23Is 3:17 therefore the Lord will strike with a scab the heads of the daughters of Zion, and the LORD will lay bare their secret parts.
23Is 3:18 In that day the Lord will take away the finery of the anklets, the headbands, and the crescents;
23Is 3:19 the pendants, the bracelets, and the scarves;
23Is 3:20 the headdresses, the armlets, the sashes, the perfume boxes, and the amulets;
23Is 3:21 the signet rings and nose rings;
23Is 3:22 the festal robes, the mantles, the cloaks, and the handbags;
23Is 3:23 the mirrors, the linen garments, the turbans, and the veils.
23Is 3:24 Instead of perfume there will be rottenness; and instead of a belt, a rope; and instead of well-set hair, baldness; and instead of a rich robe, a skirt of sackcloth; and branding instead of beauty.
23Is 3:25 Your men shall fall by the sword and your mighty men in battle.
23Is 3:26 And her gates shall lament and mourn; empty, she shall sit on the ground.
23Is 4:1 And seven women shall take hold of one man in that day, saying, "We will eat our own bread and wear our own clothes, only let us be called by your name; take away our reproach."
23Is 4:2 In that day the branch of the LORD shall be beautiful and glorious, and the fruit of the land shall be the pride and honor of the survivors of Israel.
23Is 4:3 And he who is left in Zion and remains in Jerusalem will be called holy, everyone who has been recorded for life in Jerusalem,
23Is 4:4 when the Lord shall have washed away the filth of the daughters of Zion and cleansed the bloodstains of Jerusalem from its midst by a spirit of judgment and by a spirit of burning.
23Is 4:5 Then the LORD will create over the whole site of Mount Zion and over her assemblies a cloud by day, and smoke and the shining of a flaming fire by night; for over all the glory there will be a canopy.
23Is 4:6 There will be a booth for shade by day from the heat, and for a refuge and a shelter from the storm and rain.
23Is 5:1 Let me sing for my beloved my love song concerning his vineyard: My beloved had a vineyard on a very fertile hill.
23Is 5:2 He dug it and cleared it of stones, and planted it with choice vines; he built a watchtower in the midst of it, and hewed out a wine vat in it; and he looked for it to yield grapes, but it yielded wild grapes.
23Is 5:3 And now, O inhabitants of Jerusalem and men of Judah, judge between me and my vineyard.
23Is 5:4 What more was there to do for my vineyard, that I have not done in it? When I looked for it to yield grapes, why did it yield wild grapes?
23Is 5:5 And now I will tell you what I will do to my vineyard. I will remove its hedge, and it shall be devoured; I will break down its wall, and it shall be trampled down.
23Is 5:6 I will make it a waste; it shall not be pruned or hoed, and briers and thorns shall grow up; I will also command the clouds that they rain no rain upon it.
23Is 5:7 For the vineyard of the LORD of hosts is the house of Israel, and the men of Judah are his pleasant planting; and he looked for justice, but behold, bloodshed; for righteousness, but behold, an outcry!
23Is 5:8 Woe to those who join house to house, who add field to field, until there is no more room, and you are made to dwell alone in the midst of the land.
23Is 5:9 The LORD of hosts has sworn in my hearing: "Surely many houses shall be desolate, large and beautiful houses, without inhabitant.
23Is 5:10 For ten acres of vineyard shall yield but one bath, and a homer of seed shall yield but an ephah."
23Is 5:11 Woe to those who rise early in the morning, that they may run after strong drink, who tarry late into the evening as wine inflames them!
23Is 5:12 They have lyre and harp, tambourine and flute and wine at their feasts, but they do not regard the deeds of the LORD, or see the work of his hands.
23Is 5:13 Therefore my people go into exile for lack of knowledge; their honored men go hungry, and their multitude is parched with thirst.
23Is 5:14 Therefore Sheol has enlarged its appetite and opened its mouth beyond measure, and the nobility of Jerusalem and her multitude will go down, her revelers and he who exults in her.
23Is 5:15 Man is humbled, and each one is brought low, and the eyes of the haughty are brought low.
23Is 5:16 But the LORD of hosts is exalted in justice, and the Holy God shows himself holy in righteousness.
23Is 5:17 Then shall the lambs graze as in their pasture, and nomads shall eat among the ruins of the rich.
23Is 5:18 Woe to those who draw iniquity with cords of falsehood, who draw sin as with cart ropes,
23Is 5:19 who say: "Let him be quick, let him speed his work that we may see it; let the counsel of the Holy One of Israel draw near, and let it come, that we may know it!"
23Is 5:20 Woe to those who call evil good and good evil, who put darkness for light and light for darkness, who put bitter for sweet and sweet for bitter!
23Is 5:21 Woe to those who are wise in their own eyes, and shrewd in their own sight!
23Is 5:22 Woe to those who are heroes at drinking wine, and valiant men in mixing strong drink,
23Is 5:23 who acquit the guilty for a bribe, and deprive the innocent of his right!
23Is 5:24 Therefore, as the tongue of fire devours the stubble, and as dry grass sinks down in the flame, so their root will be as rottenness, and their blossom go up like dust; for they have rejected the law of the LORD of hosts, and have despised the word of the Holy One of Israel.
23Is 5:25 Therefore the anger of the LORD was kindled against his people, and he stretched out his hand against them and struck them, and the mountains quaked; and their corpses were as refuse in the midst of the streets. For all this his anger has not turned away, and his hand is stretched out still.
23Is 5:26 He will raise a signal for nations far away, and whistle for them from the ends of the earth; and behold, quickly, speedily they come!
23Is 5:27 None is weary, none stumbles, none slumbers or sleeps, not a waistband is loose, not a sandal strap broken;
23Is 5:28 their arrows are sharp, all their bows bent, their horses' hoofs seem like flint, and their wheels like the whirlwind.
23Is 5:29 Their roaring is like a lion, like young lions they roar; they growl and seize their prey; they carry it off, and none can rescue.
23Is 5:30 They will growl over it on that day, like the growling of the sea. And if one looks to the land, behold, darkness and distress; and the light is darkened by its clouds.
23Is 6:1 In the year that King Uzziah died I saw the Lord sitting upon a throne, high and lifted up; and the train of his robe filled the temple.
23Is 6:2 Above him stood the seraphim. Each had six wings: with two he covered his face, and with two he covered his feet, and with two he flew.
23Is 6:3 And one called to another and said: "Holy, holy, holy is the LORD of hosts; the whole earth is full of his glory!"
23Is 6:4 And the foundations of the thresholds shook at the voice of him who called, and the house was filled with smoke.
23Is 6:5 And I said: "Woe is me! For I am lost; for I am a man of unclean lips, and I dwell in the midst of a people of unclean lips; for my eyes have seen the King, the LORD of hosts!"
23Is 6:6 Then one of the seraphim flew to me, having in his hand a burning coal that he had taken with tongs from the altar.
23Is 6:7 And he touched my mouth and said: "Behold, this has touched your lips; your guilt is taken away, and your sin atoned for."
23Is 6:8 And I heard the voice of the Lord saying, "Whom shall I send, and who will go for us?" Then I said, "Here am I! Send me."
23Is 6:9 And he said, "Go, and say to this people: "'Keep on hearing, but do not understand; keep on seeing, but do not perceive.'
23Is 6:10 Make the heart of this people dull, and their ears heavy, and blind their eyes; lest they see with their eyes, and hear with their ears, and understand with their hearts, and turn and be healed."
23Is 6:11 Then I said, "How long, O Lord?" And he said: "Until cities lie waste without inhabitant, and houses without people, and the land is a desolate waste,
23Is 6:12 and the LORD removes people far away, and the forsaken places are many in the midst of the land.
23Is 6:13 And though a tenth remain in it, it will be burned again, like a terebinth or an oak, whose stump remains when it is felled." The holy seed is its stump.
23Is 7:1 In the days of Ahaz the son of Jotham, son of Uzziah, king of Judah, Rezin the king of Syria and Pekah the son of Remaliah the king of Israel came up to Jerusalem to wage war against it, but could not yet mount an attack against it.
23Is 7:2 When the house of David was told, "Syria is in league with Ephraim," the heart of Ahaz and the heart of his people shook as the trees of the forest shake before the wind.
23Is 7:3 And the LORD said to Isaiah, "Go out to meet Ahaz, you and Shear-jashub your son, at the end of the conduit of the upper pool on the highway to the Washer's Field.
23Is 7:4 And say to him, 'Be careful, be quiet, do not fear, and do not let your heart be faint because of these two smoldering stumps of firebrands, at the fierce anger of Rezin and Syria and the son of Remaliah.
23Is 7:5 Because Syria, with Ephraim and the son of Remaliah, has devised evil against you, saying,
23Is 7:6 "Let us go up against Judah and terrify it, and let us conquer it for ourselves, and set up the son of Tabeel as king in the midst of it,"
23Is 7:7 thus says the Lord GOD: "'It shall not stand, and it shall not come to pass.
23Is 7:8 For the head of Syria is Damascus, and the head of Damascus is Rezin. And within sixty-five years Ephraim will be shattered from being a people.
23Is 7:9 And the head of Ephraim is Samaria, and the head of Samaria is the son of Remaliah. If you are not firm in faith, you will not be firm at all.'"
23Is 7:10 Again the LORD spoke to Ahaz,
23Is 7:11 "Ask a sign of the LORD your God; let it be deep as Sheol or high as heaven."
23Is 7:12 But Ahaz said, "I will not ask, and I will not put the LORD to the test."
23Is 7:13 And he said, "Hear then, O house of David! Is it too little for you to weary men, that you weary my God also?
23Is 7:14 Therefore the Lord himself will give you a sign. Behold, the virgin shall conceive and bear a son, and shall call his name Immanuel.
23Is 7:15 He shall eat curds and honey when he knows how to refuse the evil and choose the good.
23Is 7:16 For before the boy knows how to refuse the evil and choose the good, the land whose two kings you dread will be deserted.
23Is 7:17 The LORD will bring upon you and upon your people and upon your father's house such days as have not come since the day that Ephraim departed from Judah--the king of Assyria."
23Is 7:18 In that day the LORD will whistle for the fly that is at the end of the streams of Egypt, and for the bee that is in the land of Assyria.
23Is 7:19 And they will all come and settle in the steep ravines, and in the clefts of the rocks, and on all the thornbushes, and on all the pastures.
23Is 7:20 In that day the Lord will shave with a razor that is hired beyond the River--with the king of Assyria--the head and the hair of the feet, and it will sweep away the beard also.
23Is 7:21 In that day a man will keep alive a young cow and two sheep,
23Is 7:22 and because of the abundance of milk that they give, he will eat curds, for everyone who is left in the land will eat curds and honey.
23Is 7:23 In that day every place where there used to be a thousand vines, worth a thousand shekels of silver, will become briers and thorns.
23Is 7:24 With bow and arrows a man will come there, for all the land will be briers and thorns.
23Is 7:25 And as for all the hills that used to be hoed with a hoe, you will not come there for fear of briers and thorns, but they will become a place where cattle are let loose and where sheep tread.
23Is 8:1 Then the LORD said to me, "Take a large tablet and write on it in common characters, 'Belonging to Maher-shalal-hash-baz.'
23Is 8:2 And I will get reliable witnesses, Uriah the priest and Zechariah the son of Jeberechiah, to attest for me."
23Is 8:3 And I went to the prophetess, and she conceived and bore a son. Then the LORD said to me, "Call his name Maher-shalal-hash-baz;
23Is 8:4 for before the boy knows how to cry 'My father' or 'My mother,' the wealth of Damascus and the spoil of Samaria will be carried away before the king of Assyria."
23Is 8:5 The LORD spoke to me again:
23Is 8:6 "Because this people has refused the waters of Shiloah that flow gently, and rejoice over Rezin and the son of Remaliah,
23Is 8:7 therefore, behold, the Lord is bringing up against them the waters of the River, mighty and many, the king of Assyria and all his glory. And it will rise over all its channels and go over all its banks,
23Is 8:8 and it will sweep on into Judah, it will overflow and pass on, reaching even to the neck, and its outspread wings will fill the breadth of your land, O Immanuel."
23Is 8:9 Be broken, you peoples, and be shattered; give ear, all you far countries; strap on your armor and be shattered; strap on your armor and be shattered.
23Is 8:10 Take counsel together, but it will come to nothing; speak a word, but it will not stand, for God is with us.
23Is 8:11 For the LORD spoke thus to me with his strong hand upon me, and warned me not to walk in the way of this people, saying:
23Is 8:12 "Do not call conspiracy all that this people calls conspiracy, and do not fear what they fear, nor be in dread.
23Is 8:13 But the LORD of hosts, him you shall honor as holy. Let him be your fear, and let him be your dread.
23Is 8:14 And he will become a sanctuary and a stone of offense and a rock of stumbling to both houses of Israel, a trap and a snare to the inhabitants of Jerusalem.
23Is 8:15 And many shall stumble on it. They shall fall and be broken; they shall be snared and taken."
23Is 8:16 Bind up the testimony; seal the teaching among my disciples.
23Is 8:17 I will wait for the LORD, who is hiding his face from the house of Jacob, and I will hope in him.
23Is 8:18 Behold, I and the children whom the LORD has given me are signs and portents in Israel from the LORD of hosts, who dwells on Mount Zion.
23Is 8:19 And when they say to you, "Inquire of the mediums and the necromancers who chirp and mutter," should not a people inquire of their God? Should they inquire of the dead on behalf of the living?
23Is 8:20 To the teaching and to the testimony! If they will not speak according to this word, it is because they have no dawn.
23Is 8:21 They will pass through the land, greatly distressed and hungry. And when they are hungry, they will be enraged and will speak contemptuously against their king and their God, and turn their faces upward.
23Is 8:22 And they will look to the earth, but behold, distress and darkness, the gloom of anguish. And they will be thrust into thick darkness.
23Is 9:1  But there will be no gloom for her who was in anguish. In the former time he brought into contempt the land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali, but in the latter time he has made glorious the way of the sea, the land beyond the Jordan, Galilee of the nations.
23Is 9:2  The people who walked in darkness have seen a great light; those who dwelt in a land of deep darkness, on them has light shined.
23Is 9:3 You have multiplied the nation; you have increased its joy; they rejoice before you as with joy at the harvest, as they are glad when they divide the spoil.
23Is 9:4 For the yoke of his burden, and the staff for his shoulder, the rod of his oppressor, you have broken as on the day of Midian.
23Is 9:5 For every boot of the tramping warrior in battle tumult and every garment rolled in blood will be burned as fuel for the fire.
23Is 9:6 For to us a child is born, to us a son is given; and the government shall be upon his shoulder, and his name shall be called Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God, Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace.
23Is 9:7 Of the increase of his government and of peace there will be no end, on the throne of David and over his kingdom, to establish it and to uphold it with justice and with righteousness from this time forth and forevermore. The zeal of the LORD of hosts will do this.
23Is 9:8 The Lord has sent a word against Jacob, and it will fall on Israel;
23Is 9:9 and all the people will know, Ephraim and the inhabitants of Samaria, who say in pride and in arrogance of heart:
23Is 9:10 "The bricks have fallen, but we will build with dressed stones; the sycamores have been cut down, but we will put cedars in their place."
23Is 9:11 But the LORD raises the adversaries of Rezin against him, and stirs up his enemies.
23Is 9:12 The Syrians on the east and the Philistines on the west devour Israel with open mouth. For all this his anger has not turned away, and his hand is stretched out still.
23Is 9:13 The people did not turn to him who struck them, nor inquire of the LORD of hosts.
23Is 9:14 So the LORD cut off from Israel head and tail, palm branch and reed in one day--
23Is 9:15 the elder and honored man is the head, and the prophet who teaches lies is the tail;
23Is 9:16 for those who guide this people have been leading them astray, and those who are guided by them are swallowed up.
23Is 9:17 Therefore the Lord does not rejoice over their young men, and has no compassion on their fatherless and widows; for everyone is godless and an evildoer, and every mouth speaks folly. For all this his anger has not turned away, and his hand is stretched out still.
23Is 9:18 For wickedness burns like a fire; it consumes briers and thorns; it kindles the thickets of the forest, and they roll upward in a column of smoke.
23Is 9:19 Through the wrath of the LORD of hosts the land is scorched, and the people are like fuel for the fire; no one spares another.
23Is 9:20 They slice meat on the right, but are still hungry, and they devour on the left, but are not satisfied; each devours the flesh of his own arm,
23Is 9:21 Manasseh devours Ephraim, and Ephraim devours Manasseh; together they are against Judah. For all this his anger has not turned away, and his hand is stretched out still.
23Is 10:1 Woe to those who decree iniquitous decrees, and the writers who keep writing oppression,
23Is 10:2 to turn aside the needy from justice and to rob the poor of my people of their right, that widows may be their spoil, and that they may make the fatherless their prey!
23Is 10:3 What will you do on the day of punishment, in the ruin that will come from afar? To whom will you flee for help, and where will you leave your wealth?
23Is 10:4 Nothing remains but to crouch among the prisoners or fall among the slain. For all this his anger has not turned away, and his hand is stretched out still.
23Is 10:5 Ah, Assyria, the rod of my anger; the staff in their hands is my fury!
23Is 10:6 Against a godless nation I send him, and against the people of my wrath I command him, to take spoil and seize plunder, and to tread them down like the mire of the streets.
23Is 10:7 But he does not so intend, and his heart does not so think; but it is in his heart to destroy, and to cut off nations not a few;
23Is 10:8 for he says: "Are not my commanders all kings?
23Is 10:9 Is not Calno like Carchemish? Is not Hamath like Arpad? Is not Samaria like Damascus?
23Is 10:10 As my hand has reached to the kingdoms of the idols, whose carved images were greater than those of Jerusalem and Samaria,
23Is 10:11 shall I not do to Jerusalem and her idols as I have done to Samaria and her images?"
23Is 10:12 When the Lord has finished all his work on Mount Zion and on Jerusalem, he will punish the speech of the arrogant heart of the king of Assyria and the boastful look in his eyes.
23Is 10:13 For he says: "By the strength of my hand I have done it, and by my wisdom, for I have understanding; I remove the boundaries of peoples, and plunder their treasures; like a bull I bring down those who sit on thrones.
23Is 10:14 My hand has found like a nest the wealth of the peoples; and as one gathers eggs that have been forsaken, so I have gathered all the earth; and there was none that moved a wing or opened the mouth or chirped."
23Is 10:15 Shall the axe boast over him who hews with it, or the saw magnify itself against him who wields it? As if a rod should wield him who lifts it, or as if a staff should lift him who is not wood!
23Is 10:16 Therefore the Lord GOD of hosts will send wasting sickness among his stout warriors, and under his glory a burning will be kindled, like the burning of fire.
23Is 10:17 The light of Israel will become a fire, and his Holy One a flame, and it will burn and devour his thorns and briers in one day.
23Is 10:18 The glory of his forest and of his fruitful land the LORD will destroy, both soul and body, and it will be as when a sick man wastes away.
23Is 10:19 The remnant of the trees of his forest will be so few that a child can write them down.
23Is 10:20 In that day the remnant of Israel and the survivors of the house of Jacob will no more lean on him who struck them, but will lean on the LORD, the Holy One of Israel, in truth.
23Is 10:21 A remnant will return, the remnant of Jacob, to the mighty God.
23Is 10:22 For though your people Israel be as the sand of the sea, only a remnant of them will return. Destruction is decreed, overflowing with righteousness.
23Is 10:23 For the Lord GOD of hosts will make a full end, as decreed, in the midst of all the earth.
23Is 10:24 Therefore thus says the Lord GOD of hosts: "O my people, who dwell in Zion, be not afraid of the Assyrians when they strike with the rod and lift up their staff against you as the Egyptians did.
23Is 10:25 For in a very little while my fury will come to an end, and my anger will be directed to their destruction.
23Is 10:26 And the LORD of hosts will wield against them a whip, as when he struck Midian at the rock of Oreb. And his staff will be over the sea, and he will lift it as he did in Egypt.
23Is 10:27 And in that day his burden will depart from your shoulder, and his yoke from your neck; and the yoke will be broken because of the fat."
23Is 10:28 He has come to Aiath; he has passed through Migron; at Michmash he stores his baggage;
23Is 10:29 they have crossed over the pass; at Geba they lodge for the night; Ramah trembles; Gibeah of Saul has fled.
23Is 10:30 Cry aloud, O daughter of Gallim! Give attention, O Laishah! O poor Anathoth!
23Is 10:31 Madmenah is in flight; the inhabitants of Gebim flee for safety.
23Is 10:32 This very day he will halt at Nob; he will shake his fist at the mount of the daughter of Zion, the hill of Jerusalem.
23Is 10:33 Behold, the Lord GOD of hosts will lop the boughs with terrifying power; the great in height will be hewn down, and the lofty will be brought low.
23Is 10:34 He will cut down the thickets of the forest with an axe, and Lebanon will fall by the Majestic One.
23Is 11:1 There shall come forth a shoot from the stump of Jesse, and a branch from his roots shall bear fruit.
23Is 11:2 And the Spirit of the LORD shall rest upon him, the Spirit of wisdom and understanding, the Spirit of counsel and might, the Spirit of knowledge and the fear of the LORD.
23Is 11:3 And his delight shall be in the fear of the LORD. He shall not judge by what his eyes see, or decide disputes by what his ears hear,
23Is 11:4 but with righteousness he shall judge the poor, and decide with equity for the meek of the earth; and he shall strike the earth with the rod of his mouth, and with the breath of his lips he shall kill the wicked.
23Is 11:5 Righteousness shall be the belt of his waist, and faithfulness the belt of his loins.
23Is 11:6 The wolf shall dwell with the lamb, and the leopard shall lie down with the young goat, and the calf and the lion and the fattened calf together; and a little child shall lead them.
23Is 11:7 The cow and the bear shall graze; their young shall lie down together; and the lion shall eat straw like the ox.
23Is 11:8 The nursing child shall play over the hole of the cobra, and the weaned child shall put his hand on the adder's den.
23Is 11:9 They shall not hurt or destroy in all my holy mountain; for the earth shall be full of the knowledge of the LORD as the waters cover the sea.
23Is 11:10 In that day the root of Jesse, who shall stand as a signal for the peoples--of him shall the nations inquire, and his resting place shall be glorious.
23Is 11:11 In that day the Lord will extend his hand yet a second time to recover the remnant that remains of his people, from Assyria, from Egypt, from Pathros, from Cush, from Elam, from Shinar, from Hamath, and from the coastlands of the sea.
23Is 11:12 He will raise a signal for the nations and will assemble the banished of Israel, and gather the dispersed of Judah from the four corners of the earth.
23Is 11:13 The jealousy of Ephraim shall depart, and those who harass Judah shall be cut off; Ephraim shall not be jealous of Judah, and Judah shall not harass Ephraim.
23Is 11:14 But they shall swoop down on the shoulder of the Philistines in the west, and together they shall plunder the people of the east. They shall put out their hand against Edom and Moab, and the Ammonites shall obey them.
23Is 11:15 And the LORD will utterly destroy the tongue of the Sea of Egypt, and will wave his hand over the River with his scorching breath, and strike it into seven channels, and he will lead people across in sandals.
23Is 11:16 And there will be a highway from Assyria for the remnant that remains of his people, as there was for Israel when they came up from the land of Egypt.
23Is 12:1 You will say in that day: "I will give thanks to you, O LORD, for though you were angry with me, your anger turned away, that you might comfort me.
23Is 12:2 "Behold, God is my salvation; I will trust, and will not be afraid; for the LORD GOD is my strength and my song, and he has become my salvation."
23Is 12:3 With joy you will draw water from the wells of salvation.
23Is 12:4 And you will say in that day: "Give thanks to the LORD, call upon his name, make known his deeds among the peoples, proclaim that his name is exalted.
23Is 12:5 "Sing praises to the LORD, for he has done gloriously; let this be made known in all the earth.
23Is 12:6 Shout, and sing for joy, O inhabitant of Zion, for great in your midst is the Holy One of Israel."
23Is 13:1 The oracle concerning Babylon which Isaiah the son of Amoz saw.
23Is 13:2 On a bare hill raise a signal; cry aloud to them; wave the hand for them to enter the gates of the nobles.
23Is 13:3 I myself have commanded my consecrated ones, and have summoned my mighty men to execute my anger, my proudly exulting ones.
23Is 13:4 The sound of a tumult is on the mountains as of a great multitude! The sound of an uproar of kingdoms, of nations gathering together! The LORD of hosts is mustering a host for battle.
23Is 13:5 They come from a distant land, from the end of the heavens, the LORD and the weapons of his indignation, to destroy the whole land.
23Is 13:6 Wail, for the day of the LORD is near; as destruction from the Almighty it will come!
23Is 13:7 Therefore all hands will be feeble, and every human heart will melt.
23Is 13:8 They will be dismayed: pangs and agony will seize them; they will be in anguish like a woman in labor. They will look aghast at one another; their faces will be aflame.
23Is 13:9 Behold, the day of the LORD comes, cruel, with wrath and fierce anger, to make the land a desolation and to destroy its sinners from it.
23Is 13:10 For the stars of the heavens and their constellations will not give their light; the sun will be dark at its rising, and the moon will not shed its light.
23Is 13:11 I will punish the world for its evil, and the wicked for their iniquity; I will put an end to the pomp of the arrogant, and lay low the pompous pride of the ruthless.
23Is 13:12 I will make people more rare than fine gold, and mankind than the gold of Ophir.
23Is 13:13 Therefore I will make the heavens tremble, and the earth will be shaken out of its place, at the wrath of the LORD of hosts in the day of his fierce anger.
23Is 13:14 And like a hunted gazelle, or like sheep with none to gather them, each will turn to his own people, and each will flee to his own land.
23Is 13:15 Whoever is found will be thrust through, and whoever is caught will fall by the sword.
23Is 13:16 Their infants will be dashed in pieces before their eyes; their houses will be plundered and their wives ravished.
23Is 13:17 Behold, I am stirring up the Medes against them, who have no regard for silver and do not delight in gold.
23Is 13:18 Their bows will slaughter the young men; they will have no mercy on the fruit of the womb; their eyes will not pity children.
23Is 13:19 And Babylon, the glory of kingdoms, the splendor and pomp of the Chaldeans, will be like Sodom and Gomorrah when God overthrew them.
23Is 13:20 It will never be inhabited or lived in for all generations; no Arab will pitch his tent there; no shepherds will make their flocks lie down there.
23Is 13:21 But wild animals will lie down there, and their houses will be full of howling creatures; there ostriches will dwell, and there wild goats will dance.
23Is 13:22 Hyenas will cry in its towers, and jackals in the pleasant palaces; its time is close at hand and its days will not be prolonged.
23Is 14:1 For the LORD will have compassion on Jacob and will again choose Israel, and will set them in their own land, and sojourners will join them and will attach themselves to the house of Jacob.
23Is 14:2 And the peoples will take them and bring them to their place, and the house of Israel will possess them in the LORD's land as male and female slaves. They will take captive those who were their captors, and rule over those who oppressed them.
23Is 14:3 When the LORD has given you rest from your pain and turmoil and the hard service with which you were made to serve,
23Is 14:4 you will take up this taunt against the king of Babylon: "How the oppressor has ceased, the insolent fury ceased!
23Is 14:5 The LORD has broken the staff of the wicked, the scepter of rulers,
23Is 14:6 that struck the peoples in wrath with unceasing blows, that ruled the nations in anger with unrelenting persecution.
23Is 14:7 The whole earth is at rest and quiet; they break forth into singing.
23Is 14:8 The cypresses rejoice at you, the cedars of Lebanon, saying, 'Since you were laid low, no woodcutter comes up against us.'
23Is 14:9 Sheol beneath is stirred up to meet you when you come; it rouses the shades to greet you, all who were leaders of the earth; it raises from their thrones all who were kings of the nations.
23Is 14:10 All of them will answer and say to you: 'You too have become as weak as we! You have become like us!'
23Is 14:11 Your pomp is brought down to Sheol, the sound of your harps; maggots are laid as a bed beneath you, and worms are your covers.
23Is 14:12 "How you are fallen from heaven, O Day Star, son of Dawn! How you are cut down to the ground, you who laid the nations low!
23Is 14:13 You said in your heart, 'I will ascend to heaven; above the stars of God I will set my throne on high; I will sit on the mount of assembly in the far reaches of the north;
23Is 14:14 I will ascend above the heights of the clouds; I will make myself like the Most High.'
23Is 14:15 But you are brought down to Sheol, to the far reaches of the pit.
23Is 14:16 Those who see you will stare at you and ponder over you: 'Is this the man who made the earth tremble, who shook kingdoms,
23Is 14:17 who made the world like a desert and overthrew its cities, who did not let his prisoners go home?'
23Is 14:18 All the kings of the nations lie in glory, each in his own tomb;
23Is 14:19 but you are cast out, away from your grave, like a loathed branch, clothed with the slain, those pierced by the sword, who go down to the stones of the pit, like a dead body trampled underfoot.
23Is 14:20 You will not be joined with them in burial, because you have destroyed your land, you have slain your people. "May the offspring of evildoers nevermore be named!
23Is 14:21 Prepare slaughter for his sons because of the guilt of their fathers, lest they rise and possess the earth, and fill the face of the world with cities."
23Is 14:22 "I will rise up against them," declares the LORD of hosts, "and will cut off from Babylon name and remnant, descendants and posterity," declares the LORD.
23Is 14:23 "And I will make it a possession of the hedgehog, and pools of water, and I will sweep it with the broom of destruction," declares the LORD of hosts.
23Is 14:24 The LORD of hosts has sworn: "As I have planned, so shall it be, and as I have purposed, so shall it stand,
23Is 14:25 that I will break the Assyrian in my land, and on my mountains trample him underfoot; and his yoke shall depart from them, and his burden from their shoulder."
23Is 14:26 This is the purpose that is purposed concerning the whole earth, and this is the hand that is stretched out over all the nations.
23Is 14:27 For the LORD of hosts has purposed, and who will annul it? His hand is stretched out, and who will turn it back?
23Is 14:28 In the year that King Ahaz died came this oracle:
23Is 14:29 Rejoice not, O Philistia, all of you, that the rod that struck you is broken, for from the serpent's root will come forth an adder, and its fruit will be a flying fiery serpent.
23Is 14:30 And the firstborn of the poor will graze, and the needy lie down in safety; but I will kill your root with famine, and your remnant it will slay.
23Is 14:31 Wail, O gate; cry out, O city; melt in fear, O Philistia, all of you! For smoke comes out of the north, and there is no straggler in his ranks.
23Is 14:32 What will one answer the messengers of the nation? "The LORD has founded Zion, and in her the afflicted of his people find refuge."
23Is 15:1 An oracle concerning Moab. Because Ar of Moab is laid waste in a night, Moab is undone; because Kir of Moab is laid waste in a night, Moab is undone.
23Is 15:2 He has gone up to the temple, and to Dibon, to the high places to weep; over Nebo and over Medeba Moab wails. On every head is baldness; every beard is shorn;
23Is 15:3 in the streets they wear sackcloth; on the housetops and in the squares everyone wails and melts in tears.
23Is 15:4 Heshbon and Elealeh cry out; their voice is heard as far as Jahaz; therefore the armed men of Moab cry aloud; his soul trembles.
23Is 15:5 My heart cries out for Moab; her fugitives flee to Zoar, to Eglath-shelishiyah. For at the ascent of Luhith they go up weeping; on the road to Horonaim they raise a cry of destruction;
23Is 15:6 the waters of Nimrim are a desolation; the grass is withered, the vegetation fails, the greenery is no more.
23Is 15:7 Therefore the abundance they have gained and what they have laid up they carry away over the Brook of the Willows.
23Is 15:8 For a cry has gone around the land of Moab; her wailing reaches to Eglaim; her wailing reaches to Beer-elim.
23Is 15:9 For the waters of Dibon are full of blood; for I will bring upon Dibon even more, a lion for those of Moab who escape, for the remnant of the land.
23Is 16:1 Send the lamb to the ruler of the land, from Sela, by way of the desert, to the mount of the daughter of Zion.
23Is 16:2 Like fleeing birds, like a scattered nest, so are the daughters of Moab at the fords of the Arnon.
23Is 16:3 "Give counsel; grant justice; make your shade like night at the height of noon; shelter the outcasts; do not reveal the fugitive;
23Is 16:4 let the outcasts of Moab sojourn among you; be a shelter to them from the destroyer. When the oppressor is no more, and destruction has ceased, and he who tramples underfoot has vanished from the land,
23Is 16:5 then a throne will be established in steadfast love, and on it will sit in faithfulness in the tent of David one who judges and seeks justice and is swift to do righteousness."
23Is 16:6 We have heard of the pride of Moab-- how proud he is!-- of his arrogance, his pride, and his insolence; in his idle boasting he is not right.
23Is 16:7 Therefore let Moab wail for Moab, let everyone wail. Mourn, utterly stricken, for the raisin cakes of Kir-hareseth.
23Is 16:8 For the fields of Heshbon languish, and the vine of Sibmah; the lords of the nations have struck down its branches, which reached to Jazer and strayed to the desert; its shoots spread abroad and passed over the sea.
23Is 16:9 Therefore I weep with the weeping of Jazer for the vine of Sibmah; I drench you with my tears, O Heshbon and Elealeh; for over your summer fruit and your harvest the shout has ceased.
23Is 16:10 And joy and gladness are taken away from the fruitful field, and in the vineyards no songs are sung, no cheers are raised; no treader treads out wine in the presses; I have put an end to the shouting.
23Is 16:11 Therefore my inner parts moan like a lyre for Moab, and my inmost self for Kir-hareseth.
23Is 16:12 And when Moab presents himself, when he wearies himself on the high place, when he comes to his sanctuary to pray, he will not prevail.
23Is 16:13 This is the word that the LORD spoke concerning Moab in the past.
23Is 16:14 But now the LORD has spoken, saying, "In three years, like the years of a hired worker, the glory of Moab will be brought into contempt, in spite of all his great multitude, and those who remain will be very few and feeble."
23Is 17:1 An oracle concerning Damascus. Behold, Damascus will cease to be a city and will become a heap of ruins.
23Is 17:2 The cities of Aroer are deserted; they will be for flocks, which will lie down, and none will make them afraid.
23Is 17:3 The fortress will disappear from Ephraim, and the kingdom from Damascus; and the remnant of Syria will be like the glory of the children of Israel, declares the LORD of hosts.
23Is 17:4 And in that day the glory of Jacob will be brought low, and the fat of his flesh will grow lean.
23Is 17:5 And it shall be as when the reaper gathers standing grain and his arm harvests the ears, and as when one gleans the ears of grain in the Valley of Rephaim.
23Is 17:6 Gleanings will be left in it, as when an olive tree is beaten-- two or three berries in the top of the highest bough, four or five on the branches of a fruit tree, declares the LORD God of Israel.
23Is 17:7 In that day man will look to his Maker, and his eyes will look on the Holy One of Israel.
23Is 17:8 He will not look to the altars, the work of his hands, and he will not look on what his own fingers have made, either the Asherim or the altars of incense.
23Is 17:9 In that day their strong cities will be like the deserted places of the wooded heights and the hilltops, which they deserted because of the children of Israel, and there will be desolation.
23Is 17:10 For you have forgotten the God of your salvation and have not remembered the Rock of your refuge; therefore, though you plant pleasant plants and sow the vine-branch of a stranger,
23Is 17:11 though you make them grow on the day that you plant them, and make them blossom in the morning that you sow, yet the harvest will flee away in a day of grief and incurable pain.
23Is 17:12 Ah, the thunder of many peoples; they thunder like the thundering of the sea! Ah, the roar of nations; they roar like the roaring of mighty waters!
23Is 17:13 The nations roar like the roaring of many waters, but he will rebuke them, and they will flee far away, chased like chaff on the mountains before the wind and whirling dust before the storm.
23Is 17:14 At evening time, behold, terror! Before morning, they are no more! This is the portion of those who loot us, and the lot of those who plunder us.
23Is 18:1 Ah, land of whirring wings that is beyond the rivers of Cush,
23Is 18:2 which sends ambassadors by the sea, in vessels of papyrus on the waters! Go, you swift messengers, to a nation, tall and smooth, to a people feared near and far, a nation mighty and conquering, whose land the rivers divide.
23Is 18:3 All you inhabitants of the world, you who dwell on the earth, when a signal is raised on the mountains, look! When a trumpet is blown, hear!
23Is 18:4 For thus the LORD said to me: "I will quietly look from my dwelling like clear heat in sunshine, like a cloud of dew in the heat of harvest."
23Is 18:5 For before the harvest, when the blossom is over, and the flower becomes a ripening grape, he cuts off the shoots with pruning hooks, and the spreading branches he lops off and clears away.
23Is 18:6 They shall all of them be left to the birds of prey of the mountains and to the beasts of the earth. And the birds of prey will summer on them, and all the beasts of the earth will winter on them.
23Is 18:7 At that time tribute will be brought to the LORD of hosts from a people tall and smooth, from a people feared near and far, a nation mighty and conquering, whose land the rivers divide, to Mount Zion, the place of the name of the LORD of hosts.
23Is 19:1 An oracle concerning Egypt. Behold, the LORD is riding on a swift cloud and comes to Egypt; and the idols of Egypt will tremble at his presence, and the heart of the Egyptians will melt within them.
23Is 19:2 And I will stir up Egyptians against Egyptians, and they will fight, each against another and each against his neighbor, city against city, kingdom against kingdom;
23Is 19:3 and the spirit of the Egyptians within them will be emptied out, and I will confound their counsel; and they will inquire of the idols and the sorcerers, and the mediums and the necromancers;
23Is 19:4 and I will give over the Egyptians into the hand of a hard master, and a fierce king will rule over them, declares the Lord GOD of hosts.
23Is 19:5 And the waters of the sea will be dried up, and the river will be dry and parched,
23Is 19:6 and its canals will become foul, and the branches of Egypt's Nile will diminish and dry up, reeds and rushes will rot away.
23Is 19:7 There will be bare places by the Nile, on the brink of the Nile, and all that is sown by the Nile will be parched, will be driven away, and will be no more.
23Is 19:8 The fishermen will mourn and lament, all who cast a hook in the Nile; and they will languish who spread nets on the water.
23Is 19:9 The workers in combed flax will be in despair, and the weavers of white cotton.
23Is 19:10 Those who are the pillars of the land will be crushed, and all who work for pay will be grieved.
23Is 19:11 The princes of Zoan are utterly foolish; the wisest counselors of Pharaoh give stupid counsel. How can you say to Pharaoh, "I am a son of the wise, a son of ancient kings"?
23Is 19:12 Where then are your wise men? Let them tell you that they might know what the LORD of hosts has purposed against Egypt.
23Is 19:13 The princes of Zoan have become fools, and the princes of Memphis are deluded; those who are the cornerstones of her tribes have made Egypt stagger.
23Is 19:14 The LORD has mingled within her a spirit of confusion, and they will make Egypt stagger in all its deeds, as a drunken man staggers in his vomit.
23Is 19:15 And there will be nothing for Egypt that head or tail, palm branch or reed, may do.
23Is 19:16 In that day the Egyptians will be like women, and tremble with fear before the hand that the LORD of hosts shakes over them.
23Is 19:17 And the land of Judah will become a terror to the Egyptians. Everyone to whom it is mentioned will fear because of the purpose that the LORD of hosts has purposed against them.
23Is 19:18 In that day there will be five cities in the land of Egypt that speak the language of Canaan and swear allegiance to the LORD of hosts. One of these will be called the City of Destruction.
23Is 19:19 In that day there will be an altar to the LORD in the midst of the land of Egypt, and a pillar to the LORD at its border.
23Is 19:20 It will be a sign and a witness to the LORD of hosts in the land of Egypt. When they cry to the LORD because of oppressors, he will send them a savior and defender, and deliver them.
23Is 19:21 And the LORD will make himself known to the Egyptians, and the Egyptians will know the LORD in that day and worship with sacrifice and offering, and they will make vows to the LORD and perform them.
23Is 19:22 And the LORD will strike Egypt, striking and healing, and they will return to the LORD, and he will listen to their pleas for mercy and heal them.
23Is 19:23 In that day there will be a highway from Egypt to Assyria, and Assyria will come into Egypt, and Egypt into Assyria, and the Egyptians will worship with the Assyrians.
23Is 19:24 In that day Israel will be the third with Egypt and Assyria, a blessing in the midst of the earth,
23Is 19:25 whom the LORD of hosts has blessed, saying, "Blessed be Egypt my people, and Assyria the work of my hands, and Israel my inheritance."
23Is 20:1 In the year that the commander in chief, who was sent by Sargon the king of Assyria, came to Ashdod and fought against it and captured it--
23Is 20:2 at that time the LORD spoke by Isaiah the son of Amoz, saying, "Go, and loose the sackcloth from your waist and take off your sandals from your feet," and he did so, walking naked and barefoot.
23Is 20:3 Then the LORD said, "As my servant Isaiah has walked naked and barefoot for three years as a sign and a portent against Egypt and Cush,
23Is 20:4 so shall the king of Assyria lead away the Egyptian captives and the Cushite exiles, both the young and the old, naked and barefoot, with buttocks uncovered, the nakedness of Egypt.
23Is 20:5 Then they shall be dismayed and ashamed because of Cush their hope and of Egypt their boast.
23Is 20:6 And the inhabitants of this coastland will say in that day, 'Behold, this is what has happened to those in whom we hoped and to whom we fled for help to be delivered from the king of Assyria! And we, how shall we escape?'"
23Is 21:1 The oracle concerning the wilderness of the sea. As whirlwinds in the Negeb sweep on, it comes from the wilderness, from a terrible land.
23Is 21:2 A stern vision is told to me; the traitor betrays, and the destroyer destroys. Go up, O Elam; lay siege, O Media; all the sighing she has caused I bring to an end.
23Is 21:3 Therefore my loins are filled with anguish; pangs have seized me, like the pangs of a woman in labor; I am bowed down so that I cannot hear; I am dismayed so that I cannot see.
23Is 21:4 My heart staggers; horror has appalled me; the twilight I longed for has been turned for me into trembling.
23Is 21:5 They prepare the table, they spread the rugs, they eat, they drink. Arise, O princes; oil the shield!
23Is 21:6 For thus the Lord said to me: "Go, set a watchman; let him announce what he sees.
23Is 21:7 When he sees riders, horsemen in pairs, riders on donkeys, riders on camels, let him listen diligently, very diligently."
23Is 21:8 Then he who saw cried out: "Upon a watchtower I stand, O Lord, continually by day, and at my post I am stationed whole nights.
23Is 21:9 And behold, here come riders, horsemen in pairs!" And he answered, "Fallen, fallen is Babylon; and all the carved images of her gods he has shattered to the ground."
23Is 21:10 O my threshed and winnowed one, what I have heard from the LORD of hosts, the God of Israel, I announce to you.
23Is 21:11 The oracle concerning Dumah. One is calling to me from Seir, "Watchman, what time of the night? Watchman, what time of the night?"
23Is 21:12 The watchman says: "Morning comes, and also the night. If you will inquire, inquire; come back again."
23Is 21:13 The oracle concerning Arabia. In the thickets in Arabia you will lodge, O caravans of Dedanites.
23Is 21:14 To the thirsty bring water; meet the fugitive with bread, O inhabitants of the land of Tema.
23Is 21:15 For they have fled from the swords, from the drawn sword, from the bent bow, and from the press of battle.
23Is 21:16 For thus the Lord said to me, "Within a year, according to the years of a hired worker, all the glory of Kedar will come to an end.
23Is 21:17 And the remainder of the archers of the mighty men of the sons of Kedar will be few, for the LORD, the God of Israel, has spoken."
23Is 22:1 The oracle concerning the valley of vision. What do you mean that you have gone up, all of you, to the housetops,
23Is 22:2 you who are full of shoutings, tumultuous city, exultant town? Your slain are not slain with the sword or dead in battle.
23Is 22:3 All your leaders have fled together; without the bow they were captured. All of you who were found were captured, though they had fled far away.
23Is 22:4 Therefore I said: "Look away from me; let me weep bitter tears; do not labor to comfort me concerning the destruction of the daughter of my people."
23Is 22:5 For the Lord GOD of hosts has a day of tumult and trampling and confusion in the valley of vision, a battering down of walls and a shouting to the mountains.
23Is 22:6 And Elam bore the quiver with chariots and horsemen, and Kir uncovered the shield.
23Is 22:7 Your choicest valleys were full of chariots, and the horsemen took their stand at the gates.
23Is 22:8 He has taken away the covering of Judah. In that day you looked to the weapons of the House of the Forest,
23Is 22:9 and you saw that the breaches of the city of David were many. You collected the waters of the lower pool,
23Is 22:10 and you counted the houses of Jerusalem, and you broke down the houses to fortify the wall.
23Is 22:11 You made a reservoir between the two walls for the water of the old pool. But you did not look to him who did it, or see him who planned it long ago.
23Is 22:12 In that day the Lord GOD of hosts called for weeping and mourning, for baldness and wearing sackcloth;
23Is 22:13 and behold, joy and gladness, killing oxen and slaughtering sheep, eating flesh and drinking wine. "Let us eat and drink, for tomorrow we die."
23Is 22:14 The LORD of hosts has revealed himself in my ears: "Surely this iniquity will not be atoned for you until you die," says the Lord GOD of hosts.
23Is 22:15 Thus says the Lord GOD of hosts, "Come, go to this steward, to Shebna, who is over the household, and say to him:
23Is 22:16 What have you to do here, and whom have you here, that you have cut out here a tomb for yourself, you who cut out a tomb on the height and carve a dwelling for yourself in the rock?
23Is 22:17 Behold, the LORD will hurl you away violently, O you strong man. He will seize firm hold on you
23Is 22:18 and whirl you around and around, and throw you like a ball into a wide land. There you shall die, and there shall be your glorious chariots, you shame of your master's house.
23Is 22:19 I will thrust you from your office, and you will be pulled down from your station.
23Is 22:20 In that day I will call my servant Eliakim the son of Hilkiah,
23Is 22:21 and I will clothe him with your robe, and will bind your sash on him, and will commit your authority to his hand. And he shall be a father to the inhabitants of Jerusalem and to the house of Judah.
23Is 22:22 And I will place on his shoulder the key of the house of David. He shall open, and none shall shut; and he shall shut, and none shall open.
23Is 22:23 And I will fasten him like a peg in a secure place, and he will become a throne of honor to his father's house.
23Is 22:24 And they will hang on him the whole honor of his father's house, the offspring and issue, every small vessel, from the cups to all the flagons.
23Is 22:25 In that day, declares the LORD of hosts, the peg that was fastened in a secure place will give way, and it will be cut down and fall, and the load that was on it will be cut off, for the LORD has spoken."
23Is 23:1 The oracle concerning Tyre. Wail, O ships of Tarshish, for Tyre is laid waste, without house or harbor! From the land of Cyprus it is revealed to them.
23Is 23:2 Be still, O inhabitants of the coast; the merchants of Sidon, who cross the sea, have filled you.
23Is 23:3 And on many waters your revenue was the grain of Shihor, the harvest of the Nile; you were the merchant of the nations.
23Is 23:4 Be ashamed, O Sidon, for the sea has spoken, the stronghold of the sea, saying: "I have neither labored nor given birth, I have neither reared young men nor brought up young women."
23Is 23:5 When the report comes to Egypt, they will be in anguish over the report about Tyre.
23Is 23:6 Cross over to Tarshish; wail, O inhabitants of the coast!
23Is 23:7 Is this your exultant city whose origin is from days of old, whose feet carried her to settle far away?
23Is 23:8 Who has purposed this against Tyre, the bestower of crowns, whose merchants were princes, whose traders were the honored of the earth?
23Is 23:9 The LORD of hosts has purposed it, to defile the pompous pride of all glory, to dishonor all the honored of the earth.
23Is 23:10 Cross over your land like the Nile, O daughter of Tarshish; there is no restraint anymore.
23Is 23:11 He has stretched out his hand over the sea; he has shaken the kingdoms; the LORD has given command concerning Canaan to destroy its strongholds.
23Is 23:12 And he said: "You will no more exult, O oppressed virgin daughter of Sidon; arise, cross over to Cyprus, even there you will have no rest."
23Is 23:13 Behold the land of the Chaldeans! This is the people that was not; Assyria destined it for wild beasts. They erected their siege towers, they stripped her palaces bare, they made her a ruin.
23Is 23:14 Wail, O ships of Tarshish, for your stronghold is laid waste.
23Is 23:15 In that day Tyre will be forgotten for seventy years, like the days of one king. At the end of seventy years, it will happen to Tyre as in the song of the prostitute:
23Is 23:16 "Take a harp; go about the city, O forgotten prostitute! Make sweet melody; sing many songs, that you may be remembered."
23Is 23:17 At the end of seventy years, the LORD will visit Tyre, and she will return to her wages and will prostitute herself with all the kingdoms of the world on the face of the earth.
23Is 23:18 Her merchandise and her wages will be holy to the LORD. It will not be stored or hoarded, but her merchandise will supply abundant food and fine clothing for those who dwell before the LORD.
23Is 24:1 Behold, the LORD will empty the earth and make it desolate, and he will twist its surface and scatter its inhabitants.
23Is 24:2 And it shall be, as with the people, so with the priest; as with the slave, so with his master; as with the maid, so with her mistress; as with the buyer, so with the seller; as with the lender, so with the borrower; as with the creditor, so with the debtor.
23Is 24:3 The earth shall be utterly empty and utterly plundered; for the LORD has spoken this word.
23Is 24:4 The earth mourns and withers; the world languishes and withers; the highest people of the earth languish.
23Is 24:5 The earth lies defiled under its inhabitants; for they have transgressed the laws, violated the statutes, broken the everlasting covenant.
23Is 24:6 Therefore a curse devours the earth, and its inhabitants suffer for their guilt; therefore the inhabitants of the earth are scorched, and few men are left.
23Is 24:7 The wine mourns, the vine languishes, all the merry-hearted sigh.
23Is 24:8 The mirth of the tambourines is stilled, the noise of the jubilant has ceased, the mirth of the lyre is stilled.
23Is 24:9 No more do they drink wine with singing; strong drink is bitter to those who drink it.
23Is 24:10 The wasted city is broken down; every house is shut up so that none can enter.
23Is 24:11 There is an outcry in the streets for lack of wine; all joy has grown dark; the gladness of the earth is banished.
23Is 24:12 Desolation is left in the city; the gates are battered into ruins.
23Is 24:13 For thus it shall be in the midst of the earth among the nations, as when an olive tree is beaten, as at the gleaning when the grape harvest is done.
23Is 24:14 They lift up their voices, they sing for joy; over the majesty of the LORD they shout from the west.
23Is 24:15 Therefore in the east give glory to the LORD; in the coastlands of the sea, give glory to the name of the LORD, the God of Israel.
23Is 24:16 From the ends of the earth we hear songs of praise, of glory to the Righteous One. But I say, "I waste away, I waste away. Woe is me! For the traitors have betrayed, with betrayal the traitors have betrayed."
23Is 24:17 Terror and the pit and the snare are upon you, O inhabitant of the earth!
23Is 24:18 He who flees at the sound of the terror shall fall into the pit, and he who climbs out of the pit shall be caught in the snare. For the windows of heaven are opened, and the foundations of the earth tremble.
23Is 24:19 The earth is utterly broken, the earth is split apart, the earth is violently shaken.
23Is 24:20 The earth staggers like a drunken man; it sways like a hut; its transgression lies heavy upon it, and it falls, and will not rise again.
23Is 24:21 On that day the LORD will punish the host of heaven, in heaven, and the kings of the earth, on the earth.
23Is 24:22 They will be gathered together as prisoners in a pit; they will be shut up in a prison, and after many days they will be punished.
23Is 24:23 Then the moon will be confounded and the sun ashamed, for the LORD of hosts reigns on Mount Zion and in Jerusalem, and his glory will be before his elders.
23Is 25:1 O LORD, you are my God; I will exalt you; I will praise your name, for you have done wonderful things, plans formed of old, faithful and sure.
23Is 25:2 For you have made the city a heap, the fortified city a ruin; the foreigners' palace is a city no more; it will never be rebuilt.
23Is 25:3 Therefore strong peoples will glorify you; cities of ruthless nations will fear you.
23Is 25:4 For you have been a stronghold to the poor, a stronghold to the needy in his distress, a shelter from the storm and a shade from the heat; for the breath of the ruthless is like a storm against a wall,
23Is 25:5 like heat in a dry place. You subdue the noise of the foreigners; as heat by the shade of a cloud, so the song of the ruthless is put down.
23Is 25:6 On this mountain the LORD of hosts will make for all peoples a feast of rich food, a feast of well-aged wine, of rich food full of marrow, of aged wine well refined.
23Is 25:7 And he will swallow up on this mountain the covering that is cast over all peoples, the veil that is spread over all nations.
23Is 25:8 He will swallow up death forever; and the Lord GOD will wipe away tears from all faces, and the reproach of his people he will take away from all the earth, for the LORD has spoken.
23Is 25:9 It will be said on that day, "Behold, this is our God; we have waited for him, that he might save us. This is the LORD; we have waited for him; let us be glad and rejoice in his salvation."
23Is 25:10 For the hand of the LORD will rest on this mountain, and Moab shall be trampled down in his place, as straw is trampled down in a dunghill.
23Is 25:11 And he will spread out his hands in the midst of it as a swimmer spreads his hands out to swim, but the LORD will lay low his pompous pride together with the skill of his hands.
23Is 25:12 And the high fortifications of his walls he will bring down, lay low, and cast to the ground, to the dust.
23Is 26:1 In that day this song will be sung in the land of Judah: "We have a strong city; he sets up salvation as walls and bulwarks.
23Is 26:2 Open the gates, that the righteous nation that keeps faith may enter in.
23Is 26:3 You keep him in perfect peace whose mind is stayed on you, because he trusts in you.
23Is 26:4 Trust in the LORD forever, for the LORD GOD is an everlasting rock.
23Is 26:5 For he has humbled the inhabitants of the height, the lofty city. He lays it low, lays it low to the ground, casts it to the dust.
23Is 26:6 The foot tramples it, the feet of the poor, the steps of the needy."
23Is 26:7 The path of the righteous is level; you make level the way of the righteous.
23Is 26:8 In the path of your judgments, O LORD, we wait for you; your name and remembrance are the desire of our soul.
23Is 26:9 My soul yearns for you in the night; my spirit within me earnestly seeks you. For when your judgments are in the earth, the inhabitants of the world learn righteousness.
23Is 26:10 If favor is shown to the wicked, he does not learn righteousness; in the land of uprightness he deals corruptly and does not see the majesty of the LORD.
23Is 26:11 O LORD, your hand is lifted up, but they do not see it. Let them see your zeal for your people, and be ashamed. Let the fire for your adversaries consume them.
23Is 26:12 O LORD, you will ordain peace for us, for you have indeed done for us all our works.
23Is 26:13 O LORD our God, other lords besides you have ruled over us, but your name alone we bring to remembrance.
23Is 26:14 They are dead, they will not live; they are shades, they will not arise; to that end you have visited them with destruction and wiped out all remembrance of them.
23Is 26:15 But you have increased the nation, O LORD, you have increased the nation; you are glorified; you have enlarged all the borders of the land.
23Is 26:16 O LORD, in distress they sought you; they poured out a whispered prayer when your discipline was upon them.
23Is 26:17 Like a pregnant woman who writhes and cries out in her pangs when she is near to giving birth, so were we because of you, O LORD;
23Is 26:18 we were pregnant, we writhed, but we have given birth to wind. We have accomplished no deliverance in the earth, and the inhabitants of the world have not fallen.
23Is 26:19 Your dead shall live; their bodies shall rise. You who dwell in the dust, awake and sing for joy! For your dew is a dew of light, and the earth will give birth to the dead.
23Is 26:20 Come, my people, enter your chambers, and shut your doors behind you; hide yourselves for a little while until the fury has passed by.
23Is 26:21 For behold, the LORD is coming out from his place to punish the inhabitants of the earth for their iniquity, and the earth will disclose the blood shed on it, and will no more cover its slain.
23Is 27:1 In that day the LORD with his hard and great and strong sword will punish Leviathan the fleeing serpent, Leviathan the twisting serpent, and he will slay the dragon that is in the sea.
23Is 27:2 In that day, "A pleasant vineyard, sing of it!
23Is 27:3 I, the LORD, am its keeper; every moment I water it. Lest anyone punish it, I keep it night and day;
23Is 27:4 I have no wrath. Would that I had thorns and briers to battle! I would march against them, I would burn them up together.
23Is 27:5 Or let them lay hold of my protection, let them make peace with me, let them make peace with me."
23Is 27:6 In days to come Jacob shall take root, Israel shall blossom and put forth shoots and fill the whole world with fruit.
23Is 27:7 Has he struck them as he struck those who struck them? Or have they been slain as their slayers were slain?
23Is 27:8 Measure by measure, by exile you contended with them; he removed them with his fierce breath in the day of the east wind.
23Is 27:9 Therefore by this the guilt of Jacob will be atoned for, and this will be the full fruit of the removal of his sin: when he makes all the stones of the altars like chalkstones crushed to pieces, no Asherim or incense altars will remain standing.
23Is 27:10 For the fortified city is solitary, a habitation deserted and forsaken, like the wilderness; there the calf grazes; there it lies down and strips its branches.
23Is 27:11 When its boughs are dry, they are broken; women come and make a fire of them. For this is a people without discernment; therefore he who made them will not have compassion on them; he who formed them will show them no favor.
23Is 27:12 In that day from the river Euphrates to the Brook of Egypt the LORD will thresh out the grain, and you will be gleaned one by one, O people of Israel.
23Is 27:13 And in that day a great trumpet will be blown, and those who were lost in the land of Assyria and those who were driven out to the land of Egypt will come and worship the LORD on the holy mountain at Jerusalem.
23Is 28:1 Ah, the proud crown of the drunkards of Ephraim, and the fading flower of its glorious beauty, which is on the head of the rich valley of those overcome with wine!
23Is 28:2 Behold, the Lord has one who is mighty and strong; like a storm of hail, a destroying tempest, like a storm of mighty, overflowing waters, he casts down to the earth with his hand.
23Is 28:3 The proud crown of the drunkards of Ephraim will be trodden underfoot;
23Is 28:4 and the fading flower of its glorious beauty, which is on the head of the rich valley, will be like a first-ripe fig before the summer: when someone sees it, he swallows it as soon as it is in his hand.
23Is 28:5 In that day the LORD of hosts will be a crown of glory, and a diadem of beauty, to the remnant of his people,
23Is 28:6 and a spirit of justice to him who sits in judgment, and strength to those who turn back the battle at the gate.
23Is 28:7 These also reel with wine and stagger with strong drink; the priest and the prophet reel with strong drink, they are swallowed by wine, they stagger with strong drink, they reel in vision, they stumble in giving judgment.
23Is 28:8 For all tables are full of filthy vomit, with no space left.
23Is 28:9 "To whom will he teach knowledge, and to whom will he explain the message? Those who are weaned from the milk, those taken from the breast?
23Is 28:10 For it is precept upon precept, precept upon precept, line upon line, line upon line, here a little, there a little."
23Is 28:11 For by people of strange lips and with a foreign tongue the LORD will speak to this people,
23Is 28:12 to whom he has said, "This is rest; give rest to the weary; and this is repose"; yet they would not hear.
23Is 28:13 And the word of the LORD will be to them precept upon precept, precept upon precept, line upon line, line upon line, here a little, there a little, that they may go, and fall backward, and be broken, and snared, and taken.
23Is 28:14 Therefore hear the word of the LORD, you scoffers, who rule this people in Jerusalem!
23Is 28:15 Because you have said, "We have made a covenant with death, and with Sheol we have an agreement, when the overwhelming whip passes through it will not come to us, for we have made lies our refuge, and in falsehood we have taken shelter";
23Is 28:16 therefore thus says the Lord GOD, "Behold, I am the one who has laid as a foundation in Zion, a stone, a tested stone, a precious cornerstone, of a sure foundation: 'Whoever believes will not be in haste.'
23Is 28:17 And I will make justice the line, and righteousness the plumb line; and hail will sweep away the refuge of lies, and waters will overwhelm the shelter."
23Is 28:18 Then your covenant with death will be annulled, and your agreement with Sheol will not stand; when the overwhelming scourge passes through, you will be beaten down by it.
23Is 28:19 As often as it passes through it will take you; for morning by morning it will pass through, by day and by night; and it will be sheer terror to understand the message.
23Is 28:20 For the bed is too short to stretch oneself on, and the covering too narrow to wrap oneself in.
23Is 28:21 For the LORD will rise up as on Mount Perazim; as in the Valley of Gibeon he will be roused; to do his deed--strange is his deed! and to work his work--alien is his work!
23Is 28:22 Now therefore do not scoff, lest your bonds be made strong; for I have heard a decree of destruction from the Lord GOD of hosts against the whole land.
23Is 28:23 Give ear, and hear my voice; give attention, and hear my speech.
23Is 28:24 Does he who plows for sowing plow continually? Does he continually open and harrow his ground?
23Is 28:25 When he has leveled its surface, does he not scatter dill, sow cumin, and put in wheat in rows and barley in its proper place, and emmer as the border?
23Is 28:26 For he is rightly instructed; his God teaches him.
23Is 28:27 Dill is not threshed with a threshing sledge, nor is a cart wheel rolled over cumin, but dill is beaten out with a stick, and cumin with a rod.
23Is 28:28 Does one crush grain for bread? No, he does not thresh it forever; when he drives his cart wheel over it with his horses, he does not crush it.
23Is 28:29 This also comes from the LORD of hosts; he is wonderful in counsel and excellent in wisdom.
23Is 29:1 Ah, Ariel, Ariel, the city where David encamped! Add year to year; let the feasts run their round.
23Is 29:2 Yet I will distress Ariel, and there shall be moaning and lamentation, and she shall be to me like an Ariel.
23Is 29:3 And I will encamp against you all around, and will besiege you with towers and I will raise siegeworks against you.
23Is 29:4 And you will be brought low; from the earth you shall speak, and from the dust your speech will be bowed down; your voice shall come from the ground like the voice of a ghost, and from the dust your speech shall whisper.
23Is 29:5 But the multitude of your foreign foes shall be like small dust, and the multitude of the ruthless like passing chaff. And in an instant, suddenly,
23Is 29:6 you will be visited by the LORD of hosts with thunder and with earthquake and great noise, with whirlwind and tempest, and the flame of a devouring fire.
23Is 29:7 And the multitude of all the nations that fight against Ariel, all that fight against her and her stronghold and distress her, shall be like a dream, a vision of the night.
23Is 29:8 As when a hungry man dreams he is eating and awakes with his hunger not satisfied, or as when a thirsty man dreams he is drinking and awakes faint, with his thirst not quenched, so shall the multitude of all the nations be that fight against Mount Zion.
23Is 29:9 Astonish yourselves and be astonished; blind yourselves and be blind! Be drunk, but not with wine; stagger, but not with strong drink!
23Is 29:10 For the LORD has poured out upon you a spirit of deep sleep, and has closed your eyes (the prophets), and covered your heads (the seers).
23Is 29:11 And the vision of all this has become to you like the words of a book that is sealed. When men give it to one who can read, saying, "Read this," he says, "I cannot, for it is sealed."
23Is 29:12 And when they give the book to one who cannot read, saying, "Read this," he says, "I cannot read."
23Is 29:13 And the Lord said: "Because this people draw near with their mouth and honor me with their lips, while their hearts are far from me, and their fear of me is a commandment taught by men,
23Is 29:14 therefore, behold, I will again do wonderful things with this people, with wonder upon wonder; and the wisdom of their wise men shall perish, and the discernment of their discerning men shall be hidden."
23Is 29:15 Ah, you who hide deep from the LORD your counsel, whose deeds are in the dark, and who say, "Who sees us? Who knows us?"
23Is 29:16 You turn things upside down! Shall the potter be regarded as the clay, that the thing made should say of its maker, "He did not make me"; or the thing formed say of him who formed it, "He has no understanding"?
23Is 29:17 Is it not yet a very little while until Lebanon shall be turned into a fruitful field, and the fruitful field shall be regarded as a forest?
23Is 29:18 In that day the deaf shall hear the words of a book, and out of their gloom and darkness the eyes of the blind shall see.
23Is 29:19 The meek shall obtain fresh joy in the LORD, and the poor among mankind shall exult in the Holy One of Israel.
23Is 29:20 For the ruthless shall come to nothing and the scoffer cease, and all who watch to do evil shall be cut off,
23Is 29:21 who by a word make a man out to be an offender, and lay a snare for him who reproves in the gate, and with an empty plea turn aside him who is in the right.
23Is 29:22 Therefore thus says the LORD, who redeemed Abraham, concerning the house of Jacob: "Jacob shall no more be ashamed, no more shall his face grow pale.
23Is 29:23 For when he sees his children, the work of my hands, in his midst, they will sanctify my name; they will sanctify the Holy One of Jacob and will stand in awe of the God of Israel.
23Is 29:24 And those who go astray in spirit will come to understanding, and those who murmur will accept instruction."
23Is 30:1 "Ah, stubborn children," declares the LORD, "who carry out a plan, but not mine, and who make an alliance, but not of my Spirit, that they may add sin to sin;
23Is 30:2 who set out to go down to Egypt, without asking for my direction, to take refuge in the protection of Pharaoh and to seek shelter in the shadow of Egypt!
23Is 30:3 Therefore shall the protection of Pharaoh turn to your shame, and the shelter in the shadow of Egypt to your humiliation.
23Is 30:4 For though his officials are at Zoan and his envoys reach Hanes,
23Is 30:5 everyone comes to shame through a people that cannot profit them, that brings neither help nor profit, but shame and disgrace."
23Is 30:6 An oracle on the beasts of the Negeb. Through a land of trouble and anguish, from where come the lioness and the lion, the adder and the flying fiery serpent, they carry their riches on the backs of donkeys, and their treasures on the humps of camels, to a people that cannot profit them.
23Is 30:7 Egypt's help is worthless and empty; therefore I have called her "Rahab who sits still."
23Is 30:8 And now, go, write it before them on a tablet and inscribe it in a book, that it may be for the time to come as a witness forever.
23Is 30:9 For they are a rebellious people, lying children, children unwilling to hear the instruction of the LORD;
23Is 30:10 who say to the seers, "Do not see," and to the prophets, "Do not prophesy to us what is right; speak to us smooth things, prophesy illusions,
23Is 30:11 leave the way, turn aside from the path, let us hear no more about the Holy One of Israel."
23Is 30:12 Therefore thus says the Holy One of Israel, "Because you despise this word and trust in oppression and perverseness and rely on them,
23Is 30:13 therefore this iniquity shall be to you like a breach in a high wall, bulging out, and about to collapse, whose breaking comes suddenly, in an instant;
23Is 30:14 and its breaking is like that of a potter's vessel that is smashed so ruthlessly that among its fragments not a shard is found with which to take fire from the hearth, or to dip up water out of the cistern."
23Is 30:15 For thus said the Lord GOD, the Holy One of Israel, "In returning and rest you shall be saved; in quietness and in trust shall be your strength." But you were unwilling,
23Is 30:16 and you said, "No! We will flee upon horses"; therefore you shall flee away; and, "We will ride upon swift steeds"; therefore your pursuers shall be swift.
23Is 30:17 A thousand shall flee at the threat of one; at the threat of five you shall flee, till you are left like a flagstaff on the top of a mountain, like a signal on a hill.
23Is 30:18 Therefore the LORD waits to be gracious to you, and therefore he exalts himself to show mercy to you. For the LORD is a God of justice; blessed are all those who wait for him.
23Is 30:19 For a people shall dwell in Zion, in Jerusalem; you shall weep no more. He will surely be gracious to you at the sound of your cry. As soon as he hears it, he answers you.
23Is 30:20 And though the Lord give you the bread of adversity and the water of affliction, yet your Teacher will not hide himself anymore, but your eyes shall see your Teacher.
23Is 30:21 And your ears shall hear a word behind you, saying, "This is the way, walk in it," when you turn to the right or when you turn to the left.
23Is 30:22 Then you will defile your carved idols overlaid with silver and your gold-plated metal images. You will scatter them as unclean things. You will say to them, "Be gone!"
23Is 30:23 And he will give rain for the seed with which you sow the ground, and bread, the produce of the ground, which will be rich and plenteous. In that day your livestock will graze in large pastures,
23Is 30:24 and the oxen and the donkeys that work the ground will eat seasoned fodder, which has been winnowed with shovel and fork.
23Is 30:25 And on every lofty mountain and every high hill there will be brooks running with water, in the day of the great slaughter, when the towers fall.
23Is 30:26 Moreover, the light of the moon will be as the light of the sun, and the light of the sun will be sevenfold, as the light of seven days, in the day when the LORD binds up the brokenness of his people, and heals the wounds inflicted by his blow.
23Is 30:27 Behold, the name of the LORD comes from afar, burning with his anger, and in thick rising smoke; his lips are full of fury, and his tongue is like a devouring fire;
23Is 30:28 his breath is like an overflowing stream that reaches up to the neck; to sift the nations with the sieve of destruction, and to place on the jaws of the peoples a bridle that leads astray.
23Is 30:29 You shall have a song as in the night when a holy feast is kept, and gladness of heart, as when one sets out to the sound of the flute to go to the mountain of the LORD, to the Rock of Israel.
23Is 30:30 And the LORD will cause his majestic voice to be heard and the descending blow of his arm to be seen, in furious anger and a flame of devouring fire, with a cloudburst and storm and hailstones.
23Is 30:31 The Assyrians will be terror-stricken at the voice of the LORD, when he strikes with his rod.
23Is 30:32 And every stroke of the appointed staff that the LORD lays on them will be to the sound of tambourines and lyres. Battling with brandished arm, he will fight with them.
23Is 30:33 For a burning place has long been prepared; indeed, for the king it is made ready, its pyre made deep and wide, with fire and wood in abundance; the breath of the LORD, like a stream of sulfur, kindles it.
23Is 31:1 Woe to those who go down to Egypt for help and rely on horses, who trust in chariots because they are many and in horsemen because they are very strong, but do not look to the Holy One of Israel or consult the LORD!
23Is 31:2 And yet he is wise and brings disaster; he does not call back his words, but will arise against the house of the evildoers and against the helpers of those who work iniquity.
23Is 31:3 The Egyptians are man, and not God, and their horses are flesh, and not spirit. When the LORD stretches out his hand, the helper will stumble, and he who is helped will fall, and they will all perish together.
23Is 31:4 For thus the LORD said to me, "As a lion or a young lion growls over his prey, and when a band of shepherds is called out against him he is not terrified by their shouting or daunted at their noise, so the LORD of hosts will come down to fight on Mount Zion and on its hill.
23Is 31:5 Like birds hovering, so the LORD of hosts will protect Jerusalem; he will protect and deliver it; he will spare and rescue it."
23Is 31:6 Turn to him from whom people have deeply revolted, O children of Israel.
23Is 31:7 For in that day everyone shall cast away his idols of silver and his idols of gold, which your hands have sinfully made for you.
23Is 31:8 "And the Assyrian shall fall by a sword, not of man; and a sword, not of man, shall devour him; and he shall flee from the sword, and his young men shall be put to forced labor.
23Is 31:9 His rock shall pass away in terror, and his officers desert the standard in panic," declares the LORD, whose fire is in Zion, and whose furnace is in Jerusalem.
23Is 32:1 Behold, a king will reign in righteousness, and princes will rule in justice.
23Is 32:2 Each will be like a hiding place from the wind, a shelter from the storm, like streams of water in a dry place, like the shade of a great rock in a weary land.
23Is 32:3 Then the eyes of those who see will not be closed, and the ears of those who hear will give attention.
23Is 32:4 The heart of the hasty will understand and know, and the tongue of the stammerers will hasten to speak distinctly.
23Is 32:5 The fool will no more be called noble, nor the scoundrel said to be honorable.
23Is 32:6 For the fool speaks folly, and his heart is busy with iniquity, to practice ungodliness, to utter error concerning the LORD, to leave the craving of the hungry unsatisfied, and to deprive the thirsty of drink.
23Is 32:7 As for the scoundrel--his devices are evil; he plans wicked schemes to ruin the poor with lying words, even when the plea of the needy is right.
23Is 32:8 But he who is noble plans noble things, and on noble things he stands.
23Is 32:9 Rise up, you women who are at ease, hear my voice; you complacent daughters, give ear to my speech.
23Is 32:10 In little more than a year you will shudder, you complacent women; for the grape harvest fails, the fruit harvest will not come.
23Is 32:11 Tremble, you women who are at ease, shudder, you complacent ones; strip, and make yourselves bare, and tie sackcloth around your waist.
23Is 32:12 Beat your breasts for the pleasant fields, for the fruitful vine,
23Is 32:13 for the soil of my people growing up in thorns and briers, yes, for all the joyous houses in the exultant city.
23Is 32:14 For the palace is forsaken, the populous city deserted; the hill and the watchtower will become dens forever, a joy of wild donkeys, a pasture of flocks;
23Is 32:15 until the Spirit is poured upon us from on high, and the wilderness becomes a fruitful field, and the fruitful field is deemed a forest.
23Is 32:16 Then justice will dwell in the wilderness, and righteousness abide in the fruitful field.
23Is 32:17 And the effect of righteousness will be peace, and the result of righteousness, quietness and trust forever.
23Is 32:18 My people will abide in a peaceful habitation, in secure dwellings, and in quiet resting places.
23Is 32:19 And it will hail when the forest falls down, and the city will be utterly laid low.
23Is 32:20 Happy are you who sow beside all waters, who let the feet of the ox and the donkey range free.
23Is 33:1 Ah, you destroyer, who yourself have not been destroyed, you traitor, whom none has betrayed! When you have ceased to destroy, you will be destroyed; and when you have finished betraying, they will betray you.
23Is 33:2 O LORD, be gracious to us; we wait for you. Be our arm every morning, our salvation in the time of trouble.
23Is 33:3 At the tumultuous noise peoples flee; when you lift yourself up, nations are scattered,
23Is 33:4 and your spoil is gathered as the caterpillar gathers; as locusts leap, it is leapt upon.
23Is 33:5 The LORD is exalted, for he dwells on high; he will fill Zion with justice and righteousness,
23Is 33:6 and he will be the stability of your times, abundance of salvation, wisdom, and knowledge; the fear of the LORD is Zion's treasure.
23Is 33:7 Behold, their heroes cry in the streets; the envoys of peace weep bitterly.
23Is 33:8 The highways lie waste; the traveler ceases. Covenants are broken; cities are despised; there is no regard for man.
23Is 33:9 The land mourns and languishes; Lebanon is confounded and withers away; Sharon is like a desert, and Bashan and Carmel shake off their leaves.
23Is 33:10 "Now I will arise," says the LORD, "now I will lift myself up; now I will be exalted.
23Is 33:11 You conceive chaff; you give birth to stubble; your breath is a fire that will consume you.
23Is 33:12 And the peoples will be as if burned to lime, like thorns cut down, that are burned in the fire."
23Is 33:13 Hear, you who are far off, what I have done; and you who are near, acknowledge my might.
23Is 33:14 The sinners in Zion are afraid; trembling has seized the godless: "Who among us can dwell with the consuming fire? Who among us can dwell with everlasting burnings?"
23Is 33:15 He who walks righteously and speaks uprightly, who despises the gain of oppressions, who shakes his hands, lest they hold a bribe, who stops his ears from hearing of bloodshed and shuts his eyes from looking on evil,
23Is 33:16 he will dwell on the heights; his place of defense will be the fortresses of rocks; his bread will be given him; his water will be sure.
23Is 33:17 Your eyes will behold the king in his beauty; they will see a land that stretches afar.
23Is 33:18 Your heart will muse on the terror: "Where is he who counted, where is he who weighed the tribute? Where is he who counted the towers?"
23Is 33:19 You will see no more the insolent people, the people of an obscure speech that you cannot comprehend, stammering in a tongue that you cannot understand.
23Is 33:20 Behold Zion, the city of our appointed feasts! Your eyes will see Jerusalem, an untroubled habitation, an immovable tent, whose stakes will never be plucked up, nor will any of its cords be broken.
23Is 33:21 But there the LORD in majesty will be for us a place of broad rivers and streams, where no galley with oars can go, nor majestic ship can pass.
23Is 33:22 For the LORD is our judge; the LORD is our lawgiver; the LORD is our king; he will save us.
23Is 33:23 Your cords hang loose; they cannot hold the mast firm in its place or keep the sail spread out. Then prey and spoil in abundance will be divided; even the lame will take the prey.
23Is 33:24 And no inhabitant will say, "I am sick"; the people who dwell there will be forgiven their iniquity.
23Is 34:1 Draw near, O nations, to hear, and give attention, O peoples! Let the earth hear, and all that fills it; the world, and all that comes from it.
23Is 34:2 For the LORD is enraged against all the nations, and furious against all their host; he has devoted them to destruction, has given them over for slaughter.
23Is 34:3 Their slain shall be cast out, and the stench of their corpses shall rise; the mountains shall flow with their blood.
23Is 34:4 All the host of heaven shall rot away, and the skies roll up like a scroll. All their host shall fall, as leaves fall from the vine, like leaves falling from the fig tree.
23Is 34:5 For my sword has drunk its fill in the heavens; behold, it descends for judgment upon Edom, upon the people I have devoted to destruction.
23Is 34:6 The LORD has a sword; it is sated with blood; it is gorged with fat, with the blood of lambs and goats, with the fat of the kidneys of rams. For the LORD has a sacrifice in Bozrah, a great slaughter in the land of Edom.
23Is 34:7 Wild oxen shall fall with them, and young steers with the mighty bulls. Their land shall drink its fill of blood, and their soil shall be gorged with fat.
23Is 34:8 For the LORD has a day of vengeance, a year of recompense for the cause of Zion.
23Is 34:9 And the streams of Edom shall be turned into pitch, and her soil into sulfur; her land shall become burning pitch.
23Is 34:10 Night and day it shall not be quenched; its smoke shall go up forever. From generation to generation it shall lie waste; none shall pass through it forever and ever.
23Is 34:11 But the hawk and the porcupine shall possess it, the owl and the raven shall dwell in it. He shall stretch the line of confusion over it, and the plumb line of emptiness.
23Is 34:12 Its nobles--there is no one there to call it a kingdom, and all its princes shall be nothing.
23Is 34:13 Thorns shall grow over its strongholds, nettles and thistles in its fortresses. It shall be the haunt of jackals, an abode for ostriches.
23Is 34:14 And wild animals shall meet with hyenas; the wild goat shall cry to his fellow; indeed, there the night bird settles and finds for herself a resting place.
23Is 34:15 There the owl nests and lays and hatches and gathers her young in her shadow; indeed, there the hawks are gathered, each one with her mate.
23Is 34:16 Seek and read from the book of the LORD: Not one of these shall be missing; none shall be without her mate. For the mouth of the LORD has commanded, and his Spirit has gathered them.
23Is 34:17 He has cast the lot for them; his hand has portioned it out to them with the line; they shall possess it forever; from generation to generation they shall dwell in it.
23Is 35:1 The wilderness and the dry land shall be glad; the desert shall rejoice and blossom like the crocus;
23Is 35:2 it shall blossom abundantly and rejoice with joy and singing. The glory of Lebanon shall be given to it, the majesty of Carmel and Sharon. They shall see the glory of the LORD, the majesty of our God.
23Is 35:3 Strengthen the weak hands, and make firm the feeble knees.
23Is 35:4 Say to those who have an anxious heart, "Be strong; fear not! Behold, your God will come with vengeance, with the recompense of God. He will come and save you."
23Is 35:5 Then the eyes of the blind shall be opened, and the ears of the deaf unstopped;
23Is 35:6 then shall the lame man leap like a deer, and the tongue of the mute sing for joy. For waters break forth in the wilderness, and streams in the desert;
23Is 35:7 the burning sand shall become a pool, and the thirsty ground springs of water; in the haunt of jackals, where they lie down, the grass shall become reeds and rushes.
23Is 35:8 And a highway shall be there, and it shall be called the Way of Holiness; the unclean shall not pass over it. It shall belong to those who walk on the way; even if they are fools, they shall not go astray.
23Is 35:9 No lion shall be there, nor shall any ravenous beast come up on it; they shall not be found there, but the redeemed shall walk there.
23Is 35:10 And the ransomed of the LORD shall return and come to Zion with singing; everlasting joy shall be upon their heads; they shall obtain gladness and joy, and sorrow and sighing shall flee away.
23Is 36:1 In the fourteenth year of King Hezekiah, Sennacherib king of Assyria came up against all the fortified cities of Judah and took them.
23Is 36:2 And the king of Assyria sent the Rabshakeh from Lachish to King Hezekiah at Jerusalem, with a great army. And he stood by the conduit of the upper pool on the highway to the Washer's Field.
23Is 36:3 And there came out to him Eliakim the son of Hilkiah, who was over the household, and Shebna the secretary, and Joah the son of Asaph, the recorder.
23Is 36:4 And the Rabshakeh said to them, "Say to Hezekiah, 'Thus says the great king, the king of Assyria: On what do you rest this trust of yours?
23Is 36:5 Do you think that mere words are strategy and power for war? In whom do you now trust, that you have rebelled against me?
23Is 36:6 Behold, you are trusting in Egypt, that broken reed of a staff, which will pierce the hand of any man who leans on it. Such is Pharaoh king of Egypt to all who trust in him.
23Is 36:7 But if you say to me, "We trust in the LORD our God," is it not he whose high places and altars Hezekiah has removed, saying to Judah and to Jerusalem, "You shall worship before this altar"?
23Is 36:8 Come now, make a wager with my master the king of Assyria: I will give you two thousand horses, if you are able on your part to set riders on them.
23Is 36:9 How then can you repulse a single captain among the least of my master's servants, when you trust in Egypt for chariots and for horsemen?
23Is 36:10 Moreover, is it without the LORD that I have come up against this land to destroy it? The LORD said to me, Go up against this land and destroy it.'"
23Is 36:11 Then Eliakim, Shebna, and Joah said to the Rabshakeh, "Please speak to your servants in Aramaic, for we understand it. Do not speak to us in the language of Judah within the hearing of the people who are on the wall."
23Is 36:12 But the Rabshakeh said, "Has my master sent me to speak these words to your master and to you, and not to the men sitting on the wall, who are doomed with you to eat their own dung and drink their own urine?"
23Is 36:13 Then the Rabshakeh stood and called out in a loud voice in the language of Judah: "Hear the words of the great king, the king of Assyria!
23Is 36:14 Thus says the king: 'Do not let Hezekiah deceive you, for he will not be able to deliver you.
23Is 36:15 Do not let Hezekiah make you trust in the LORD by saying, "The LORD will surely deliver us. This city will not be given into the hand of the king of Assyria."
23Is 36:16 Do not listen to Hezekiah. For thus says the king of Assyria: Make your peace with me and come out to me. Then each one of you will eat of his own vine, and each one of his own fig tree, and each one of you will drink the water of his own cistern,
23Is 36:17 until I come and take you away to a land like your own land, a land of grain and wine, a land of bread and vineyards.
23Is 36:18 Beware lest Hezekiah mislead you by saying, "The LORD will deliver us." Has any of the gods of the nations delivered his land out of the hand of the king of Assyria?
23Is 36:19 Where are the gods of Hamath and Arpad? Where are the gods of Sepharvaim? Have they delivered Samaria out of my hand?
23Is 36:20 Who among all the gods of these lands have delivered their lands out of my hand, that the LORD should deliver Jerusalem out of my hand?'"
23Is 36:21 But they were silent and answered him not a word, for the king's command was, "Do not answer him."
23Is 36:22 Then Eliakim the son of Hilkiah, who was over the household, and Shebna the secretary, and Joah the son of Asaph, the recorder, came to Hezekiah with their clothes torn, and told him the words of the Rabshakeh.
23Is 37:1 As soon as King Hezekiah heard it, he tore his clothes and covered himself with sackcloth and went into the house of the LORD.
23Is 37:2 And he sent Eliakim, who was over the household, and Shebna the secretary, and the senior priests, covered with sackcloth, to the prophet Isaiah the son of Amoz.
23Is 37:3 They said to him, "Thus says Hezekiah, 'This day is a day of distress, of rebuke, and of disgrace; children have come to the point of birth, and there is no strength to bring them forth.
23Is 37:4 It may be that the LORD your God will hear the words of the Rabshakeh, whom his master the king of Assyria has sent to mock the living God, and will rebuke the words that the LORD your God has heard; therefore lift up your prayer for the remnant that is left.'"
23Is 37:5 When the servants of King Hezekiah came to Isaiah,
23Is 37:6 Isaiah said to them, "Say to your master, 'Thus says the LORD: Do not be afraid because of the words that you have heard, with which the young men of the king of Assyria have reviled me.
23Is 37:7 Behold, I will put a spirit in him, so that he shall hear a rumor and return to his own land, and I will make him fall by the sword in his own land.'"
23Is 37:8 The Rabshakeh returned, and found the king of Assyria fighting against Libnah, for he had heard that the king had left Lachish.
23Is 37:9 Now the king heard concerning Tirhakah king of Cush, "He has set out to fight against you." And when he heard it, he sent messengers to Hezekiah, saying,
23Is 37:10 "Thus shall you speak to Hezekiah king of Judah: 'Do not let your God in whom you trust deceive you by promising that Jerusalem will not be given into the hand of the king of Assyria.
23Is 37:11 Behold, you have heard what the kings of Assyria have done to all lands, devoting them to destruction. And shall you be delivered?
23Is 37:12 Have the gods of the nations delivered them, the nations that my fathers destroyed, Gozan, Haran, Rezeph, and the people of Eden who were in Telassar?
23Is 37:13 Where is the king of Hamath, the king of Arpad, the king of the city of Sepharvaim, the king of Hena, or the king of Ivvah?'"
23Is 37:14 Hezekiah received the letter from the hand of the messengers, and read it; and Hezekiah went up to the house of the LORD, and spread it before the LORD.
23Is 37:15 And Hezekiah prayed to the LORD:
23Is 37:16 "O LORD of hosts, God of Israel, enthroned above the cherubim, you are the God, you alone, of all the kingdoms of the earth; you have made heaven and earth.
23Is 37:17 Incline your ear, O LORD, and hear; open your eyes, O LORD, and see; and hear all the words of Sennacherib, which he has sent to mock the living God.
23Is 37:18 Truly, O LORD, the kings of Assyria have laid waste all the nations and their lands,
23Is 37:19 and have cast their gods into the fire. For they were no gods, but the work of men's hands, wood and stone. Therefore they were destroyed.
23Is 37:20 So now, O LORD our God, save us from his hand, that all the kingdoms of the earth may know that you alone are the LORD."
23Is 37:21 Then Isaiah the son of Amoz sent to Hezekiah, saying, "Thus says the LORD, the God of Israel: Because you have prayed to me concerning Sennacherib king of Assyria,
23Is 37:22 this is the word that the LORD has spoken concerning him: "'She despises you, she scorns you-- the virgin daughter of Zion; she wags her head behind you-- the daughter of Jerusalem.
23Is 37:23 "'Whom have you mocked and reviled? Against whom have you raised your voice and lifted your eyes to the heights? Against the Holy One of Israel!
23Is 37:24 By your servants you have mocked the Lord, and you have said, With my many chariots I have gone up the heights of the mountains, to the far recesses of Lebanon, to cut down its tallest cedars, its choicest cypresses, to come to its remotest height, its most fruitful forest.
23Is 37:25 I dug wells and drank waters, to dry up with the sole of my foot all the streams of Egypt.
23Is 37:26 "'Have you not heard that I determined it long ago? I planned from days of old what now I bring to pass, that you should make fortified cities crash into heaps of ruins,
23Is 37:27 while their inhabitants, shorn of strength, are dismayed and confounded, and have become like plants of the field and like tender grass, like grass on the housetops, blighted before it is grown.
23Is 37:28 "'I know your sitting down and your going out and coming in, and your raging against me.
23Is 37:29 Because you have raged against me and your complacency has come to my ears, I will put my hook in your nose and my bit in your mouth, and I will turn you back on the way by which you came.'
23Is 37:30 "And this shall be the sign for you: this year you shall eat what grows of itself, and in the second year what springs from that. Then in the third year sow and reap, and plant vineyards, and eat their fruit.
23Is 37:31 And the surviving remnant of the house of Judah shall again take root downward and bear fruit upward.
23Is 37:32 For out of Jerusalem shall go a remnant, and out of Mount Zion a band of survivors. The zeal of the LORD of hosts will do this.
23Is 37:33 "Therefore thus says the LORD concerning the king of Assyria: He shall not come into this city or shoot an arrow there or come before it with a shield or cast up a siege mound against it.
23Is 37:34 By the way that he came, by the same he shall return, and he shall not come into this city, declares the LORD.
23Is 37:35 For I will defend this city to save it, for my own sake and for the sake of my servant David."
23Is 37:36 And the angel of the LORD went out and struck down a hundred and eighty-five thousand in the camp of the Assyrians. And when people arose early in the morning, behold, these were all dead bodies.
23Is 37:37 Then Sennacherib king of Assyria departed and returned home and lived at Nineveh.
23Is 37:38 And as he was worshiping in the house of Nisroch his god, Adrammelech and Sharezer, his sons, struck him down with the sword. And after they escaped into the land of Ararat, Esarhaddon his son reigned in his place.
23Is 38:1 In those days Hezekiah became sick and was at the point of death. And Isaiah the prophet the son of Amoz came to him, and said to him, "Thus says the LORD: Set your house in order, for you shall die, you shall not recover."
23Is 38:2 Then Hezekiah turned his face to the wall and prayed to the LORD,
23Is 38:3 and said, "Please, O LORD, remember how I have walked before you in faithfulness and with a whole heart, and have done what is good in your sight." And Hezekiah wept bitterly.
23Is 38:4 Then the word of the LORD came to Isaiah:
23Is 38:5 "Go and say to Hezekiah, Thus says the LORD, the God of David your father: I have heard your prayer; I have seen your tears. Behold, I will add fifteen years to your life.
23Is 38:6 I will deliver you and this city out of the hand of the king of Assyria, and will defend this city.
23Is 38:7 "This shall be the sign to you from the LORD, that the LORD will do this thing that he has promised:
23Is 38:8 Behold, I will make the shadow cast by the declining sun on the dial of Ahaz turn back ten steps." So the sun turned back on the dial the ten steps by which it had declined.
23Is 38:9 A writing of Hezekiah king of Judah, after he had been sick and had recovered from his sickness:
23Is 38:10 I said, In the middle of my days I must depart; I am consigned to the gates of Sheol for the rest of my years.
23Is 38:11 I said, I shall not see the LORD, the LORD in the land of the living; I shall look on man no more among the inhabitants of the world.
23Is 38:12 My dwelling is plucked up and removed from me like a shepherd's tent; like a weaver I have rolled up my life; he cuts me off from the loom; from day to night you bring me to an end;
23Is 38:13 I calmed myself until morning; like a lion he breaks all my bones; from day to night you bring me to an end.
23Is 38:14 Like a swallow or a crane I chirp; I moan like a dove. My eyes are weary with looking upward. O Lord, I am oppressed; be my pledge of safety!
23Is 38:15 What shall I say? For he has spoken to me, and he himself has done it. I walk slowly all my years because of the bitterness of my soul.
23Is 38:16 O Lord, by these things men live, and in all these is the life of my spirit. Oh restore me to health and make me live!
23Is 38:17 Behold, it was for my welfare that I had great bitterness; but in love you have delivered my life from the pit of destruction, for you have cast all my sins behind your back.
23Is 38:18 For Sheol does not thank you; death does not praise you; those who go down to the pit do not hope for your faithfulness.
23Is 38:19 The living, the living, he thanks you, as I do this day; the father makes known to the children your faithfulness.
23Is 38:20 The LORD will save me, and we will play my music on stringed instruments all the days of our lives, at the house of the LORD.
23Is 38:21 Now Isaiah had said, "Let them take a cake of figs and apply it to the boil, that he may recover."
23Is 38:22 Hezekiah also had said, "What is the sign that I shall go up to the house of the LORD?"
23Is 39:1 At that time Merodach-baladan the son of Baladan, king of Babylon, sent envoys with letters and a present to Hezekiah, for he heard that he had been sick and had recovered.
23Is 39:2 And Hezekiah welcomed them gladly. And he showed them his treasure house, the silver, the gold, the spices, the precious oil, his whole armory, all that was found in his storehouses. There was nothing in his house or in all his realm that Hezekiah did not show them.
23Is 39:3 Then Isaiah the prophet came to King Hezekiah, and said to him, "What did these men say? And from where did they come to you?" Hezekiah said, "They have come to me from a far country, from Babylon."
23Is 39:4 He said, "What have they seen in your house?" Hezekiah answered, "They have seen all that is in my house. There is nothing in my storehouses that I did not show them."
23Is 39:5 Then Isaiah said to Hezekiah, "Hear the word of the LORD of hosts:
23Is 39:6 Behold, the days are coming, when all that is in your house, and that which your fathers have stored up till this day, shall be carried to Babylon. Nothing shall be left, says the LORD.
23Is 39:7 And some of your own sons, who will come from you, whom you will father, shall be taken away, and they shall be eunuchs in the palace of the king of Babylon."
23Is 39:8 Then said Hezekiah to Isaiah, "The word of the LORD that you have spoken is good." For he thought, "There will be peace and security in my days."
23Is 40:1 Comfort, comfort my people, says your God.
23Is 40:2 Speak tenderly to Jerusalem, and cry to her that her warfare is ended, that her iniquity is pardoned, that she has received from the LORD's hand double for all her sins.
23Is 40:3 A voice cries: "In the wilderness prepare the way of the LORD; make straight in the desert a highway for our God.
23Is 40:4 Every valley shall be lifted up, and every mountain and hill be made low; the uneven ground shall become level, and the rough places a plain.
23Is 40:5 And the glory of the LORD shall be revealed, and all flesh shall see it together, for the mouth of the LORD has spoken."
23Is 40:6 A voice says, "Cry!" And I said, "What shall I cry?" All flesh is grass, and all its beauty is like the flower of the field.
23Is 40:7 The grass withers, the flower fades when the breath of the LORD blows on it; surely the people are grass.
23Is 40:8 The grass withers, the flower fades, but the word of our God will stand forever.
23Is 40:9 Get you up to a high mountain, O Zion, herald of good news; lift up your voice with strength, O Jerusalem, herald of good news; lift it up, fear not; say to the cities of Judah, "Behold your God!"
23Is 40:10 Behold, the Lord GOD comes with might, and his arm rules for him; behold, his reward is with him, and his recompense before him.
23Is 40:11 He will tend his flock like a shepherd; he will gather the lambs in his arms; he will carry them in his bosom, and gently lead those that are with young.
23Is 40:12 Who has measured the waters in the hollow of his hand and marked off the heavens with a span, enclosed the dust of the earth in a measure and weighed the mountains in scales and the hills in a balance?
23Is 40:13 Who has measured the Spirit of the LORD, or what man shows him his counsel?
23Is 40:14 Whom did he consult, and who made him understand? Who taught him the path of justice, and taught him knowledge, and showed him the way of understanding?
23Is 40:15 Behold, the nations are like a drop from a bucket, and are accounted as the dust on the scales; behold, he takes up the coastlands like fine dust.
23Is 40:16 Lebanon would not suffice for fuel, nor are its beasts enough for a burnt offering.
23Is 40:17 All the nations are as nothing before him, they are accounted by him as less than nothing and emptiness.
23Is 40:18 To whom then will you liken God, or what likeness compare with him?
23Is 40:19 An idol! A craftsman casts it, and a goldsmith overlays it with gold and casts for it silver chains.
23Is 40:20 He who is too impoverished for an offering chooses wood that will not rot; he seeks out a skillful craftsman to set up an idol that will not move.
23Is 40:21 Do you not know? Do you not hear? Has it not been told you from the beginning? Have you not understood from the foundations of the earth?
23Is 40:22 It is he who sits above the circle of the earth, and its inhabitants are like grasshoppers; who stretches out the heavens like a curtain, and spreads them like a tent to dwell in;
23Is 40:23 who brings princes to nothing, and makes the rulers of the earth as emptiness.
23Is 40:24 Scarcely are they planted, scarcely sown, scarcely has their stem taken root in the earth, when he blows on them, and they wither, and the tempest carries them off like stubble.
23Is 40:25 To whom then will you compare me, that I should be like him? says the Holy One.
23Is 40:26 Lift up your eyes on high and see: who created these? He who brings out their host by number, calling them all by name, by the greatness of his might, and because he is strong in power not one is missing.
23Is 40:27 Why do you say, O Jacob, and speak, O Israel, "My way is hidden from the LORD, and my right is disregarded by my God"?
23Is 40:28 Have you not known? Have you not heard? The LORD is the everlasting God, the Creator of the ends of the earth. He does not faint or grow weary; his understanding is unsearchable.
23Is 40:29 He gives power to the faint, and to him who has no might he increases strength.
23Is 40:30 Even youths shall faint and be weary, and young men shall fall exhausted;
23Is 40:31 but they who wait for the LORD shall renew their strength; they shall mount up with wings like eagles; they shall run and not be weary; they shall walk and not faint.
23Is 41:1 Listen to me in silence, O coastlands; let the peoples renew their strength; let them approach, then let them speak; let us together draw near for judgment.
23Is 41:2 Who stirred up one from the east whom victory meets at every step? He gives up nations before him, so that he tramples kings underfoot; he makes them like dust with his sword, like driven stubble with his bow.
23Is 41:3 He pursues them and passes on safely, by paths his feet have not trod.
23Is 41:4 Who has performed and done this, calling the generations from the beginning? I, the LORD, the first, and with the last; I am he.
23Is 41:5 The coastlands have seen and are afraid; the ends of the earth tremble; they have drawn near and come.
23Is 41:6 Everyone helps his neighbor and says to his brother, "Be strong!"
23Is 41:7 The craftsman strengthens the goldsmith, and he who smooths with the hammer him who strikes the anvil, saying of the soldering, "It is good"; and they strengthen it with nails so that it cannot be moved.
23Is 41:8 But you, Israel, my servant, Jacob, whom I have chosen, the offspring of Abraham, my friend;
23Is 41:9 you whom I took from the ends of the earth, and called from its farthest corners, saying to you, "You are my servant, I have chosen you and not cast you off";
23Is 41:10 fear not, for I am with you; be not dismayed, for I am your God; I will strengthen you, I will help you, I will uphold you with my righteous right hand.
23Is 41:11 Behold, all who are incensed against you shall be put to shame and confounded; those who strive against you shall be as nothing and shall perish.
23Is 41:12 You shall seek those who contend with you, but you shall not find them; those who war against you shall be as nothing at all.
23Is 41:13 For I, the LORD your God, hold your right hand; it is I who say to you, "Fear not, I am the one who helps you."
23Is 41:14 Fear not, you worm Jacob, you men of Israel! I am the one who helps you, declares the LORD; your Redeemer is the Holy One of Israel.
23Is 41:15 Behold, I make of you a threshing sledge, new, sharp, and having teeth; you shall thresh the mountains and crush them, and you shall make the hills like chaff;
23Is 41:16 you shall winnow them, and the wind shall carry them away, and the tempest shall scatter them. And you shall rejoice in the LORD; in the Holy One of Israel you shall glory.
23Is 41:17 When the poor and needy seek water, and there is none, and their tongue is parched with thirst, I the LORD will answer them; I the God of Israel will not forsake them.
23Is 41:18 I will open rivers on the bare heights, and fountains in the midst of the valleys. I will make the wilderness a pool of water, and the dry land springs of water.
23Is 41:19 I will put in the wilderness the cedar, the acacia, the myrtle, and the olive. I will set in the desert the cypress, the plane and the pine together,
23Is 41:20 that they may see and know, may consider and understand together, that the hand of the LORD has done this, the Holy One of Israel has created it.
23Is 41:21 Set forth your case, says the LORD; bring your proofs, says the King of Jacob.
23Is 41:22 Let them bring them, and tell us what is to happen. Tell us the former things, what they are, that we may consider them, that we may know their outcome; or declare to us the things to come.
23Is 41:23 Tell us what is to come hereafter, that we may know that you are gods; do good, or do harm, that we may be dismayed and terrified.
23Is 41:24 Behold, you are nothing, and your work is less than nothing; an abomination is he who chooses you.
23Is 41:25 I stirred up one from the north, and he has come, from the rising of the sun, and he shall call upon my name; he shall trample on rulers as on mortar, as the potter treads clay.
23Is 41:26 Who declared it from the beginning, that we might know, and beforehand, that we might say, "He is right"? There was none who declared it, none who proclaimed, none who heard your words.
23Is 41:27 I was the first to say to Zion, "Behold, here they are!" and I give to Jerusalem a herald of good news.
23Is 41:28 But when I look, there is no one; among these there is no counselor who, when I ask, gives an answer.
23Is 41:29 Behold, they are all a delusion; their works are nothing; their metal images are empty wind.
23Is 42:1 Behold my servant, whom I uphold, my chosen, in whom my soul delights; I have put my Spirit upon him; he will bring forth justice to the nations.
23Is 42:2 He will not cry aloud or lift up his voice, or make it heard in the street;
23Is 42:3 a bruised reed he will not break, and a faintly burning wick he will not quench; he will faithfully bring forth justice.
23Is 42:4 He will not grow faint or be discouraged till he has established justice in the earth; and the coastlands wait for his law.
23Is 42:5 Thus says God, the LORD, who created the heavens and stretched them out, who spread out the earth and what comes from it, who gives breath to the people on it and spirit to those who walk in it:
23Is 42:6 "I am the LORD; I have called you in righteousness; I will take you by the hand and keep you; I will give you as a covenant for the people, a light for the nations,
23Is 42:7 to open the eyes that are blind, to bring out the prisoners from the dungeon, from the prison those who sit in darkness.
23Is 42:8 I am the LORD; that is my name; my glory I give to no other, nor my praise to carved idols.
23Is 42:9 Behold, the former things have come to pass, and new things I now declare; before they spring forth I tell you of them."
23Is 42:10 Sing to the LORD a new song, his praise from the end of the earth, you who go down to the sea, and all that fills it, the coastlands and their inhabitants.
23Is 42:11 Let the desert and its cities lift up their voice, the villages that Kedar inhabits; let the habitants of Sela sing for joy, let them shout from the top of the mountains.
23Is 42:12 Let them give glory to the LORD, and declare his praise in the coastlands.
23Is 42:13 The LORD goes out like a mighty man, like a man of war he stirs up his zeal; he cries out, he shouts aloud, he shows himself mighty against his foes.
23Is 42:14 For a long time I have held my peace; I have kept still and restrained myself; now I will cry out like a woman in labor; I will gasp and pant.
23Is 42:15 I will lay waste mountains and hills, and dry up all their vegetation; I will turn the rivers into islands, and dry up the pools.
23Is 42:16 And I will lead the blind in a way that they do not know, in paths that they have not known I will guide them. I will turn the darkness before them into light, the rough places into level ground. These are the things I do, and I do not forsake them.
23Is 42:17 They are turned back and utterly put to shame, who trust in carved idols, who say to metal images, "You are our gods."
23Is 42:18 Hear, you deaf, and look, you blind, that you may see!
23Is 42:19 Who is blind but my servant, or deaf as my messenger whom I send? Who is blind as my dedicated one, or blind as the servant of the LORD?
23Is 42:20 He sees many things, but does not observe them; his ears are open, but he does not hear.
23Is 42:21 The LORD was pleased, for his righteousness' sake, to magnify his law and make it glorious.
23Is 42:22 But this is a people plundered and looted; they are all of them trapped in holes and hidden in prisons; they have become plunder with none to rescue, spoil with none to say, "Restore!"
23Is 42:23 Who among you will give ear to this, will attend and listen for the time to come?
23Is 42:24 Who gave up Jacob to the looter, and Israel to the plunderers? Was it not the LORD, against whom we have sinned, in whose ways they would not walk, and whose law they would not obey?
23Is 42:25 So he poured on him the heat of his anger and the might of battle; it set him on fire all around, but he did not understand; it burned him up, but he did not take it to heart.
23Is 43:1 But now thus says the LORD, he who created you, O Jacob, he who formed you, O Israel: "Fear not, for I have redeemed you; I have called you by name, you are mine.
23Is 43:2 When you pass through the waters, I will be with you; and through the rivers, they shall not overwhelm you; when you walk through fire you shall not be burned, and the flame shall not consume you.
23Is 43:3 For I am the LORD your God, the Holy One of Israel, your Savior. I give Egypt as your ransom, Cush and Seba in exchange for you.
23Is 43:4 Because you are precious in my eyes, and honored, and I love you, I give men in return for you, peoples in exchange for your life.
23Is 43:5 Fear not, for I am with you; I will bring your offspring from the east, and from the west I will gather you.
23Is 43:6 I will say to the north, Give up, and to the south, Do not withhold; bring my sons from afar and my daughters from the end of the earth,
23Is 43:7 everyone who is called by my name, whom I created for my glory, whom I formed and made."
23Is 43:8 Bring out the people who are blind, yet have eyes, who are deaf, yet have ears!
23Is 43:9 All the nations gather together, and the peoples assemble. Who among them can declare this, and show us the former things? Let them bring their witnesses to prove them right, and let them hear and say, It is true.
23Is 43:10 "You are my witnesses," declares the LORD, "and my servant whom I have chosen, that you may know and believe me and understand that I am he. Before me no god was formed, nor shall there be any after me.
23Is 43:11 I, I am the LORD, and besides me there is no savior.
23Is 43:12 I declared and saved and proclaimed, when there was no strange god among you; and you are my witnesses," declares the LORD, "and I am God.
23Is 43:13 Also henceforth I am he; there is none who can deliver from my hand; I work, and who can turn it back?"
23Is 43:14 Thus says the LORD, your Redeemer, the Holy One of Israel: "For your sake I send to Babylon and bring them all down as fugitives, even the Chaldeans, in the ships in which they rejoice.
23Is 43:15 I am the LORD, your Holy One, the Creator of Israel, your King."
23Is 43:16 Thus says the LORD, who makes a way in the sea, a path in the mighty waters,
23Is 43:17 who brings forth chariot and horse, army and warrior; they lie down, they cannot rise, they are extinguished, quenched like a wick:
23Is 43:18 "Remember not the former things, nor consider the things of old.
23Is 43:19 Behold, I am doing a new thing; now it springs forth, do you not perceive it? I will make a way in the wilderness and rivers in the desert.
23Is 43:20 The wild beasts will honor me, the jackals and the ostriches, for I give water in the wilderness, rivers in the desert, to give drink to my chosen people,
23Is 43:21 the people whom I formed for myself that they might declare my praise.
23Is 43:22 "Yet you did not call upon me, O Jacob; but you have been weary of me, O Israel!
23Is 43:23 You have not brought me your sheep for burnt offerings, or honored me with your sacrifices. I have not burdened you with offerings, or wearied you with frankincense.
23Is 43:24 You have not bought me sweet cane with money, or satisfied me with the fat of your sacrifices. But you have burdened me with your sins; you have wearied me with your iniquities.
23Is 43:25 "I, I am he who blots out your transgressions for my own sake, and I will not remember your sins.
23Is 43:26 Put me in remembrance; let us argue together; set forth your case, that you may be proved right.
23Is 43:27 Your first father sinned, and your mediators transgressed against me.
23Is 43:28 Therefore I will profane the princes of the sanctuary, and deliver Jacob to utter destruction and Israel to reviling.
23Is 44:1 "But now hear, O Jacob my servant, Israel whom I have chosen!
23Is 44:2 Thus says the LORD who made you, who formed you from the womb and will help you: Fear not, O Jacob my servant, Jeshurun whom I have chosen.
23Is 44:3 For I will pour water on the thirsty land, and streams on the dry ground; I will pour my Spirit upon your offspring, and my blessing on your descendants.
23Is 44:4 They shall spring up among the grass like willows by flowing streams.
23Is 44:5 This one will say, 'I am the LORD's,' another will call on the name of Jacob, and another will write on his hand, 'The LORD's,' and name himself by the name of Israel."
23Is 44:6 Thus says the LORD, the King of Israel and his Redeemer, the LORD of hosts: "I am the first and I am the last; besides me there is no god.
23Is 44:7 Who is like me? Let him proclaim it. Let him declare and set it before me, since I appointed an ancient people. Let them declare what is to come, and what will happen.
23Is 44:8 Fear not, nor be afraid; have I not told you from of old and declared it? And you are my witnesses! Is there a God besides me? There is no Rock; I know not any."
23Is 44:9 All who fashion idols are nothing, and the things they delight in do not profit. Their witnesses neither see nor know, that they may be put to shame.
23Is 44:10 Who fashions a god or casts an idol that is profitable for nothing?
23Is 44:11 Behold, all his companions shall be put to shame, and the craftsmen are only human. Let them all assemble, let them stand forth. They shall be terrified; they shall be put to shame together.
23Is 44:12 The ironsmith takes a cutting tool and works it over the coals. He fashions it with hammers and works it with his strong arm. He becomes hungry, and his strength fails; he drinks no water and is faint.
23Is 44:13 The carpenter stretches a line; he marks it out with a pencil. He shapes it with planes and marks it with a compass. He shapes it into the figure of a man, with the beauty of a man, to dwell in a house.
23Is 44:14 He cuts down cedars, or he chooses a cypress tree or an oak and lets it grow strong among the trees of the forest. He plants a cedar and the rain nourishes it.
23Is 44:15 Then it becomes fuel for a man. He takes a part of it and warms himself; he kindles a fire and bakes bread. Also he makes a god and worships it; he makes it an idol and falls down before it.
23Is 44:16 Half of it he burns in the fire. Over the half he eats meat; he roasts it and is satisfied. Also he warms himself and says, "Aha, I am warm, I have seen the fire!"
23Is 44:17 And the rest of it he makes into a god, his idol, and falls down to it and worships it. He prays to it and says, "Deliver me, for you are my god!"
23Is 44:18 They know not, nor do they discern, for he has shut their eyes, so that they cannot see, and their hearts, so that they cannot understand.
23Is 44:19 No one considers, nor is there knowledge or discernment to say, "Half of it I burned in the fire; I also baked bread on its coals; I roasted meat and have eaten. And shall I make the rest of it an abomination? Shall I fall down before a block of wood?"
23Is 44:20 He feeds on ashes; a deluded heart has led him astray, and he cannot deliver himself or say, "Is there not a lie in my right hand?"
23Is 44:21 Remember these things, O Jacob, and Israel, for you are my servant; I formed you; you are my servant; O Israel, you will not be forgotten by me.
23Is 44:22 I have blotted out your transgressions like a cloud and your sins like mist; return to me, for I have redeemed you.
23Is 44:23 Sing, O heavens, for the LORD has done it; shout, O depths of the earth; break forth into singing, O mountains, O forest, and every tree in it! For the LORD has redeemed Jacob, and will be glorified in Israel.
23Is 44:24 Thus says the LORD, your Redeemer, who formed you from the womb: "I am the LORD, who made all things, who alone stretched out the heavens, who spread out the earth by myself,
23Is 44:25 who frustrates the signs of liars and makes fools of diviners, who turns wise men back and makes their knowledge foolish,
23Is 44:26 who confirms the word of his servant and fulfills the counsel of his messengers, who says of Jerusalem, 'She shall be inhabited,' and of the cities of Judah, 'They shall be built, and I will raise up their ruins';
23Is 44:27 who says to the deep, 'Be dry; I will dry up your rivers';
23Is 44:28 who says of Cyrus, 'He is my shepherd, and he shall fulfill all my purpose'; saying of Jerusalem, 'She shall be built,' and of the temple, 'Your foundation shall be laid.'"
23Is 45:1 Thus says the LORD to his anointed, to Cyrus, whose right hand I have grasped, to subdue nations before him and to loose the belts of kings, to open doors before him that gates may not be closed:
23Is 45:2 "I will go before you and level the exalted places, I will break in pieces the doors of bronze and cut through the bars of iron,
23Is 45:3 I will give you the treasures of darkness and the hoards in secret places, that you may know that it is I, the LORD, the God of Israel, who call you by your name.
23Is 45:4 For the sake of my servant Jacob, and Israel my chosen, I call you by your name, I name you, though you do not know me.
23Is 45:5 I am the LORD, and there is no other, besides me there is no God; I equip you, though you do not know me,
23Is 45:6 that people may know, from the rising of the sun and from the west, that there is none besides me; I am the LORD, and there is no other.
23Is 45:7 I form light and create darkness, I make well-being and create calamity, I am the LORD, who does all these things.
23Is 45:8 "Shower, O heavens, from above, and let the clouds rain down righteousness; let the earth open, that salvation and righteousness may bear fruit; let the earth cause them both to sprout; I the LORD have created it.
23Is 45:9 "Woe to him who strives with him who formed him, a pot among earthen pots! Does the clay say to him who forms it, 'What are you making?' or 'Your work has no handles'?
23Is 45:10 Woe to him who says to a father, 'What are you begetting?' or to a woman, 'With what are you in labor?'"
23Is 45:11 Thus says the LORD, the Holy One of Israel, and the one who formed him: "Ask me of things to come; will you command me concerning my children and the work of my hands?
23Is 45:12 I made the earth and created man on it; it was my hands that stretched out the heavens, and I commanded all their host.
23Is 45:13 I have stirred him up in righteousness, and I will make all his ways level; he shall build my city and set my exiles free, not for price or reward," says the LORD of hosts.
23Is 45:14 Thus says the LORD: "The wealth of Egypt and the merchandise of Cush, and the Sabeans, men of stature, shall come over to you and be yours; they shall follow you; they shall come over in chains and bow down to you. They will plead with you, saying: 'Surely God is in you, and there is no other, no god besides him.'"
23Is 45:15 Truly, you are a God who hides himself, O God of Israel, the Savior.
23Is 45:16 All of them are put to shame and confounded; the makers of idols go in confusion together.
23Is 45:17 But Israel is saved by the LORD with everlasting salvation; you shall not be put to shame or confounded to all eternity.
23Is 45:18 For thus says the LORD, who created the heavens (he is God!), who formed the earth and made it (he established it; he did not create it empty, he formed it to be inhabited!): "I am the LORD, and there is no other.
23Is 45:19 I did not speak in secret, in a land of darkness; I did not say to the offspring of Jacob, 'Seek me in vain.' I the LORD speak the truth; I declare what is right.
23Is 45:20 "Assemble yourselves and come; draw near together, you survivors of the nations! They have no knowledge who carry about their wooden idols, and keep on praying to a god that cannot save.
23Is 45:21 Declare and present your case; let them take counsel together! Who told this long ago? Who declared it of old? Was it not I, the LORD? And there is no other god besides me, a righteous God and a Savior; there is none besides me.
23Is 45:22 "Turn to me and be saved, all the ends of the earth! For I am God, and there is no other.
23Is 45:23 By myself I have sworn; from my mouth has gone out in righteousness a word that shall not return: 'To me every knee shall bow, every tongue shall swear allegiance.'
23Is 45:24 "Only in the LORD, it shall be said of me, are righteousness and strength; to him shall come and be ashamed all who were incensed against him.
23Is 45:25 In the LORD all the offspring of Israel shall be justified and shall glory."
23Is 46:1 Bel bows down; Nebo stoops; their idols are on beasts and livestock; these things you carry are borne as burdens on weary beasts.
23Is 46:2 They stoop; they bow down together; they cannot save the burden, but themselves go into captivity.
23Is 46:3 "Listen to me, O house of Jacob, all the remnant of the house of Israel, who have been borne by me from before your birth, carried from the womb;
23Is 46:4 even to your old age I am he, and to gray hairs I will carry you. I have made, and I will bear; I will carry and will save.
23Is 46:5 "To whom will you liken me and make me equal, and compare me, that we may be alike?
23Is 46:6 Those who lavish gold from the purse, and weigh out silver in the scales, hire a goldsmith, and he makes it into a god; then they fall down and worship!
23Is 46:7 They lift it to their shoulders, they carry it, they set it in its place, and it stands there; it cannot move from its place. If one cries to it, it does not answer or save him from his trouble.
23Is 46:8 "Remember this and stand firm, recall it to mind, you transgressors,
23Is 46:9 remember the former things of old; for I am God, and there is no other; I am God, and there is none like me,
23Is 46:10 declaring the end from the beginning and from ancient times things not yet done, saying, 'My counsel shall stand, and I will accomplish all my purpose,'
23Is 46:11 calling a bird of prey from the east, the man of my counsel from a far country. I have spoken, and I will bring it to pass; I have purposed, and I will do it.
23Is 46:12 "Listen to me, you stubborn of heart, you who are far from righteousness:
23Is 46:13 I bring near my righteousness; it is not far off, and my salvation will not delay; I will put salvation in Zion, for Israel my glory."
23Is 47:1 Come down and sit in the dust, O virgin daughter of Babylon; sit on the ground without a throne, O daughter of the Chaldeans! For you shall no more be called tender and delicate.
23Is 47:2 Take the millstones and grind flour, put off your veil, strip off your robe, uncover your legs, pass through the rivers.
23Is 47:3 Your nakedness shall be uncovered, and your disgrace shall be seen. I will take vengeance, and I will spare no one.
23Is 47:4 Our Redeemer--the LORD of hosts is his name-- is the Holy One of Israel.
23Is 47:5 Sit in silence, and go into darkness, O daughter of the Chaldeans; for you shall no more be called the mistress of kingdoms.
23Is 47:6 I was angry with my people; I profaned my heritage; I gave them into your hand; you showed them no mercy; on the aged you made your yoke exceedingly heavy.
23Is 47:7 You said, "I shall be mistress forever," so that you did not lay these things to heart or remember their end.
23Is 47:8 Now therefore hear this, you lover of pleasures, who sit securely, who say in your heart, "I am, and there is no one besides me; I shall not sit as a widow or know the loss of children":
23Is 47:9 These two things shall come to you in a moment, in one day; the loss of children and widowhood shall come upon you in full measure, in spite of your many sorceries and the great power of your enchantments.
23Is 47:10 You felt secure in your wickedness, you said, "No one sees me"; your wisdom and your knowledge led you astray, and you said in your heart, "I am, and there is no one besides me."
23Is 47:11 But evil shall come upon you, which you will not know how to charm away; disaster shall fall upon you, for which you will not be able to atone; and ruin shall come upon you suddenly, of which you know nothing.
23Is 47:12 Stand fast in your enchantments and your many sorceries, with which you have labored from your youth; perhaps you may be able to succeed; perhaps you may inspire terror.
23Is 47:13 You are wearied with your many counsels; let them stand forth and save you, those who divide the heavens, who gaze at the stars, who at the new moons make known what shall come upon you.
23Is 47:14 Behold, they are like stubble; the fire consumes them; they cannot deliver themselves from the power of the flame. No coal for warming oneself is this, no fire to sit before!
23Is 47:15 Such to you are those with whom you have labored, who have done business with you from your youth; they wander about, each in his own direction; there is no one to save you.
23Is 48:1 Hear this, O house of Jacob, who are called by the name of Israel, and who came from the waters of Judah, who swear by the name of the LORD and confess the God of Israel, but not in truth or right.
23Is 48:2 For they call themselves after the holy city, and stay themselves on the God of Israel; the LORD of hosts is his name.
23Is 48:3 "The former things I declared of old; they went out from my mouth, and I announced them; then suddenly I did them, and they came to pass.
23Is 48:4 Because I know that you are obstinate, and your neck is an iron sinew and your forehead brass,
23Is 48:5 I declared them to you from of old, before they came to pass I announced them to you, lest you should say, 'My idol did them, my carved image and my metal image commanded them.'
23Is 48:6 "You have heard; now see all this; and will you not declare it? From this time forth I announce to you new things, hidden things that you have not known.
23Is 48:7 They are created now, not long ago; before today you have never heard of them, lest you should say, 'Behold, I knew them.'
23Is 48:8 You have never heard, you have never known, from of old your ear has not been opened. For I knew that you would surely deal treacherously, and that from before birth you were called a rebel.
23Is 48:9 "For my name's sake I defer my anger, for the sake of my praise I restrain it for you, that I may not cut you off.
23Is 48:10 Behold, I have refined you, but not as silver; I have tried you in the furnace of affliction.
23Is 48:11 For my own sake, for my own sake, I do it, for how should my name be profaned? My glory I will not give to another.
23Is 48:12 "Listen to me, O Jacob, and Israel, whom I called! I am he; I am the first, and I am the last.
23Is 48:13 My hand laid the foundation of the earth, and my right hand spread out the heavens; when I call to them, they stand forth together.
23Is 48:14 "Assemble, all of you, and listen! Who among them has declared these things? The LORD loves him; he shall perform his purpose on Babylon, and his arm shall be against the Chaldeans.
23Is 48:15 I, even I, have spoken and called him; I have brought him, and he will prosper in his way.
23Is 48:16 Draw near to me, hear this: from the beginning I have not spoken in secret, from the time it came to be I have been there." And now the Lord GOD has sent me, and his Spirit.
23Is 48:17 Thus says the LORD, your Redeemer, the Holy One of Israel: "I am the LORD your God, who teaches you to profit, who leads you in the way you should go.
23Is 48:18 Oh that you had paid attention to my commandments! Then your peace would have been like a river, and your righteousness like the waves of the sea;
23Is 48:19 your offspring would have been like the sand, and your descendants like its grains; their name would never be cut off or destroyed from before me."
23Is 48:20 Go out from Babylon, flee from Chaldea, declare this with a shout of joy, proclaim it, send it out to the end of the earth; say, "The LORD has redeemed his servant Jacob!"
23Is 48:21 They did not thirst when he led them through the deserts; he made water flow for them from the rock; he split the rock and the water gushed out.
23Is 48:22 "There is no peace," says the LORD, "for the wicked."
23Is 49:1 Listen to me, O coastlands, and give attention, you peoples from afar. The LORD called me from the womb, from the body of my mother he named my name.
23Is 49:2 He made my mouth like a sharp sword; in the shadow of his hand he hid me; he made me a polished arrow; in his quiver he hid me away.
23Is 49:3 And he said to me, "You are my servant, Israel, in whom I will be glorified."
23Is 49:4 But I said, "I have labored in vain; I have spent my strength for nothing and vanity; yet surely my right is with the LORD, and my recompense with my God."
23Is 49:5 And now the LORD says, he who formed me from the womb to be his servant, to bring Jacob back to him; and that Israel might be gathered to him-- for I am honored in the eyes of the LORD, and my God has become my strength--
23Is 49:6 he says: "It is too light a thing that you should be my servant to raise up the tribes of Jacob and to bring back the preserved of Israel; I will make you as a light for the nations, that my salvation may reach to the end of the earth."
23Is 49:7 Thus says the LORD, the Redeemer of Israel and his Holy One, to one deeply despised, abhorred by the nation, the servant of rulers: "Kings shall see and arise; princes, and they shall prostrate themselves; because of the LORD, who is faithful, the Holy One of Israel, who has chosen you."
23Is 49:8 Thus says the LORD: "In a time of favor I have answered you; in a day of salvation I have helped you; I will keep you and give you as a covenant to the people, to establish the land, to apportion the desolate heritages,
23Is 49:9 saying to the prisoners, 'Come out,' to those who are in darkness, 'Appear.' They shall feed along the ways; on all bare heights shall be their pasture;
23Is 49:10 they shall not hunger or thirst, neither scorching wind nor sun shall strike them, for he who has pity on them will lead them, and by springs of water will guide them.
23Is 49:11 And I will make all my mountains a road, and my highways shall be raised up.
23Is 49:12 Behold, these shall come from afar, and behold, these from the north and from the west, and these from the land of Syene."
23Is 49:13 Sing for joy, O heavens, and exult, O earth; break forth, O mountains, into singing! For the LORD has comforted his people and will have compassion on his afflicted.
23Is 49:14 But Zion said, "The LORD has forsaken me; my Lord has forgotten me."
23Is 49:15 "Can a woman forget her nursing child, that she should have no compassion on the son of her womb? Even these may forget, yet I will not forget you.
23Is 49:16 Behold, I have engraved you on the palms of my hands; your walls are continually before me.
23Is 49:17 Your builders make haste; your destroyers and those who laid you waste go out from you.
23Is 49:18 Lift up your eyes around and see; they all gather, they come to you. As I live, declares the LORD, you shall put them all on as an ornament; you shall bind them on as a bride does.
23Is 49:19 "Surely your waste and your desolate places and your devastated land-- surely now you will be too narrow for your inhabitants, and those who swallowed you up will be far away.
23Is 49:20 The children of your bereavement will yet say in your ears: 'The place is too narrow for me; make room for me to dwell in.'
23Is 49:21 Then you will say in your heart: 'Who has borne me these? I was bereaved and barren, exiled and put away, but who has brought up these? Behold, I was left alone; from where have these come?'"
23Is 49:22 Thus says the Lord GOD: "Behold, I will lift up my hand to the nations, and raise my signal to the peoples; and they shall bring your sons in their bosom, and your daughters shall be carried on their shoulders.
23Is 49:23 Kings shall be your foster fathers, and their queens your nursing mothers. With their faces to the ground they shall bow down to you, and lick the dust of your feet. Then you will know that I am the LORD; those who wait for me shall not be put to shame."
23Is 49:24 Can the prey be taken from the mighty, or the captives of a tyrant be rescued?
23Is 49:25 For thus says the LORD: "Even the captives of the mighty shall be taken, and the prey of the tyrant be rescued, for I will contend with those who contend with you, and I will save your children.
23Is 49:26 I will make your oppressors eat their own flesh, and they shall be drunk with their own blood as with wine. Then all flesh shall know that I am the LORD your Savior, and your Redeemer, the Mighty One of Jacob."
23Is 50:1 Thus says the LORD: "Where is your mother's certificate of divorce, with which I sent her away? Or which of my creditors is it to whom I have sold you? Behold, for your iniquities you were sold, and for your transgressions your mother was sent away.
23Is 50:2 Why, when I came, was there no man; why, when I called, was there no one to answer? Is my hand shortened, that it cannot redeem? Or have I no power to deliver? Behold, by my rebuke I dry up the sea, I make the rivers a desert; their fish stink for lack of water and die of thirst.
23Is 50:3 I clothe the heavens with blackness and make sackcloth their covering."
23Is 50:4 The Lord GOD has given me the tongue of those who are taught, that I may know how to sustain with a word him who is weary. Morning by morning he awakens; he awakens my ear to hear as those who are taught.
23Is 50:5 The Lord GOD has opened my ear, and I was not rebellious; I turned not backward.
23Is 50:6 I gave my back to those who strike, and my cheeks to those who pull out the beard; I hid not my face from disgrace and spitting.
23Is 50:7 But the Lord GOD helps me; therefore I have not been disgraced; therefore I have set my face like a flint, and I know that I shall not be put to shame.
23Is 50:8 He who vindicates me is near. Who will contend with me? Let us stand up together. Who is my adversary? Let him come near to me.
23Is 50:9 Behold, the Lord GOD helps me; who will declare me guilty? Behold, all of them will wear out like a garment; the moth will eat them up.
23Is 50:10 Who among you fears the LORD and obeys the voice of his servant? Let him who walks in darkness and has no light trust in the name of the LORD and rely on his God.
23Is 50:11 Behold, all you who kindle a fire, who equip yourselves with burning torches! Walk by the light of your fire, and by the torches that you have kindled! This you have from my hand: you shall lie down in torment.
23Is 51:1 "Listen to me, you who pursue righteousness, you who seek the LORD: look to the rock from which you were hewn, and to the quarry from which you were dug.
23Is 51:2 Look to Abraham your father and to Sarah who bore you; for he was but one when I called him, that I might bless him and multiply him.
23Is 51:3 For the LORD comforts Zion; he comforts all her waste places and makes her wilderness like Eden, her desert like the garden of the LORD; joy and gladness will be found in her, thanksgiving and the voice of song.
23Is 51:4 "Give attention to me, my people, and give ear to me, my nation; for a law will go out from me, and I will set my justice for a light to the peoples.
23Is 51:5 My righteousness draws near, my salvation has gone out, and my arms will judge the peoples; the coastlands hope for me, and for my arm they wait.
23Is 51:6 Lift up your eyes to the heavens, and look at the earth beneath; for the heavens vanish like smoke, the earth will wear out like a garment, and they who dwell in it will die in like manner; but my salvation will be forever, and my righteousness will never be dismayed.
23Is 51:7 "Listen to me, you who know righteousness, the people in whose heart is my law; fear not the reproach of man, nor be dismayed at their revilings.
23Is 51:8 For the moth will eat them up like a garment, and the worm will eat them like wool; but my righteousness will be forever, and my salvation to all generations."
23Is 51:9 Awake, awake, put on strength, O arm of the LORD; awake, as in days of old, the generations of long ago. Was it not you who cut Rahab in pieces, who pierced the dragon?
23Is 51:10 Was it not you who dried up the sea, the waters of the great deep, who made the depths of the sea a way for the redeemed to pass over?
23Is 51:11 And the ransomed of the LORD shall return and come to Zion with singing; everlasting joy shall be upon their heads; they shall obtain gladness and joy, and sorrow and sighing shall flee away.
23Is 51:12 "I, I am he who comforts you; who are you that you are afraid of man who dies, of the son of man who is made like grass,
23Is 51:13 and have forgotten the LORD, your Maker, who stretched out the heavens and laid the foundations of the earth, and you fear continually all the day because of the wrath of the oppressor, when he sets himself to destroy? And where is the wrath of the oppressor?
23Is 51:14 He who is bowed down shall speedily be released; he shall not die and go down to the pit, neither shall his bread be lacking.
23Is 51:15 I am the LORD your God, who stirs up the sea so that its waves roar-- the LORD of hosts is his name.
23Is 51:16 And I have put my words in your mouth and covered you in the shadow of my hand, establishing the heavens and laying the foundations of the earth, and saying to Zion, 'You are my people.'"
23Is 51:17 Wake yourself, wake yourself, stand up, O Jerusalem, you who have drunk from the hand of the LORD the cup of his wrath, who have drunk to the dregs the bowl, the cup of staggering.
23Is 51:18 There is none to guide her among all the sons she has borne; there is none to take her by the hand among all the sons she has brought up.
23Is 51:19 These two things have happened to you-- who will console you?-- devastation and destruction, famine and sword; who will comfort you?
23Is 51:20 Your sons have fainted; they lie at the head of every street like an antelope in a net; they are full of the wrath of the LORD, the rebuke of your God.
23Is 51:21 Therefore hear this, you who are afflicted, who are drunk, but not with wine:
23Is 51:22 Thus says your Lord, the LORD, your God who pleads the cause of his people: "Behold, I have taken from your hand the cup of staggering; the bowl of my wrath you shall drink no more;
23Is 51:23 and I will put it into the hand of your tormentors, who have said to you, 'Bow down, that we may pass over'; and you have made your back like the ground and like the street for them to pass over."
23Is 52:1 Awake, awake, put on your strength, O Zion; put on your beautiful garments, O Jerusalem, the holy city; for there shall no more come into you the uncircumcised and the unclean.
23Is 52:2 Shake yourself from the dust and arise; be seated, O Jerusalem; loose the bonds from your neck, O captive daughter of Zion.
23Is 52:3 For thus says the LORD: "You were sold for nothing, and you shall be redeemed without money."
23Is 52:4 For thus says the Lord GOD: "My people went down at the first into Egypt to sojourn there, and the Assyrian oppressed them for nothing.
23Is 52:5 Now therefore what have I here," declares the LORD, "seeing that my people are taken away for nothing? Their rulers wail," declares the LORD, "and continually all the day my name is despised.
23Is 52:6 Therefore my people shall know my name. Therefore in that day they shall know that it is I who speak; here am I."
23Is 52:7 How beautiful upon the mountains are the feet of him who brings good news, who publishes peace, who brings good news of happiness, who publishes salvation, who says to Zion, "Your God reigns."
23Is 52:8 The voice of your watchmen--they lift up their voice; together they sing for joy; for eye to eye they see the return of the LORD to Zion.
23Is 52:9 Break forth together into singing, you waste places of Jerusalem, for the LORD has comforted his people; he has redeemed Jerusalem.
23Is 52:10 The LORD has bared his holy arm before the eyes of all the nations, and all the ends of the earth shall see the salvation of our God.
23Is 52:11 Depart, depart, go out from there; touch no unclean thing; go out from the midst of her; purify yourselves, you who bear the vessels of the LORD.
23Is 52:12 For you shall not go out in haste, and you shall not go in flight, for the LORD will go before you, and the God of Israel will be your rear guard.
23Is 52:13 Behold, my servant shall act wisely; he shall be high and lifted up, and shall be exalted.
23Is 52:14 As many were astonished at you-- his appearance was so marred, beyond human semblance, and his form beyond that of the children of mankind--
23Is 52:15 so shall he sprinkle many nations; kings shall shut their mouths because of him; for that which has not been told them they see, and that which they have not heard they understand.
23Is 53:1 Who has believed what he has heard from us? And to whom has the arm of the LORD been revealed?
23Is 53:2 For he grew up before him like a young plant, and like a root out of dry ground; he had no form or majesty that we should look at him, and no beauty that we should desire him.
23Is 53:3 He was despised and rejected by men; a man of sorrows, and acquainted with grief; and as one from whom men hide their faces he was despised, and we esteemed him not.
23Is 53:4 Surely he has borne our griefs and carried our sorrows; yet we esteemed him stricken, smitten by God, and afflicted.
23Is 53:5 But he was wounded for our transgressions; he was crushed for our iniquities; upon him was the chastisement that brought us peace, and with his stripes we are healed.
23Is 53:6 All we like sheep have gone astray; we have turned--every one--to his own way; and the LORD has laid on him the iniquity of us all.
23Is 53:7 He was oppressed, and he was afflicted, yet he opened not his mouth; like a lamb that is led to the slaughter, and like a sheep that before its shearers is silent, so he opened not his mouth.
23Is 53:8 By oppression and judgment he was taken away; and as for his generation, who considered that he was cut off out of the land of the living, stricken for the transgression of my people?
23Is 53:9 And they made his grave with the wicked and with a rich man in his death, although he had done no violence, and there was no deceit in his mouth.
23Is 53:10 Yet it was the will of the LORD to crush him; he has put him to grief; when his soul makes an offering for guilt, he shall see his offspring; he shall prolong his days; the will of the LORD shall prosper in his hand.
23Is 53:11 Out of the anguish of his soul he shall see and be satisfied; by his knowledge shall the righteous one, my servant, make many to be accounted righteous, and he shall bear their iniquities.
23Is 53:12 Therefore I will divide him a portion with the many, and he shall divide the spoil with the strong, because he poured out his soul to death and was numbered with the transgressors; yet he bore the sin of many, and makes intercession for the transgressors.
23Is 54:1 "Sing, O barren one, who did not bear; break forth into singing and cry aloud, you who have not been in labor! For the children of the desolate one will be more than the children of her who is married," says the LORD.
23Is 54:2 "Enlarge the place of your tent, and let the curtains of your habitations be stretched out; do not hold back; lengthen your cords and strengthen your stakes.
23Is 54:3 For you will spread abroad to the right and to the left, and your offspring will possess the nations and will people the desolate cities.
23Is 54:4 "Fear not, for you will not be ashamed; be not confounded, for you will not be disgraced; for you will forget the shame of your youth, and the reproach of your widowhood you will remember no more.
23Is 54:5 For your Maker is your husband, the LORD of hosts is his name; and the Holy One of Israel is your Redeemer, the God of the whole earth he is called.
23Is 54:6 For the LORD has called you like a wife deserted and grieved in spirit, like a wife of youth when she is cast off, says your God.
23Is 54:7 For a brief moment I deserted you, but with great compassion I will gather you.
23Is 54:8 In overflowing anger for a moment I hid my face from you, but with everlasting love I will have compassion on you," says the LORD, your Redeemer.
23Is 54:9 "This is like the days of Noah to me: as I swore that the waters of Noah should no more go over the earth, so I have sworn that I will not be angry with you, and will not rebuke you.
23Is 54:10 For the mountains may depart and the hills be removed, but my steadfast love shall not depart from you, and my covenant of peace shall not be removed," says the LORD, who has compassion on you.
23Is 54:11 "O afflicted one, storm-tossed and not comforted, behold, I will set your stones in antimony, and lay your foundations with sapphires.
23Is 54:12 I will make your pinnacles of agate, your gates of carbuncles, and all your wall of precious stones.
23Is 54:13 All your children shall be taught by the LORD, and great shall be the peace of your children.
23Is 54:14 In righteousness you shall be established; you shall be far from oppression, for you shall not fear; and from terror, for it shall not come near you.
23Is 54:15 If anyone stirs up strife, it is not from me; whoever stirs up strife with you shall fall because of you.
23Is 54:16 Behold, I have created the smith who blows the fire of coals and produces a weapon for its purpose. I have also created the ravager to destroy;
23Is 54:17 no weapon that is fashioned against you shall succeed, and you shall confute every tongue that rises against you in judgment. This is the heritage of the servants of the LORD and their vindication from me, declares the LORD."
23Is 55:1 "Come, everyone who thirsts, come to the waters; and he who has no money, come, buy and eat! Come, buy wine and milk without money and without price.
23Is 55:2 Why do you spend your money for that which is not bread, and your labor for that which does not satisfy? Listen diligently to me, and eat what is good, and delight yourselves in rich food.
23Is 55:3 Incline your ear, and come to me; hear, that your soul may live; and I will make with you an everlasting covenant, my steadfast, sure love for David.
23Is 55:4 Behold, I made him a witness to the peoples, a leader and commander for the peoples.
23Is 55:5 Behold, you shall call a nation that you do not know, and a nation that did not know you shall run to you, because of the LORD your God, and of the Holy One of Israel, for he has glorified you.
23Is 55:6 "Seek the LORD while he may be found; call upon him while he is near;
23Is 55:7 let the wicked forsake his way, and the unrighteous man his thoughts; let him return to the LORD, that he may have compassion on him, and to our God, for he will abundantly pardon.
23Is 55:8 For my thoughts are not your thoughts, neither are your ways my ways, declares the LORD.
23Is 55:9 For as the heavens are higher than the earth, so are my ways higher than your ways and my thoughts than your thoughts.
23Is 55:10 "For as the rain and the snow come down from heaven and do not return there but water the earth, making it bring forth and sprout, giving seed to the sower and bread to the eater,
23Is 55:11 so shall my word be that goes out from my mouth; it shall not return to me empty, but it shall accomplish that which I purpose, and shall succeed in the thing for which I sent it.
23Is 55:12 "For you shall go out in joy and be led forth in peace; the mountains and the hills before you shall break forth into singing, and all the trees of the field shall clap their hands.
23Is 55:13 Instead of the thorn shall come up the cypress; instead of the brier shall come up the myrtle; and it shall make a name for the LORD, an everlasting sign that shall not be cut off."
23Is 56:1 Thus says the LORD: "Keep justice, and do righteousness, for soon my salvation will come, and my deliverance be revealed.
23Is 56:2 Blessed is the man who does this, and the son of man who holds it fast, who keeps the Sabbath, not profaning it, and keeps his hand from doing any evil."
23Is 56:3 Let not the foreigner who has joined himself to the LORD say, "The LORD will surely separate me from his people"; and let not the eunuch say, "Behold, I am a dry tree."
23Is 56:4 For thus says the LORD: "To the eunuchs who keep my Sabbaths, who choose the things that please me and hold fast my covenant,
23Is 56:5 I will give in my house and within my walls a monument and a name better than sons and daughters; I will give them an everlasting name that shall not be cut off.
23Is 56:6 "And the foreigners who join themselves to the LORD, to minister to him, to love the name of the LORD, and to be his servants, everyone who keeps the Sabbath and does not profane it, and holds fast my covenant--
23Is 56:7 these I will bring to my holy mountain, and make them joyful in my house of prayer; their burnt offerings and their sacrifices will be accepted on my altar; for my house shall be called a house of prayer for all peoples."
23Is 56:8 The Lord GOD, who gathers the outcasts of Israel, declares, "I will gather yet others to him besides those already gathered."
23Is 56:9 All you beasts of the field, come to devour-- all you beasts in the forest.
23Is 56:10 His watchmen are blind; they are all without knowledge; they are all silent dogs; they cannot bark, dreaming, lying down, loving to slumber.
23Is 56:11 The dogs have a mighty appetite; they never have enough. But they are shepherds who have no understanding; they have all turned to their own way, each to his own gain, one and all.
23Is 56:12 "Come," they say, "let me get wine; let us fill ourselves with strong drink; and tomorrow will be like this day, great beyond measure."
23Is 57:1 The righteous man perishes, and no one lays it to heart; devout men are taken away, while no one understands. For the righteous man is taken away from calamity;
23Is 57:2 he enters into peace; they rest in their beds who walk in their uprightness.
23Is 57:3 But you, draw near, sons of the sorceress, offspring of the adulterer and the loose woman.
23Is 57:4 Whom are you mocking? Against whom do you open your mouth wide and stick out your tongue? Are you not children of transgression, the offspring of deceit,
23Is 57:5 you who burn with lust among the oaks, under every green tree, who slaughter your children in the valleys, under the clefts of the rocks?
23Is 57:6 Among the smooth stones of the valley is your portion; they, they, are your lot; to them you have poured out a drink offering, you have brought a grain offering. Shall I relent for these things?
23Is 57:7 On a high and lofty mountain you have set your bed, and there you went up to offer sacrifice.
23Is 57:8 Behind the door and the doorpost you have set up your memorial; for, deserting me, you have uncovered your bed, you have gone up to it, you have made it wide; and you have made a covenant for yourself with them, you have loved their bed, you have looked on nakedness.
23Is 57:9 You journeyed to the king with oil and multiplied your perfumes; you sent your envoys far off, and sent down even to Sheol.
23Is 57:10 You were wearied with the length of your way, but you did not say, "It is hopeless"; you found new life for your strength, and so you were not faint.
23Is 57:11 Whom did you dread and fear, so that you lied, and did not remember me, did not lay it to heart? Have I not held my peace, even for a long time, and you do not fear me?
23Is 57:12 I will declare your righteousness and your deeds, but they will not profit you.
23Is 57:13 When you cry out, let your collection of idols deliver you! The wind will carry them off, a breath will take them away. But he who takes refuge in me shall possess the land and shall inherit my holy mountain.
23Is 57:14 And it shall be said, "Build up, build up, prepare the way, remove every obstruction from my people's way."
23Is 57:15 For thus says the One who is high and lifted up, who inhabits eternity, whose name is Holy: "I dwell in the high and holy place, and also with him who is of a contrite and lowly spirit, to revive the spirit of the lowly, and to revive the heart of the contrite.
23Is 57:16 For I will not contend forever, nor will I always be angry; for the spirit would grow faint before me, and the breath of life that I made.
23Is 57:17 Because of the iniquity of his unjust gain I was angry, I struck him; I hid my face and was angry, but he went on backsliding in the way of his own heart.
23Is 57:18 I have seen his ways, but I will heal him; I will lead him and restore comfort to him and his mourners,
23Is 57:19 creating the fruit of the lips. Peace, peace, to the far and to the near," says the LORD, "and I will heal him.
23Is 57:20 But the wicked are like the tossing sea; for it cannot be quiet, and its waters toss up mire and dirt.
23Is 57:21 There is no peace," says my God, "for the wicked."
23Is 58:1 "Cry aloud; do not hold back; lift up your voice like a trumpet; declare to my people their transgression, to the house of Jacob their sins.
23Is 58:2 Yet they seek me daily and delight to know my ways, as if they were a nation that did righteousness and did not forsake the judgment of their God; they ask of me righteous judgments; they delight to draw near to God.
23Is 58:3 'Why have we fasted, and you see it not? Why have we humbled ourselves, and you take no knowledge of it?' Behold, in the day of your fast you seek your own pleasure, and oppress all your workers.
23Is 58:4 Behold, you fast only to quarrel and to fight and to hit with a wicked fist. Fasting like yours this day will not make your voice to be heard on high.
23Is 58:5 Is such the fast that I choose, a day for a person to humble himself? Is it to bow down his head like a reed, and to spread sackcloth and ashes under him? Will you call this a fast, and a day acceptable to the LORD?
23Is 58:6 "Is not this the fast that I choose: to loose the bonds of wickedness, to undo the straps of the yoke, to let the oppressed go free, and to break every yoke?
23Is 58:7 Is it not to share your bread with the hungry and bring the homeless poor into your house; when you see the naked, to cover him, and not to hide yourself from your own flesh?
23Is 58:8 Then shall your light break forth like the dawn, and your healing shall spring up speedily; your righteousness shall go before you; the glory of the LORD shall be your rear guard.
23Is 58:9 Then you shall call, and the LORD will answer; you shall cry, and he will say, 'Here I am.' If you take away the yoke from your midst, the pointing of the finger, and speaking wickedness,
23Is 58:10 if you pour yourself out for the hungry and satisfy the desire of the afflicted, then shall your light rise in the darkness and your gloom be as the noonday.
23Is 58:11 And the LORD will guide you continually and satisfy your desire in scorched places and make your bones strong; and you shall be like a watered garden, like a spring of water, whose waters do not fail.
23Is 58:12 And your ancient ruins shall be rebuilt; you shall raise up the foundations of many generations; you shall be called the repairer of the breach, the restorer of streets to dwell in.
23Is 58:13 "If you turn back your foot from the Sabbath, from doing your pleasure on my holy day, and call the Sabbath a delight and the holy day of the LORD honorable; if you honor it, not going your own ways, or seeking your own pleasure, or talking idly;
23Is 58:14 then you shall take delight in the LORD, and I will make you ride on the heights of the earth; I will feed you with the heritage of Jacob your father, for the mouth of the LORD has spoken."
23Is 59:1 Behold, the LORD's hand is not shortened, that it cannot save, or his ear dull, that it cannot hear;
23Is 59:2 but your iniquities have made a separation between you and your God, and your sins have hidden his face from you so that he does not hear.
23Is 59:3 For your hands are defiled with blood and your fingers with iniquity; your lips have spoken lies; your tongue mutters wickedness.
23Is 59:4 No one enters suit justly; no one goes to law honestly; they rely on empty pleas, they speak lies, they conceive mischief and give birth to iniquity.
23Is 59:5 They hatch adders' eggs; they weave the spider's web; he who eats their eggs dies, and from one that is crushed a viper is hatched.
23Is 59:6 Their webs will not serve as clothing; men will not cover themselves with what they make. Their works are works of iniquity, and deeds of violence are in their hands.
23Is 59:7 Their feet run to evil, and they are swift to shed innocent blood; their thoughts are thoughts of iniquity; desolation and destruction are in their highways.
23Is 59:8 The way of peace they do not know, and there is no justice in their paths; they have made their roads crooked; no one who treads on them knows peace.
23Is 59:9 Therefore justice is far from us, and righteousness does not overtake us; we hope for light, and behold, darkness, and for brightness, but we walk in gloom.
23Is 59:10 We grope for the wall like the blind; we grope like those who have no eyes; we stumble at noon as in the twilight, among those in full vigor we are like dead men.
23Is 59:11 We all growl like bears; we moan and moan like doves; we hope for justice, but there is none; for salvation, but it is far from us.
23Is 59:12 For our transgressions are multiplied before you, and our sins testify against us; for our transgressions are with us, and we know our iniquities:
23Is 59:13 transgressing, and denying the LORD, and turning back from following our God, speaking oppression and revolt, conceiving and uttering from the heart lying words.
23Is 59:14 Justice is turned back, and righteousness stands far away; for truth has stumbled in the public squares, and uprightness cannot enter.
23Is 59:15 Truth is lacking, and he who departs from evil makes himself a prey. The LORD saw it, and it displeased him that there was no justice.
23Is 59:16 He saw that there was no man, and wondered that there was no one to intercede; then his own arm brought him salvation, and his righteousness upheld him.
23Is 59:17 He put on righteousness as a breastplate, and a helmet of salvation on his head; he put on garments of vengeance for clothing, and wrapped himself in zeal as a cloak.
23Is 59:18 According to their deeds, so will he repay, wrath to his adversaries, repayment to his enemies; to the coastlands he will render repayment.
23Is 59:19 So they shall fear the name of the LORD from the west, and his glory from the rising of the sun; for he will come like a rushing stream, which the wind of the LORD drives.
23Is 59:20 "And a Redeemer will come to Zion, to those in Jacob who turn from transgression," declares the LORD.
23Is 59:21 "And as for me, this is my covenant with them," says the LORD: "My Spirit that is upon you, and my words that I have put in your mouth, shall not depart out of your mouth, or out of the mouth of your offspring, or out of the mouth of your children's offspring," says the LORD, "from this time forth and forevermore."
23Is 60:1 Arise, shine, for your light has come, and the glory of the LORD has risen upon you.
23Is 60:2 For behold, darkness shall cover the earth, and thick darkness the peoples; but the LORD will arise upon you, and his glory will be seen upon you.
23Is 60:3 And nations shall come to your light, and kings to the brightness of your rising.
23Is 60:4 Lift up your eyes all around, and see; they all gather together, they come to you; your sons shall come from afar, and your daughters shall be carried on the hip.
23Is 60:5 Then you shall see and be radiant; your heart shall thrill and exult, because the abundance of the sea shall be turned to you, the wealth of the nations shall come to you.
23Is 60:6 A multitude of camels shall cover you, the young camels of Midian and Ephah; all those from Sheba shall come. They shall bring gold and frankincense, and shall bring good news, the praises of the LORD.
23Is 60:7 All the flocks of Kedar shall be gathered to you; the rams of Nebaioth shall minister to you; they shall come up with acceptance on my altar, and I will beautify my beautiful house.
23Is 60:8 Who are these that fly like a cloud, and like doves to their windows?
23Is 60:9 For the coastlands shall hope for me, the ships of Tarshish first, to bring your children from afar, their silver and gold with them, for the name of the LORD your God, and for the Holy One of Israel, because he has made you beautiful.
23Is 60:10 Foreigners shall build up your walls, and their kings shall minister to you; for in my wrath I struck you, but in my favor I have had mercy on you.
23Is 60:11 Your gates shall be open continually; day and night they shall not be shut, that people may bring to you the wealth of the nations, with their kings led in procession.
23Is 60:12 For the nation and kingdom that will not serve you shall perish; those nations shall be utterly laid waste.
23Is 60:13 The glory of Lebanon shall come to you, the cypress, the plane, and the pine, to beautify the place of my sanctuary, and I will make the place of my feet glorious.
23Is 60:14 The sons of those who afflicted you shall come bending low to you, and all who despised you shall bow down at your feet; they shall call you the City of the LORD, the Zion of the Holy One of Israel.
23Is 60:15 Whereas you have been forsaken and hated, with no one passing through, I will make you majestic forever, a joy from age to age.
23Is 60:16 You shall suck the milk of nations; you shall nurse at the breast of kings; and you shall know that I, the LORD, am your Savior and your Redeemer, the Mighty One of Jacob.
23Is 60:17 Instead of bronze I will bring gold, and instead of iron I will bring silver; instead of wood, bronze, instead of stones, iron. I will make your overseers peace and your taskmasters righteousness.
23Is 60:18 Violence shall no more be heard in your land, devastation or destruction within your borders; you shall call your walls Salvation, and your gates Praise.
23Is 60:19 The sun shall be no more your light by day, nor for brightness shall the moon give you light; but the LORD will be your everlasting light, and your God will be your glory.
23Is 60:20 Your sun shall no more go down, nor your moon withdraw itself; for the LORD will be your everlasting light, and your days of mourning shall be ended.
23Is 60:21 Your people shall all be righteous; they shall possess the land forever, the branch of my planting, the work of my hands, that I might be glorified.
23Is 60:22 The least one shall become a clan, and the smallest one a mighty nation; I am the LORD; in its time I will hasten it.
23Is 61:1 The Spirit of the Lord GOD is upon me, because the LORD has anointed me to bring good news to the poor; he has sent me to bind up the brokenhearted, to proclaim liberty to the captives, and the opening of the prison to those who are bound;
23Is 61:2 to proclaim the year of the LORD's favor, and the day of vengeance of our God; to comfort all who mourn;
23Is 61:3 to grant to those who mourn in Zion-- to give them a beautiful headdress instead of ashes, the oil of gladness instead of mourning, the garment of praise instead of a faint spirit; that they may be called oaks of righteousness, the planting of the LORD, that he may be glorified.
23Is 61:4 They shall build up the ancient ruins; they shall raise up the former devastations; they shall repair the ruined cities, the devastations of many generations.
23Is 61:5 Strangers shall stand and tend your flocks; foreigners shall be your plowmen and vinedressers;
23Is 61:6 but you shall be called the priests of the LORD; they shall speak of you as the ministers of our God; you shall eat the wealth of the nations, and in their glory you shall boast.
23Is 61:7 Instead of your shame there shall be a double portion; instead of dishonor they shall rejoice in their lot; therefore in their land they shall possess a double portion; they shall have everlasting joy.
23Is 61:8 For I the LORD love justice; I hate robbery and wrong; I will faithfully give them their recompense, and I will make an everlasting covenant with them.
23Is 61:9 Their offspring shall be known among the nations, and their descendants in the midst of the peoples; all who see them shall acknowledge them, that they are an offspring the LORD has blessed.
23Is 61:10 I will greatly rejoice in the LORD; my soul shall exult in my God, for he has clothed me with the garments of salvation; he has covered me with the robe of righteousness, as a bridegroom decks himself like a priest with a beautiful headdress, and as a bride adorns herself with her jewels.
23Is 61:11 For as the earth brings forth its sprouts, and as a garden causes what is sown in it to sprout up, so the Lord GOD will cause righteousness and praise to sprout up before all the nations.
23Is 62:1 For Zion's sake I will not keep silent, and for Jerusalem's sake I will not be quiet, until her righteousness goes forth as brightness, and her salvation as a burning torch.
23Is 62:2 The nations shall see your righteousness, and all the kings your glory, and you shall be called by a new name that the mouth of the LORD will give.
23Is 62:3 You shall be a crown of beauty in the hand of the LORD, and a royal diadem in the hand of your God.
23Is 62:4 You shall no more be termed Forsaken, and your land shall no more be termed Desolate, but you shall be called My Delight Is in Her, and your land Married; for the LORD delights in you, and your land shall be married.
23Is 62:5 For as a young man marries a young woman, so shall your sons marry you, and as the bridegroom rejoices over the bride, so shall your God rejoice over you.
23Is 62:6 On your walls, O Jerusalem, I have set watchmen; all the day and all the night they shall never be silent. You who put the LORD in remembrance, take no rest,
23Is 62:7 and give him no rest until he establishes Jerusalem and makes it a praise in the earth.
23Is 62:8 The LORD has sworn by his right hand and by his mighty arm: "I will not again give your grain to be food for your enemies, and foreigners shall not drink your wine for which you have labored;
23Is 62:9 but those who garner it shall eat it and praise the LORD, and those who gather it shall drink it in the courts of my sanctuary."
23Is 62:10 Go through, go through the gates; prepare the way for the people; build up, build up the highway; clear it of stones; lift up a signal over the peoples.
23Is 62:11 Behold, the LORD has proclaimed to the end of the earth: Say to the daughter of Zion, "Behold, your salvation comes; behold, his reward is with him, and his recompense before him."
23Is 62:12 And they shall be called The Holy People, The Redeemed of the LORD; and you shall be called Sought Out, A City Not Forsaken.
23Is 63:1 Who is this who comes from Edom, in crimsoned garments from Bozrah, he who is splendid in his apparel, marching in the greatness of his strength? "It is I, speaking in righteousness, mighty to save."
23Is 63:2 Why is your apparel red, and your garments like his who treads in the winepress?
23Is 63:3 "I have trodden the winepress alone, and from the peoples no one was with me; I trod them in my anger and trampled them in my wrath; their lifeblood spattered on my garments, and stained all my apparel.
23Is 63:4 For the day of vengeance was in my heart, and my year of redemption had come.
23Is 63:5 I looked, but there was no one to help; I was appalled, but there was no one to uphold; so my own arm brought me salvation, and my wrath upheld me.
23Is 63:6 I trampled down the peoples in my anger; I made them drunk in my wrath, and I poured out their lifeblood on the earth."
23Is 63:7 I will recount the steadfast love of the LORD, the praises of the LORD, according to all that the LORD has granted us, and the great goodness to the house of Israel that he has granted them according to his compassion, according to the abundance of his steadfast love.
23Is 63:8 For he said, "Surely they are my people, children who will not deal falsely." And he became their Savior.
23Is 63:9 In all their affliction he was afflicted, and the angel of his presence saved them; in his love and in his pity he redeemed them; he lifted them up and carried them all the days of old.
23Is 63:10 But they rebelled and grieved his Holy Spirit; therefore he turned to be their enemy, and himself fought against them.
23Is 63:11 Then he remembered the days of old, of Moses and his people. Where is he who brought them up out of the sea with the shepherds of his flock? Where is he who put in the midst of them his Holy Spirit,
23Is 63:12 who caused his glorious arm to go at the right hand of Moses, who divided the waters before them to make for himself an everlasting name,
23Is 63:13 who led them through the depths? Like a horse in the desert, they did not stumble.
23Is 63:14 Like livestock that go down into the valley, the Spirit of the LORD gave them rest. So you led your people, to make for yourself a glorious name.
23Is 63:15 Look down from heaven and see, from your holy and beautiful habitation. Where are your zeal and your might? The stirring of your inner parts and your compassion are held back from me.
23Is 63:16 For you are our Father, though Abraham does not know us, and Israel does not acknowledge us; you, O LORD, are our Father, our Redeemer from of old is your name.
23Is 63:17 O LORD, why do you make us wander from your ways and harden our heart, so that we fear you not? Return for the sake of your servants, the tribes of your heritage.
23Is 63:18 Your holy people held possession for a little while; our adversaries have trampled down your sanctuary.
23Is 63:19 We have become like those over whom you have never ruled, like those who are not called by your name.
23Is 64:1 Oh that you would rend the heavens and come down, that the mountains might quake at your presence--
23Is 64:2  as when fire kindles brushwood and the fire causes water to boil-- to make your name known to your adversaries, and that the nations might tremble at your presence!
23Is 64:3 When you did awesome things that we did not look for, you came down, the mountains quaked at your presence.
23Is 64:4 From of old no one has heard or perceived by the ear, no eye has seen a God besides you, who acts for those who wait for him.
23Is 64:5 You meet him who joyfully works righteousness, those who remember you in your ways. Behold, you were angry, and we sinned; in our sins we have been a long time, and shall we be saved?
23Is 64:6 We have all become like one who is unclean, and all our righteous deeds are like a polluted garment. We all fade like a leaf, and our iniquities, like the wind, take us away.
23Is 64:7 There is no one who calls upon your name, who rouses himself to take hold of you; for you have hidden your face from us, and have made us melt in the hand of our iniquities.
23Is 64:8 But now, O LORD, you are our Father; we are the clay, and you are our potter; we are all the work of your hand.
23Is 64:9 Be not so terribly angry, O LORD, and remember not iniquity forever. Behold, please look, we are all your people.
23Is 64:10 Your holy cities have become a wilderness; Zion has become a wilderness, Jerusalem a desolation.
23Is 64:11 Our holy and beautiful house, where our fathers praised you, has been burned by fire, and all our pleasant places have become ruins.
23Is 64:12 Will you restrain yourself at these things, O LORD? Will you keep silent, and afflict us so terribly?
23Is 65:1 I was ready to be sought by those who did not ask for me; I was ready to be found by those who did not seek me. I said, "Here am I, here am I," to a nation that was not called by my name.
23Is 65:2 I spread out my hands all the day to a rebellious people, who walk in a way that is not good, following their own devices;
23Is 65:3 a people who provoke me to my face continually, sacrificing in gardens and making offerings on bricks;
23Is 65:4 who sit in tombs, and spend the night in secret places; who eat pig's flesh, and broth of tainted meat is in their vessels;
23Is 65:5 who say, "Keep to yourself, do not come near me, for I am too holy for you." These are a smoke in my nostrils, a fire that burns all the day.
23Is 65:6 Behold, it is written before me: "I will not keep silent, but I will repay; I will indeed repay into their bosom
23Is 65:7 both your iniquities and your fathers' iniquities together, says the LORD; because they made offerings on the mountains and insulted me on the hills, I will measure into their bosom payment for their former deeds."
23Is 65:8 Thus says the LORD: "As the new wine is found in the cluster, and they say, 'Do not destroy it, for there is a blessing in it,' so I will do for my servants' sake, and not destroy them all.
23Is 65:9 I will bring forth offspring from Jacob, and from Judah possessors of my mountains; my chosen shall possess it, and my servants shall dwell there.
23Is 65:10 Sharon shall become a pasture for flocks, and the Valley of Achor a place for herds to lie down, for my people who have sought me.
23Is 65:11 But you who forsake the LORD, who forget my holy mountain, who set a table for Fortune and fill cups of mixed wine for Destiny,
23Is 65:12 I will destine you to the sword, and all of you shall bow down to the slaughter, because, when I called, you did not answer; when I spoke, you did not listen, but you did what was evil in my eyes and chose what I did not delight in."
23Is 65:13 Therefore thus says the Lord GOD: "Behold, my servants shall eat, but you shall be hungry; behold, my servants shall drink, but you shall be thirsty; behold, my servants shall rejoice, but you shall be put to shame;
23Is 65:14 behold, my servants shall sing for gladness of heart, but you shall cry out for pain of heart and shall wail for breaking of spirit.
23Is 65:15 You shall leave your name to my chosen for a curse, and the Lord GOD will put you to death, but his servants he will call by another name.
23Is 65:16 So that he who blesses himself in the land shall bless himself by the God of truth, and he who takes an oath in the land shall swear by the God of truth; because the former troubles are forgotten and are hidden from my eyes.
23Is 65:17 "For behold, I create new heavens and a new earth, and the former things shall not be remembered or come into mind.
23Is 65:18 But be glad and rejoice forever in that which I create; for behold, I create Jerusalem to be a joy, and her people to be a gladness.
23Is 65:19 I will rejoice in Jerusalem and be glad in my people; no more shall be heard in it the sound of weeping and the cry of distress.
23Is 65:20 No more shall there be in it an infant who lives but a few days, or an old man who does not fill out his days, for the young man shall die a hundred years old, and the sinner a hundred years old shall be accursed.
23Is 65:21 They shall build houses and inhabit them; they shall plant vineyards and eat their fruit.
23Is 65:22 They shall not build and another inhabit; they shall not plant and another eat; for like the days of a tree shall the days of my people be, and my chosen shall long enjoy the work of their hands.
23Is 65:23 They shall not labor in vain or bear children for calamity, for they shall be the offspring of the blessed of the LORD, and their descendants with them.
23Is 65:24 Before they call I will answer; while they are yet speaking I will hear.
23Is 65:25 The wolf and the lamb shall graze together; the lion shall eat straw like the ox, and dust shall be the serpent's food. They shall not hurt or destroy in all my holy mountain," says the LORD.
23Is 66:1 Thus says the LORD: "Heaven is my throne, and the earth is my footstool; what is the house that you would build for me, and what is the place of my rest?
23Is 66:2 All these things my hand has made, and so all these things came to be, declares the LORD. But this is the one to whom I will look: he who is humble and contrite in spirit and trembles at my word.
23Is 66:3 "He who slaughters an ox is like one who kills a man; he who sacrifices a lamb, like one who breaks a dog's neck; he who presents a grain offering, like one who offers pig's blood; he who makes a memorial offering of frankincense, like one who blesses an idol. These have chosen their own ways, and their soul delights in their abominations;
23Is 66:4 I also will choose harsh treatment for them and bring their fears upon them, because when I called, no one answered, when I spoke, they did not listen; but they did what was evil in my eyes and chose that in which I did not delight."
23Is 66:5 Hear the word of the LORD, you who tremble at his word: "Your brothers who hate you and cast you out for my name's sake have said, 'Let the LORD be glorified, that we may see your joy'; but it is they who shall be put to shame.
23Is 66:6 "The sound of an uproar from the city! A sound from the temple! The sound of the LORD, rendering recompense to his enemies!
23Is 66:7 "Before she was in labor she gave birth; before her pain came upon her she delivered a son.
23Is 66:8 Who has heard such a thing? Who has seen such things? Shall a land be born in one day? Shall a nation be brought forth in one moment? For as soon as Zion was in labor she brought forth her children.
23Is 66:9 Shall I bring to the point of birth and not cause to bring forth?" says the LORD; "shall I, who cause to bring forth, shut the womb?" says your God.
23Is 66:10 "Rejoice with Jerusalem, and be glad for her, all you who love her; rejoice with her in joy, all you who mourn over her;
23Is 66:11 that you may nurse and be satisfied from her consoling breast; that you may drink deeply with delight from her glorious abundance."
23Is 66:12 For thus says the LORD: "Behold, I will extend peace to her like a river, and the glory of the nations like an overflowing stream; and you shall nurse, you shall be carried upon her hip, and bounced upon her knees.
23Is 66:13 As one whom his mother comforts, so I will comfort you; you shall be comforted in Jerusalem.
23Is 66:14 You shall see, and your heart shall rejoice; your bones shall flourish like the grass; and the hand of the LORD shall be known to his servants, and he shall show his indignation against his enemies.
23Is 66:15 "For behold, the LORD will come in fire, and his chariots like the whirlwind, to render his anger in fury, and his rebuke with flames of fire.
23Is 66:16 For by fire will the LORD enter into judgment, and by his sword, with all flesh; and those slain by the LORD shall be many.
23Is 66:17 "Those who sanctify and purify themselves to go into the gardens, following one in the midst, eating pig's flesh and the abomination and mice, shall come to an end together, declares the LORD.
23Is 66:18 "For I know their works and their thoughts, and the time is coming to gather all nations and tongues. And they shall come and shall see my glory,
23Is 66:19 and I will set a sign among them. And from them I will send survivors to the nations, to Tarshish, Pul, and Lud, who draw the bow, to Tubal and Javan, to the coastlands far away, that have not heard my fame or seen my glory. And they shall declare my glory among the nations.
23Is 66:20 And they shall bring all your brothers from all the nations as an offering to the LORD, on horses and in chariots and in litters and on mules and on dromedaries, to my holy mountain Jerusalem, says the LORD, just as the Israelites bring their grain offering in a clean vessel to the house of the LORD.
23Is 66:21 And some of them also I will take for priests and for Levites, says the LORD.
23Is 66:22 "For as the new heavens and the new earth that I make shall remain before me, says the LORD, so shall your offspring and your name remain.
23Is 66:23 From new moon to new moon, and from Sabbath to Sabbath, all flesh shall come to worship before me, declares the LORD.
23Is 66:24 "And they shall go out and look on the dead bodies of the men who have rebelled against me. For their worm shall not die, their fire shall not be quenched, and they shall be an abhorrence to all flesh."
